<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Meese-Poll     07-05 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Poll,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll: 33 Percent Say Meese Should Have Resigned Sooner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Meese Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-three percent of the people surveyed
Tuesday following Attorney General Edwin Meese III's announcement
that he has submitted his resignation said Meese should have quit
sooner, a poll found.
   The poll, conducted for USA Today and Cable News Network, found
that 22 percent supported Meese's decision and 25 percent said he
should have opted to stay at the Justice Department. Twenty percent
said they didn't know.
   The telephone survey of 646 people was conducted by Gordon S.
Black Corp. and had a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage
points.
   Meese announced he will resign later this month or in early
August. His announcement came after an independent prosecutor's
14-month probe into his official conduct ended without indictment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
