<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IranianProtest     07-05 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iranian Protest,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians Demonstrate Against Downing of Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A protest against the U.S. downing of a
civilian airliner in the Persian Gulf turned violent when 10
demonstrators from the mostly Iranian crowd attacked an
anti-Khomeini television commentator.
   Rafi Khachatour of Channel 18, a local station featuring ethnic
programs, suffered cuts and bruises to the face Monday from
protesters wielding placards and a cane taken from an elderly
woman, police and witnesses said.
   ``They were all over him. It was terrible,'' said a woman who
identified herself only as Khachatour's friend.
   Police arrested two men in front of the Federal Building in West
Los Angeles after the attack on Khachatour, widely known in the
Iranian community for his strong views against Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini's government.
   Police booked Ali Sinaki, 34, and Seyeo Hashemi, 35, both of Los
Angeles, for investigation of assault with a deadly weapon in the
attack on Khachatour, said Sgt. Rick Walker.
   Demonstrators left shortly after the beating as about a dozen
police cars arrived. Protest organizers took no responsibility for
the beating and many denied knowing about it.
   Khachatour was listed in stable condition at UCLA Medical
Center, said a nursing supervisor who declined to give her name.
   The protesters, most Iranian nationals, marched and chanted in
English and Farsi in front of the Federal Building, located near
the University of California at Los Angeles and a popular spot for
anti-government demonstrations.
   Demonstrators chanted, ``U.S. Out of Persian Gulf,'' and carried
signs reading, ``We Condemn The U.S. Massacre of Civilian
Passengers,'' ``Iraqi Invasion, U.S. Aggression,'' and ``U.S. Out
of Muslim Land.''
   About half the women protesters wore chadors, the traditional
veiled body-length black gown worn in their homeland.
   ``Why were you there to begin with to get scared by that
jetliner?'' asked protester Soheil Mohases of Garden Grove. ``I
don't think the U.S. should even be there.''
   Motorists expressed disapproval by shouting obscenities and
gesturing at the protesters. At least two arguments nearly
developed into fistfights between protesters and angry passers-by.
   According to the Defense Department, the guided missile cruiser
USS Vincennes mistook the Iran Air Airbus for an Iranian F-14
fighter and the plane did not respond to radio warnings. The plane
was brought down Sunday by one of two missiles fired from the
Vincennes. All 290 aboard are believed to have died.
   ``It's a pack of lies,'' said Loraine Mirza of Los Angeles. ``I
think they will be shooting anything in sight. I think it was a
deliberate act.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
