<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 0057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-PrivateLife Bjt   07-05 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Private Life, Bjt,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis' Home Life: Tomato-Growing, Cooking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When questions of character came up last
year with revelations about then-Democratic presidential candidates
Gary Hart and Joseph Biden, the joke around the Massachusetts
statehouse was that Gov. Michael Dukakis planned a major
disclosure: he once bought a suit retail.
   ``Nope. Nope. Not true,'' replied Dukakis, sometimes known to be
tightfisted, when an aide told him of the joke. ``I've bought them
upstairs (not in the discount basement), but always on sale.''
   The incident provided one of the few glimpses that anyone gets
into Dukakis' life away from politics. The Democratic nominee-to-be
prefers to keep details of his home life private, and his campaign
office is hard-pressed to provide any material on the subject.
   The office has a mountain of clippings on Dukakis as governor;
it doesn't keep a file on the 54-year-old husband and father.
   There are a few details that are common knowledge, however.
Dukakis enjoys growing tomatoes in the front yard of his house and
every year plants a rose bush for his mother, Euterpe. He likes to
prepare Sunday breakfast and usually washes the dishes. And he
loathes large parties.
   ``Mike likes small groups. He's in so many big ones at work,''
said Richard Giesser, a longtime Dukakis friend and political ally.
``He enjoys the family. He likes to putter. He likes to grow
things. It's fun just to stand and chat with him while he prunes
the bushes.''
   Dukakis, whose net worth is at least $500,000, lives in a duplex
he bought less than 20 years ago for $25,000, drives a 5-year-old
Dodge and generally vacations at the homes of friends or family.
   On one vacation, Dukakis took along a book on Swedish land-use
planning.
   A non-smoker and a drinker of white wine only on rare occasions,
Dukakis is more likely to take a walk to the ice cream store than
attend a Brookline bash, according to Giesser.
   The presidential candidate is also not much of a television
watcher or moviegoer, although when his son John appeared on
several episodes of the television series ``Family Ties,'' Dukakis
and his wife, Kitty, tuned in.
   In his younger days, Dukakis was a regular jogger, but recently
he has taken up ``power walking'' with hand weights, a routine he
keeps up faithfully on the campaign trail. He also has played the
trumpet a few times on the trail, to the delight of photographers
covering the candidate.
   Ira Jackson, a former Dukakis cabinet member and family friend
for 25 years, said the candidate's jogging, tomato-growing, cooking
and cleaning indicates a man ahead of his time.
   ``He was jogging way before it was fashionable. He was gardening
long before it became a yuppie pursuit. He moved closer to the city
at a time when others were moving away. He's always cooked
breakfast and done the dishes long before women's liberation
dictated that husbands should do this,'' Jackson said.
   Family is a key concern for Dukakis, who put off Secret Service
protection for months to avoid possible disruptions.
   ``He's got a world within his family that he's largely shielded
from the public. That reveals part of Michael Dukakis that I find
encouraging,'' Jackson said.
   Before his son John (by Kitty's previous marriage) and his
daughters, Kara and Andrea, went off to college, Dukakis would be
home for dinner regularly. He would frequently return to work
afterward, but was faithful about attending dinner and he expected
the rest of the family to be there.
   John Dukakis called the dinners at home ``a compressed hour'' of
political discussion and debate.
   If Dukakis wins the presidency there will be no ``first family''
in the White House _ just Dukakis and Kitty. Andrea is interested
in publishing, and Kara has three years of college to complete at
Brown University.
   John has taken an intense interest in politics, running Dukakis'
southern campaign and is political director in California.
   ``My father always thought that I would eventually return to
politics,'' said John, who was pursuing an acting career when he
went to work for Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass. He says he is mulling a
run for political office in Brookline.
   The story of Dukakis' private life has its unhappy moments.
Dukakis' brother Stelian attempted suicide in 1951 and was killed
by a hit-and-run driver in 1973 as he rode his bicycle through
Brookline. The two brothers' relationship was sometimes stormy.
   Kitty was addicted to diet pills for 26 years, a habit she
kicked and acknowledged publicly last year as Dukakis' presidential
campaign got under way.
   The campaign has forced the couple to make some emotional
adjustments, according to Kitty.
   ``We were very lonely during the first six months of the
campaign. We were often 40 miles away in different hotels.''
   Now, she said, they are just happy to get some private time.
   ``We don't go to restaurants anymore. We don't go to movies even
if we have the time. ... We had some time at Cape Cod recently. ...
We did a lot of walking and just being together.''
</TEXT>
