<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SovietInspections 1stLd-Writethru a0686 07-05 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Inspections, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0686,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Complete On-site Inspections under INF Treaty</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 9th graf `In Pueblo' and 17th graf `An Air' to add
numbers of Soviets. Adds final graf with number leaving Tuesday.</NOTE>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Soviet inspectors prepared to head home after completing their
looks Monday at defense sites in the United States under the new
nuclear arms treaty.
   The head of a Soviet team that inspected a defense plant in San
Diego hailed the cooperative effort as unprecedented, and
congratulated Americans celebrating the anniversary of their
country's independence.
   The Soviets sent teams to make ``baseline inspections'' at five
missile storage sites in four states over the Fourth of July
weekend. While Soviet inspectors were in California, Colorado, Utah
and Arizona, American teams visited Soviet missile facilities in
Warsaw Pact nations for the On-Site Inpections Agency under the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty.
   The inspections are designed to verify the exact number of
missiles and related components to be destroyed within the next
three years.
   Vyacheslav Kharlamov led a 10-member Soviet team that completed
a grueling 24-hour inspection Monday of San Diego's General
Dynamics plant, which until last December made cruise missile
launchers.
   ``Together with representatives of the OSIA and with cooperation
of representatives of the plant, the first unprecedented action was
fulfilled in verification of the compliance with the obligation
under the treaty between the U.S.S.R and the U.S,'' Kharlamov said
through an interpreter. ``We will take note of the U.S. authorities
to ensure the fulfillment of the inspection according to the
provisions of the INF treaty.''
   After reviewing their findings with a 10-member group of
Americans that escorted them, the Soviets boarded an Air Force
C-141 transport plane and departed for Travis Air Force Base near
San Francisco.
   ``Today on the national day of your country we go back to San
Francisco and, after a short rest, we will return to Moscow,''
Kharlamov said. ``We like to extend our congratulations on your
national day.''
   In Pueblo, Colo., 10 Soviet inspectors inventoried U.S. Pershing
missiles at an Army depot.
   Depot spokeswoman Mary Wilson said the Soviets were very
friendly, but said she couldn't comment on their observations or
the inspection itself.
   Wilson said the Pueblo site was the only one subject to
unlimited inspection by the Soviets under the pact implemented this
year.
   She said high-technology machines and weapons at the Pueblo
depot remained under wraps, but the Soviet team was entitled to
look under the covers to see if they were hiding missile parts.
   At Dugway Proving Ground, a remote Army installation in the
western Utah desert, 10 Soviet treaty inspectors completed their
visit, wrote reports and changed clothes before departing for
Travis Air Force Base Monday, said spokeswoman Kathy Whittaker.
   Under the treaty, the Soviets could return to San Francisco or
move to another site open to inspection. They were not required to
say what they would do before boarding the departure aircraft.
   ``From our end of it, we were able to provide them with the
opportunity to see what they wanted to and inspect all inspectable
areas on the post,'' Whittaker said.
   Soviet teams departed Monday after concluding inspections of two
Arizona military bases' facilities for ground-launched cruise
missiles.
   An Air Force transport picked up one 10-man team of Soviets at
the Army's Fort Huachuca in Sierra Vista, then picked up another
8-member Soviet team at Davis-Monthan Air Force Base in Tucson.
   Some 70 Soviet inspectors arrived at Travis late Friday before
fanning out to sites eligible for inspections under the treaty.
   A group of 22 inspectors who headed to the Hercules Aerospace
Co. missile plant in Magna, Utah, will be the only permanently
based Soviets, and can stay up to 13 years under the treaty. The
other 48 inspectors were to leave at midday Tuesday.
</TEXT>
