<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 0216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     07-05 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says US Policy in Gulf Shouldn't Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush calls the Navy's
destruction of an Iranian jetliner with 290 people aboard ``an
unhappy incident,'' but says it won't lead to changes in U.S.
policy.
   ``Life goes on,'' Bush said Monday. ``Our mission goes on and
the world keeps turning.''
   Bush said a more thorough study of the tragedy is needed before
deciding if U.S. reparations to families of the deceased will be
offered.
   Speaking with reporters on Air Force II as he returned from July
4th campaign appearances in three Midwestern cities, Bush voiced
concern about possible Iranian retaliation.
   ``I don't know what they'll do,'' he said, but ``we can't be
deterred by threats.''
   Asked whether he was concerned that rising anti-American
sentiment in the area over the incident might further endanger
hostages held in Lebanon, Bush said: ``I worry about the hostages
being held in the first place.''
   ``Those people took revenge on society by taking the hostages in
the first places,'' he said.
   The vice president said he planned to meet today with President
Reagan on the episode. He had no public appearances scheduled.
   At an Independence Day celebration on the banks of the
Mississippi River in St. Louis on Monday, Bush was applauded when
he said that the captain of the Navy warship Vincennes ``did what
he had to do.''
   Later, during an air show as military jets swooped overhead,
Bush told reporters that he felt the people who applauded were
mainly displaying patriotism.
   ``I think people respond to that, they understand that and
they're right, as a matter of fact,'' he said.
   ``It's just an unhappy incident. We expressed our proper
regrets. It appears that the captain acted appropriately. ... We're
not going to change our policy because of this unfortunate
incident.''
   On the issue of possible financial compensation to families of
the dead, Bush said: ``I don't know. Let's look into the whole
thing, understand it more fully, before reaching any conclusions of
that nature.''
   He told a festival crowd in Elmwood Park, Ill., a Chicago
suburb, that ``I probably speak for all when I say we regret the
loss of innocent life in the gulf.''
   ``But as I listen to the description of the chief of naval
operations about what happened there, I can identify with the
dilemma faced by the captain of the USS Vincennes.''
   Bush said the captain did not want to put his crew ``more in
harm's way. He gave seven times warning. And it's regrettable that
life was lost but he was doing what he had to do.''
</TEXT>
