<DOCNO> AP880705-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 0224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-05 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHURCH HILL, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hugh and Ann Alley were looking for
some barnyard pets after they got out of the cattle business when
they stumbled onto something small.
   The couple have five miniature Sicilian donkeys that stand 34
inches tall or less. Any taller than 36 inches, and they wouldn't
be considered miniature. Regular donkeys can grow to 52 inches,
Alley said.
   ``Ours are no more than big dogs,'' Alley said recently.
``Everyone says dogs are man's best friend. A donkey would have to
be second.''
   ``They like to be loved,'' Mrs. Alley said. ``They drink iced
tea. We bring them in the house and they mind real good. They're
jealous if one gets more love than the other one. We've had more
company than we've ever had in our life. People come from all over
to make their picture.''
   ``They just care so much for you. They'll put their head in your
lap like a dog,'' Mrs. Alley said.
   The retired Church Hill couple was looking for a barnyard pet
last year after they got out of the cattle business and leased most
of their 64-acre farm. They decided on a burro and began to look
for one when they contacted a West Virginia woman who breeds the
miniature donkeys.
   The tidbit donkeys are a big hit with the neighbors and make
regular appearances in parades dressed in costumes. The couple also
takes them to nursing homes and schools, including a school for the
blind.
   ``One blind boy just fell in love,'' Alley said. ``He walked
over this donkey with his fingers like he was playing the piano.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year ago, Jay Green vowed that he would not
taste defeat again. Instead, he tasted sweet victory _ and spicy
hot dogs.
   Green swallowed 10 hot dogs and rolls in 12 minutes to defeat 12
other contestants Monday at the Nathan's Famous 72nd annual Hot
Dog-Eating Contest. Last year, the 30-year-old manager of a
limousine service came in second.
   ``In the newspapers, I vowed that I would win this year,'' Green
said.
   He lives in nearby Sheepshead Bay and eats franks at the Coney
Island emporium four times a week. ``I've been eating them since I
was 4. I just totally love them,'' he said.
   This was not a particularly good year for the sport of hot-dog
eating. The record, set in 1979, was 17{. And Green himself ate 13\
hot dogs last year in a losing effort. Was the competition weak
this year?
   ``I guess so,'' the champ said.
</TEXT>
