<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 0227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe-Thumbnails 2Takes   07-05 0923</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Thumbnails, 2 Takes,940-1740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Principals in Pentagon Bribery Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are thumbnail sketches of figures in the
burgeoning probe into allegations that defense contractors and
consultants, many of them former military personnel, bribed
Pentagon officials for contracting details to help win lucrative
military contracts.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CONSULTANTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Melvyn Paisley</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Paisley is described as a major target in the probe, and the
highest-ranking former Pentagon official implicated. He is a former
Boeing Corp. executive who was assistant secretary of the Navy for
research, engineering and systems before leaving the government in
1987 to become a consultant to major defense contractors.
   At the Pentagon, Paisley fought hard for increases in the Navy
budget that would help build the fleet to 600 ships, working
closely with Navy Secretary John Lehman Jr. Paisley supervised
procurement, specializing in acquisition of aircraft and combat
systems. He was known in Navy circles as a tough boss who was
contemptuous of bureaucrats. He was also known as a fun-loving
socializer married to his fourth wife.
   Paisley's consulting office was bugged and phone tapped for much
of the two-year FBI probe. His wife Vicki worked for BDM
International Inc. of McLean, Va. which does extensive business
with the Pentagon and which was subpoenaed in the probe. She now
owns VAMAO Inc., a defense firm founded in 1986 by defense
consultant William M. Galvin.
   A search warrant served on McDonnell Douglas Corp., where
Paisley did consulting work, alleged that when Paisley was in the
Navy he tried to steer a major Navy aircraft program to McDonnell
Douglas, funneled confidential bidding documents to the company and
used his influence to help the company in its competition for a
contract with South Korea for sales of the F-18 fighter.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>William Galvin</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A well-connected defense consultant, Galvin has done work for a
number of the companies whose offices were searched by the FBI,
including Loral Corp., Unisys Corp., Cubic Defense Systems, Norden
Systems and United Technologies Corp. He is a member of the board
of Armtec Inc. of Palatka, Fla., whose offices were searched. He
has a consulting firm named Sapphire Systems.
   Published reports have said Galvin was a conduit to Paisley when
Paisley was in the Pentagon and that Galvin often boasted of his
access to him. He is also said to have entertained Pentagon and
industry figures lavishly.
   His office in the Watergate complex was searched, as was the
office of his stepson, Kenneth F. Brooke. His daughter, Joan
Galvin, was reassigned from her duties as a defense aide to Rep.
Andy Ireland, R-Fla.
   Galvin and his wife Evelyn recently moved to the Watergate from
an exclusive area of McLean, Va. They are described as very active
socially and fond of entertaining.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Charles Gardner</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gardner resigned in March from his job as a Unisys vice
president. He met in May with Rep. Roy Dyson, D-Md., a member of
the House Armed Services Committee. Dyson had visited Unisys' Great
Neck, N.Y. defense facility. Gardner's home in Malverne, N.Y. was
searched.
   Gardner, now a defense consultant, hired Galvin as a consultant
while at Unisys and became a director of Sapphire Systems, one of
Galvin's consulting concerns. His phone was tapped during the
investigation. He was a campaign contributor to both Dyson and Rep.
William Chappell, D-Fla., chairman of the defense appropriations
subcommittee.
   At Unisys, Gardner directed the surveillance and fire control
division of the company's Shipboard and Ground Systems Group. He
was responsible for Unisys' contract for the Aegis radar system.
Unisys won bidding to be a second source for the Aegis system after
Paisley revised the bidding rules in a way that favored Unisys.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>William Parkin</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   An Alexandria, Va., defense consultant, Parkin worked in the
Navy's Joint Cruise Missile Project office from 1977 to 1983, first
as chief of the program's contracting division and later as deputy
for acquisition. He went to work for Galvin after he left the Navy,
doing some part-time consulting for Sapphire Systems. He now runs
his own business.
   Among Parkin's clients is Hazeltine Corp., one of the companies
searched, which was trying to win a Navy contract involving an
electronic aircraft identification device supervised by Stuart E.
Berlin, a Navy official whose office was searched.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Retired Adm. James A. `Ace' Lyons</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A former commander of the Pacific fleet, Lyons was an apparent
favorite of Lehman and a colleague of Paisley, sources have said.
According to a search warrant, Lyons has worked as a consultant to
McDonnell Douglas since at least last December. Sources say he was
hired to help the company sell jet fighters to South Korea.
   He is not believed to be a target of the investigation. He lives
in the exclusive Washington suburb of McLean, Va.
   Lyons became friends with Lehman while working with President
Reagan's transition committee in 1980. He was promoted rapidly over
the next few years, and is widely thought to have won his fourth
star and the command of the Pacific fleet because of Lehman's
intervention. James H. Webb, Lehman's successor, last year accused
Lehman of favoritism in handling military promotions and cited
Lyons as an example.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Marcus Saunders</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A former contracts specialist with the Naval Electronics Systems
Command, Saunders was fired after pleading guilty in October 1982
to using inside information about a $58 million contract his staff
had negotiated to make about $9,000 in the stock market. He was
also fined $5,000.
   Saunders is a defense contract consultant who works out of his
home in Alexandria, Va., which was searched in June.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
