<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 0228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseProbe-Thumbnails 1stAdd   07-05 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Thumbnails, 1st Add,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: in June.</HEAD>
<HEAD>PENTAGON PERSONNEL</HEAD>
<HEAD>Victor Cohen</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Cohen is deputy assistant Air Force secretary in charge of
buying tactical command, control, communications and computer
systems. His home was searched, his phone tapped and his Pentagon
offices searched and sealed off. He has been relieved of
contracting responsibilities.
   He is a former employee of Northrop Corp. and Grumman Aerospace
Corp. He holds a doctorate from Stevens Institute of Technology in
Hoboken, N.J. and is a specialist in analyzing weapons systems. He
had frequent social and business contacts with Galvin, associates
said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>James Gaines</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gaines is deputy assistant Navy secretary for acquisition and
management. His phone was tapped and his offices searched and
sealed. His job gives him access to Navy purchasing plans. He also
has been relieved of sensitive contracting duties.
   He is a former official of Boeing, where he worked under Paisley.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Jack Sherman</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Sherman is a negotiator with the Marine Corps contracts
division, installation and logistics department. Published reports
have said he was the first Defense Department employee to be
implicated in the inquiry and one of those served with a search
warrant. He has been relieved of procurement duties.
   He is a former Marine who worked as a civilian for the Navy
before transferring to a civilian job in the Marines. According to
The Washington Post, investigators are examining what they believe
is an information network involving Sherman, Navy official George
Stone and two consultants.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   George Stone
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Stone is head of the information management services and
information transfer purchases division of the Navy's Space and
Naval Warfare Systems Command. He replaced Saunders when Saunders
was fired from the Navy.
   Stone's office was searched in June. He also has been reassigned.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Stuart Berlin</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   An executive with the Naval Air Systems Command, he also has
been stripped of contracting duties and reassigned. He has headed
the ship systems engineering branch of the Naval Air Systems
Command since 1986. His office was searched in June.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CONGRESSMEN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have said no member of Congress is a target in the
probe, and no subpoena or search warrant has been issued for the
congressmen or their staffs.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>William Chappell, D-Fla.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   He is chairman of the House Appropriations subcommittee on
defense. A company in his congressional district, Armtec, was
served with a search warrant in the probe and the company's
president, William Roberts, is a longtime friend of Chappell.
   He is known as a shrewd strategist thrust into the key
chairmanship post after the death of Rep. Joseph Addabbo, D-N.Y. He
was a naval aviator and a captain in the Naval Reserve. He is one
of Congress' largest recipients of defense industry political
contributions and speech fees, according to campaign finance
records.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Roy Dyson, D-Md.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dyson met with former Unisys vice president Charles Gardner in
Great Neck, N.Y., to discuss the company's defense contracts. He is
a member of the House Armed Services Committee. Among his campaign
contributors are several whose offices were searched as part of the
probe, including Kenneth Brooke, who is Galvin's stepson; Jeffrey
Zuba, who operates Zubier Enterprises of Harrisburg, Pa., a
consulting firm and contractor.
   His top aide, Tom Pappas, committed suicide in May by jumping
from a hotel room in New York. Dyson, who was also in New York at
the time, went into seclusion for several days. He met the press
the next week to say that he thought Pappas killed himself because
of a Washington Post article questioning his ``unorthodox'' demands
on male staffers. At the news conference, Dyson denied that either
he or Pappas were homosexuals.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>OTHERS</HEAD>
<HEAD>John F. Lehman Jr.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Lehman is a former Navy secretary who had as his goal the
buildup of the fleet to 600 ships. He also revised the Navy's
procurement system. He is not a subject of the probe, officials
said, but a wiretap on others suggested that Lehman may have tipped
off Paisley that the FBI was investigating him. Paisley and Lehman
have known each other for at least a decade and are social friends.
Lehman is now with the Wall Street investment firm Paine Webber Inc.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Caspar W. Weinberger</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The former defense secretary is not under investigation, and
says he did not know of the investigation while he was at the
Pentagon. He was secretary from 1981 to 1987, when the alleged
abuses took place. He has attributed the corruption to a handful of
dishonest individuals inside and outside the Pentagon.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Henry E. Hudson</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. attorney for the Eastern District of Virginia, Hudson
is the chief prosecutor in the case. He is coordinating the
investigation and will try any cases that result. He became known
as an anti-pornography crusader and has the reputation of an
aggressive prosecutor who is not publicity-shy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
