<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-Fourth     07-05 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Fourth,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>July Fourth Quiet In Persian Gulf After U.S. Attack On Iranian
Jetliner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner-World, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fourth of July was even quieter that
usual among Americans in the Persian Gulf this year because of the
U.S. attack on an Iranian jetliner.
   Those who had not gone on vacation to escape the searing heat
observed Independence Day by going to work as usual, except for
embassy staffs, who had the day off.
   The missile cruiser USS Vincennes shot down the Iran Air Airbus
on Sunday after mistaking it for an F-14 fighter and warning it
seven times. Iran said all 290 people aboard were killed.
   All of the approximately 20,000 U.S. citizens in the gulf Arab
states were advised to maintain low profiles, and U.S. embassies
around the world issued warnings to Americans to ``exercise
discretion'' in their activities.
   Americans around the gulf paid special heed because some of the
Arab countries have large populations of Shiite Moslems, the
dominant sect in Iran.
   Navy officials canceled leaves and shore passes for American
servicemen as another precaution against possible terrorist acts
against the sailors.
   U.S. sources say the American population of the gulf has
dwindled in recent years and includes about 15,000 in Saudi Arabia,
1,200 in Bahrain and fewer than 1,000 each in Kuwait, the United
Arab Emirates, Qatar and Oman.
   In addition, about 20,000 American military personnel are in the
region, most aboard ships.
   A few U.S. diplomatic missions, including the fortress-like
embassy in downtown Kuwait, had small July 4th parties for staff
members and a few guests.
   Security concerns have reduced the size of official Independence
Day celebrations. The U.S. Embassy in Bahrain even held one in
February, built around ``Presidents' Day'' marking the birthdays of
George Washington and Abraham Lincoln.
   Officials said the date was chosen because more people were on
hand at that time than in the heat of July.
   At the small U.S. Navy shore facility, hidden away near
Bahrain's main port, just 40 sailors were present for the
ceremonial raising of the Stars and Stripes that occurs only July 4.
   An American officer said many more usually would attend the
flag-raising and an outdoor cookout, but plans to bring about 200
sailors ashore for the day were canceled.
   A bus awaiting a bomb check at the gate carried only about 15
men.
   No American sailors were at their few in-town haunts: hotel
lobbies with international telephone booths, coffee shops, the
Sheraton complex shopping mall and the Arab market district.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880705-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 0315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StairSafety     07-05 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stair Safety,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Pay People to Fall Down Stairs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia Tech researchers have constructed
collapsing stairs and are paying volunteers to tumble down them
wearing crash helmets, neck braces and padded mittens. All in the
name of science.
   ``Stairs are the second most dangerous consumer product _ right
after automobiles _ but the one thing we really don't know is what
happens in the instant of a fall,'' said researcher Deborah Hyde of
Georgia Institute of Technology's School of Architecture.
   Researchers have constructed a pneumatic stairway that can
collapse in any of five different ways to prompt a scientific
pratfall. Volunteers are paid $15 dollars for falling on that
air-cushioned flight. Each subject's flailing arms and legs are
frozen by strobe lights and high-speed cameras for later analysis.
   Designers are looking for new insights into how to make a safer
flight of stairs. Results already have disspelled some
misconceptions about when and how people stumble.
   For example, although people generally fear falling down a
flight of stairs, research shows they are more likely to stumble on
the way up.
   During the experiment, each volunteer is trussed in a green
flight suit, neck brace, crash helmet and padded mittens, and slung
from a red parachute harness that automatically arrests each fall.
   ``At a predetermined point, we turn on an electric beam that
goes across the front edge of the stair we want them to fall on,''
Ms. Hyde said. ``They break the beam and that acts as the trigger
to collapse the stair.''
   So far the researchers have entered 1,400 images from 50
recorded falls into a computer to recreate a complete electronic
composite of a bad fall.
   ``The computer simulation will tell us what position they would
have landed in, what they would have hit first,'' Ms. Hyde said.
``We need to learn what kind of forces people generate when they
fall.''
   As many as 2.6 million people every year are injured in stairway
falls. An undeveloped or deteriorating sense of balance make the
danger acute for children or the elderly.
   The Georgia Tech team has a two-year, $125,000 grant from the
National Science Foundation to develop energy-absorbing foams that
could replace the wood, metal and stone of traditional stairways.
   ``With stairs, you are always going to have accidents. You can't
pad people,'' Ms. Hyde said. ``So you have to come up with some way
to attenuate the forces that build up in a fall.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880705-0040 </DOCNO>
