<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 0355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Church     07-05 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Church,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anglican Church Debates Whether To Ordain Women Priests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Anglican Church said the
priesthood in England can only gain by ordaining women, but
opponents within the church said they based their case on tradition
and the Bible.
   ``I have come to the judgment that the ordination of women to
the priesthood would actually be an enlargement of the Catholic
(universal) priesthood, an opening up of priesthood, rather than
its overturning,'' Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie said
Monday.
   Runcie, the church's spiritual head and leader of the world's 70
million Anglicans, made his comments before the policy-making
General Synod of 574 bishops, clergy and laity as it opened its
regular three-day summer session.
   An all-day debate on allowing women into the priesthood was
planned today.
   The church still bars women priests although Anglican churches
in other countries have ordained about 1,000 women, according to
England's Movement for the Ordination of Women. Ordaining churches
include the U.S. Episcopalians and Anglicans in Canada, New
Zealand, Hong Kong, Brazil, Kenya and Uganda.
   Runcie said that in an age when women took part in leadership,
the priesthood actually may be weakened by being solely male.
   Opponents say there is nothing in the Bible to support women
priests; that Jesus Christ who founded Christianity had only male
apostles and for nearly 2,000 years the church ordained only men.
   The debate on women's ordination has lasted more than 20 years.
   New proposals in the debate include giving a bishop who opposes
women priests the right to bar them in his diocese and to pay up to
$51,000 compensation to priests who leave the church over the issue
on grounds of conscience.
   The Anglican state church has seemed to be moving slowly toward
ordaining women but even if the proposals are endorsed there is
still a long way to go.
   The legislation will be referred to revision committees and then
to all 44 diocesan synods. It will return to the General Synod for
final approval but it must then be approved by Parliament.
   The church cannot legislate alone on matters of doctrine because
it is an established church, meaning it is established by laws made
by Parliament and has the monarch as its temporal head.
   If all stages are passed without delay, the Church of England's
first woman priest may be ordained in 1992 or 1993.
   A majority of the 53 diocesan and deputy bishops are in favor of
women priests but some, like Bishop of London Graham Leonard _ the
third-ranking prelate _ are strongly against. Sections of the
clergy and laity are also opposed.
   Speakers in favor of women priests at Monday's debate
outnumbered opponents by four to one.
   Bishop of Durham David Jenkins said he found the arguments for a
male God ``wholly incredible.''
   ``This portrayal of God attempts to retain the power of men in
the church, is an affront to the full, vital and immensely needed
humanity of women and is a denial of the mystery of God,'' he said.
   But Sir John Stokes, a Conservative Party legislator, asked:
``Have we the power to make such a fundamental change without
consulting the rest of Christendom when we are clearly not of one
mind?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
