<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AirlinerProbe     07-05 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner Probe,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Asks For Investigation of U.S. Attack on Airliner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner-World, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has asked the International Civil Aviation
Organization to immediately begin an investigation into an American
warship's downing of an Iranian passenger jetliner over the Persian
Gulf.
   But officials of the U.N. agency said Monday that they need more
information, particularly from the United States, before granting
the request.
   ``We have not received ... preliminary reports regarding the
circumstances from the parties involved, except from Iran,''
organization president Assad Kotaite said.
   Ali Akbar Golruni, Iran's representative to the organization,
filed a formal request Monday for an emergency meeting of the
agency's council to set up an inquiry into the crash.
   The USS Vincennes shot down the Iran Air jetliner on Sunday on a
commercial flight over the Strait of Hormuz, the gateway to the
gulf. All 290 people aboard were believed killed.
   The Pentagon said the Airbus 300 was mistaken for an Iranian
fighter jet, was flying outside the commercial air corridor and did
not respond to seven radioed warnings.
   Iran claims the jet was inside the commercial corridor. It has
also said the pilot did not report any emergency before the crash.
   The International Civil Aviation Organization, with 159 member
countries, oversees the safety and efficiency of world airlines.
</TEXT>
