<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 0448EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MidgetSub     07-05 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Midget Sub,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Japanese Midget Sub Might Have Been Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEARL HARBOR, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An object in about 800 feet of water
outside the mouth of Pearl Harbor might be a Japanese submarine
believed sunk hours before the attack on Dec. 7, 1941, authorities
said.
   ``It could be anything,'' said Bill Dickinson, superintendent of
the USS Arizona Memorial Park. ``Even a bunch of oil drums in a
line. But it looks promising.''
   Sonar pings produced a shape that matches what is known about
midget submarines involved in the Japanese attack, Dickinson said,
adding that it was in a ``high probably area'' for the midget sub.
   ``It's going to take a lot more to confirm what's down there,''
he said. ``First, we have to locate the resources to pay for a
search and then convince the University of Hawaii or National
Geographic or somebody else with deep-diving equipment to go down
and take a look.''
   ``That's the only way the mystery will be solved,'' he said.
   In the predawn hours before the Japanese launched their surprise
air assault on Pearl Harbor and other military bases on the island
of Oahu, the destroyer USS Ward spotted something odd in the water
leading to the harbor entrance.
   It was one of five midget subs involved in the attack and was
trying to slip into the harbor. Each sub had a two-man crew and two
torpedoes.
   The Ward fired shells at the intruder, apparently hitting the
conning tower, and then blanketed the area with depth charges.
   Nothing more was seen of the sub and it remains the only one of
the five unaccounted for.
   The underwater object was detected Friday during a survey of
Pearl Harbor and surrounding waters as a cooperative effort of the
Navy and the National Parks Service with funds from the Arizona
Memorial Museum.
   It is being done to fulfill a federal requirement that historic
artifacts in a national historic landmark be catalogued.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
