<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NorthernIreland     07-05 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twenty Officers Face Hearings In Killings Of Unarmed Catholics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of this British
province's mostly Protestant police force has ordered an internal
disciplinary hearing for 20 officers in the 1982 killings of six
unarmed Roman Catholics.
   Chief Constable Sir John Hermon of the Royal Ulster Constabulary
ordered the hearing on Monday. Critics have charged that police had
a ``shoot-to-kill'' policy and that a subsequent cover-up
undermined efforts to persuade the Catholic minority to accept
police authority.
   Prime Minister Charles Haughey's government across the border in
the Irish Republic said that substituting an internal police
hearing for prosecutions in the courts will not allay public
concern.
   The officers at the closed-door internal hearing could face
penalties ranging from cautions and reprimands to fines, loss of
pension rights, demotions and dismissal from the police force.
   Hermon said a chief constable from the British mainland will be
appointed to preside over the hearing. He did not name the 20
officers, give details of the precise charges against them or say
when the hearing will be held.
   But press reports said it is expected to be held in Belfast and
that the 20 officers range from constable, the lowest rank in the
police force, to middle-ranked chief superintendent.
   Haughey's government, Catholic politicians, civil libertarians
and the human rights group Amnesty International say the killings
were illegal.
   In a three-week period at the end of 1982, police shot to death
five acknowledged guerrillas, all unarmed, and an innocent
teen-ager in three incidents, two at police roadblocks and one in a
barn.
   Two years later, a senior mainland detective was called in to
investigate after it emerged in court that officers had perjured
themselves covering up the circumstances of the killings.
   The detective, John Stalker, has written a book that says he was
forced off the case because he was close to proving police
conspired to bypass legal procedures and shoot to kill guerrilla
suspects.
   His inquiry was completed by Colin Sampson, another senior
mainland officer. Sampson's conclusions led to an announcement by
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government that while evidence
indicated that officers perverted justice, there would be no
prosecutions.
   Acting on Sampson's report, the police authority decided no
disciplinary action was required against Hermon or his two deputies.
   Meanwhile, a parallel investigation was conducted into the
conduct of lower-ranking officers, and this led to Monday's
announcement of an internal disciplinary hearing.
   Seamus Mallon, deputy leader of the Social Democratic and Labor
Party, the province's largest Catholic party, said he was
dissatisfied.
   ``It is both unfair and unjust for 20 men of lower rank to take
the rap when those with real responsibility remain protected by and
shrouded in mystery regarding their own conduct,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, the monthly meeting of Belfast City Council was
abandoned Monday night after fist fights broke out between
Protestant and Catholic members.
   The fighting involved about 20 people _ members of the
province's two Protestant Unionist parties and members of Sinn
Fein, legal political arm of the outlawed, mainly Catholic Irish
Republican Army.
   Five of those involved were treated in hospital for minor
injuries, said a press officer at Belfast police headquarters.
   The IRA is fighting to push the British out of this
Protestant-dominated province, join it with the Republic of Ireland
and set up an all-Ireland socialist state.
</TEXT>
