<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms In Southeast, Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered thunderstorms dampened the Southeast today after rain
fell over the northern Rockies, the High Plains and western Oregon
and up to 18 inches of hail dropped on Montana.
   The strongest storms occurred Monday afternoon in Montana, when
dime-size hail piled up 2{ inches deep between Geyser and Stanford,
and up to 18 inches was reported in gullies near Colony.
   Scattered thunderstorms fell Monday night along a small area of
the High Plains from southwestern South Dakota and eastern Wyoming
through eastern Colorado into parts of New Mexico. Winds gusted to
61 mph at Redig, S.D. Thunderstorms also developed over North
Dakota, with winds gusting to 68 mph at Dickinson.
   Early today, thunderstorms continued to extend from northern
Georgia across much of Alabama into southern Mississippi. Near
Huntsville, Ala., just over a third of an inch of rain fell within
30 minutes.
   Much of the Plains and the Mississippi, Ohio and Tennessee
valleys had a very warm, humid night. Temperatures early today were
in the 70s and there were scattered readings in the 80s across the
central Plains.
   Record high temperatures for July 4 were set in a number of
communities, including 105 degrees at Aberdeen, S.D., a degree
higher than the 1936 record; 92 degrees at Buffalo, N.Y., beating
the 91-degree mark of 1897; and 89 at Duluth, Minn., topping the
88-degree record of 1948.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from Texas
to the lower Mississippi and lower Tennessee valleys to the south
Atlantic Coast, and for Minnesota, the western Great Plains and the
Rocky Mountain states, with showers and thunderstorms most numerous
in Alabama, the Florida Panhandle and southeast Louisiana; a few
showers were expected in Oregon and Washington; and sunshine in the
Northeast and much of the Southwest.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 80s or 90s across most
of the nation; the 60s or 70s in northwest Montana, Washington and
Oregon, parts of Idaho, and along the California coast; between 100
and 105 degrees from sections of the northern and central Great
Plains to southwest Minnesota; and up to 115 over the desert
Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Redmond, Ore., to 95 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 70 foggy; Boston 65 fair; Buffalo 66 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 67 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 72 fair; Cleveland 66
fair; Detroit 66 fair; Miami 78 fair; New York 66 fair;
Philadelphia 72 fair; Pittsburgh 65 fair; Portland, Maine 57 fair;
Washington 70 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 71 cloudy; Chicago 72 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
76 fair; Denver 68 fair; Des Moines 75 fair; Indianapolis 76 fair;
Kansas City 79 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 77 fair; Nashville 72
fair; New Orleans 72 fair; St. Louis 76 hazy.
   _West: Albuquerque 75 partly cloudy; Anchorage 55 cloudy; Las
Vegas 84 fair; Los Angeles 62 fair; Phoenix 95 fair; Salt Lake City
79 fair; San Diego 63 fair; San Francisco 56 windy; Seattle 55
partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
