<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0464 07-05 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0464,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arabs Shut Down Gaza And Much Of West Bank With General Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with today's action. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians shut down shops and transportation
in the occupied lands today in a PLO-ordered general strike, and
underground leaders of the uprising urged Arabs to step up civil
disobedience against Israeli rule.
   Israeli troops shot and wounded a 17-year-old Arab in the chest
today during a clash in the West Bank city of Nablus, said an
official at the city's Al Ittihad Hospital.
   An army spokesman said the soldiers opened fire after a group of
youths hurled rocks at them from a rooftop in the city's
marketplace. The hospital official identified the youth as Hatem
Kilani.
   Since the unrest began Dec. 8 against Israel's 21-year
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip, 215 Palestinians and
four Israelis have been killed.
   The army demolished two homes belonging to Arabs suspected of
staging firebomb attacks in the West Bank city of Bethlehem, Israel
army radio and Arab witnesses said.
   ``We shall reach anyone, every place where a firebomb is thrown
... (where) a man has thrown a firebomb in cold blood, intending to
kill everyone here,'' Brig. Gen. Gabi Ofir, a West Bank commander,
said on the radio.
   The violence came hours before the strike turned six Arab cities
in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip _ Nablus, Gaza City, Hebron,
Jenin, Ramallah and Bethlehem _ into virtual ghost towns.
   Most of about 120,000 Palestinians employed in Israel also
stayed away from their jobs as part of a general strike ordered in
a leaflet last month by uprising leaders affliated with the
Palestine Liberation Organization, Arab news reports said.
   About 800 Arab schools in the West Bank were shut today as part
of a three-day closing ordered by the army on Monday in an an
attempt to prevent further violence.
   The school shutdown also came in response to instructions by
uprising leaders to rename ``all institutions and schools not
bearing Palestinian names'' today.
   Brig. Gen. Shaike Erez, who heads the West Bank military
government, said Monday the he hoped the closings ``would bring
home to students and parents that the current level of disturbances
is unacceptable.''
   Palestinians were also urged today to boycott military
government offices. But Arabs complied only partially after the
military summoned many to appear at its offices, apparently as a
counter-measure, Israel radio reported.
   In Bethlehem, hundreds of men and women were seen lining up in
front of the Israeli authorities' headquarters to obtain various
documents.
   But in the seaside Gaza Strip, a total strike was reported. An
Arab reporter in Gaza said he saw soldiers trying to order workers
to board buses to Israel in the Jabaliya refugee camp, but the men
refused. Jabaliya, a frequent trouble spot, is home to about 60,000
Palestinians.
   Two new leaflets distributed today urged Arabs to stage more
daylong general strikes throughout July to mark seven months of the
rebellion.
   The leaflets gave conflicting dates for the strikes, and it was
not immediately known whether they were distributed by rival
factions of the underground leadership.
</TEXT>
