<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NewspageSoccer     07-05 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newspage Soccer,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soccer Finals To Be Played In United States In 1994</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Cup soccer championship
finals will be held in the United States for the first time ever in
1994, the international soccer association decided.
   The U.S. bid to stage the event, held every four years, won over
bids by Brazil and Morocco. Possible sites for the title match
include Miami; Pasadena, Calif.; and Kansas City, Mo.
   U.S. delegates clapped and cheered Monday when Harry Cavan,
senior vice president of the Federation Internationale de Football
Association, announced the tally after a morning filled with
meetings by the international soccer governing body's executive
committee.
   ``Obviously the first instant reaction is relief,'' said U.S.
Soccer Federation President Werner Fricker. ``The decision is made.
After that, I guess the next thing is `What's next?'''
   After the announcement, Cavan said: ``I noticed the U.S.
delegation in its presentation used the word `football.' I was
quite happy about that because I have been trying for years to get
them to do that.''
   The U.S. presentation also included a videotaped message from
President Reagan.
   As host, the United States automatically qualifies for the 1994
World Cup. The four-week, 52-match tournament will be the biggest
undertaking ever for American soccer, which Fricker said has made
``unbelievable'' progress in the past decade.
   ``We're not as successful as other soccer powers, but we've
played the game for about 100 years,'' he said. ``The American
public is interested in all major sporting events. We expect to
fill all stadiums to about 80 percent capacity.''
   The 1986 World Cup was held in Mexico, while the 1990
competition is to be held in Italy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
