<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Orange Juice-Poison,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poison-Filled Syringe Found In Orange Juice Carton</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discovery of a poison-filled syringe in a
carton of orange juice led supermarket officials to pull the
brand's entire stock of juice from shelves, police said.
   No injuries were reported in the Monday incident, police Officer
Bill Frio said. A customer alerted store officials to the syringe
found inside a 64-ounce cardboard carton of Minute Maid juice,
according to Frio.
   Tests by an independent laboratory confirmed the device was
filled with a poisonous substance, West Valley police spokesman Jim
McClurg said today. The type of poison found would not be revealed
until a police lab test was conducted, he added.
   Daryl Byrum, a manager at the Vons store in Woodland Hills,
declined comment on the incident early today.
</TEXT>
