<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 0900EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DestroyerSlaying     07-05 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Destroyer Slaying,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sailor's Court-Martial Set To Begin This Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL AIR STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys are preparing
for the court-martial of a Navy sailor facing murder and robbery
charges in the slaying of a payroll officer on board ship.
   Once pretrial motions are completed this week, a court-martial
panel will be selected for the trial of Petty Officer 1st Class
Ruben Colon, officials said.
   Colon, 34, is charged in the shooting death of Lt. j.g. Ratish
Prasad, the disbursing officer of the USS Hancock, and with
stealing more than $94,000 from the ship's safe. Charges against
Colon include murder, robbery, kidnapping and receipt of stolen
property.
   Colon faces the death penalty if found guilty. The last time the
Navy executed one of its own was in 1849, when two brothers were
hanged in San Francisco for mutiny, desertion and assaulting an
officer.
   A pretrial hearing began June 20. U.S. Magistrate Harvey E.
Schlesinger is scheduled to testify today as the hearing's final
witness.
   Colon's attorney, Lt. Matthew Michels, has argued that
Schlesinger should not have issued a federal warrant to naval
investigators to search three bank safe-deposit boxes based on an
erroneous affidavit. Michels contends the seized items should not
be admitted into evidence.
   One of the safe-deposit boxes held more than $87,000 in cash and
2,575 blank U.S. Treasury checks imprinted with the name of the
Mayport-based destroyer. All three boxes had been rented in Colon's
name, investigators said.
   The checks and $94,629 were reported stolen from the Hancock on
March 15, the day Prasad's body was discovered in a sea-bag locker.
   Prasad, 24, was bound, gagged, choked, and shot in the head at
point-blank range with a .38-caliber handgun, investigators said.
   Colon, a Navy technician from Vega Baja, Puerto Rico, has been
held at the brig at Jacksonville Naval Air Station since his arrest
April 12 aboard the Hancock.
   Opening arguments in the trial are set to begin Wednesday or
Thursday at the Fleet Training Center, according to Navy officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
