<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Airliner-Say     07-05 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Say,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage's Sister Fears Repercussions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CADIZ, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sister of an American who has been held
hostage in Lebanon since 1985 says she feels empathy for the
relatives of the 290 people killed when an Iranian jetliner was
shot down by a U.S. missile.
   ``I know what it is to be an innocent victim,'' said Peggy Say,
sister of hostage Terry Anderson. ``Here we have 290 grieving
families that were caught up in something outside of themselves the
same as we have been. My heart goes out to them.''
   She added: ``I think we have to apologize over and over again. I
don't think we can apologize enough for something like this.''
   Mrs. Say, meeting with reporters at her new home near here
Monday, declined to say whether she agreed with the United States'
Persian Gulf policy, but she said she hoped the United States would
re-examine its policy.
   ``The question I've been asking myself, just as an American, is
how we could make such a horrendous mistake,'' she said.
   All 290 people aboard the jetliner were killed.
   Anderson, 40, the chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press, was abducted March 16, 1985, in Beirut, Lebanon.
He is one of nine Americans believed held captive by factions with
ties to Iran and has been held the longest of any American.
   Mrs. Say said she feared the incident would harm any current
effort to gain the release of her brother and the other hostages.
   ``I'm very concerned, yet hoping and praying that they (in Iran)
will be able to understand that this has nothing to do with these
hostages,'' she said.
</TEXT>
