<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Sisulu     07-05 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Sisulu,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Editor of Black Newspaper Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Afirca (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zwelakhe Sisulu, the detained
editor of the New Nation newspaper, has been hospitalized and is
being treated for depression, his attorney said today.
   Sisulu, 37, was taken Friday from Diepkloof Prison in the black
township of Soweto and admitted to Johannesburg Hospital, said his
attorney, Priscilla Jana.
   ``I visited him this morning. He is still depressed and he's
lost a lot of weight,'' she said.
   Sisulu has been detained without charge since December 1986, and
courts have rejected requests that the government charge or release
him.
   During his detention, the 2-year-old newspaper, which is
published for black readers by the South African Catholic Bishops
Conference, was banned for three months. It resumed publication
last week.
   Government officials have said Sisulu was being detained because
of his journalistic activities and because he was allegedly a
member of the National Education Crisis Committee. Sisulu denied
that he was a member of the committee, which is legal and
unrestricted, but the court upheld the police's right to hold him
under national emergency regulations.
   Sisulu, who studied at Harvard University under a Nieman
Fellowship, is the son of imprisoned African National Congress
leader Walter Sisulu.
   His brother, Thabo, is chief spokesman for the outlawed ANC in
Lusaka, Zambia, and his mother, Albertina, is a co-president of the
banned United Democratic Front, an anti-apartheid group. She is
prohibited from giving news interviews or speeches.
   Under apartheid, the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs and the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
