<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WillieB'sBirthday     07-05 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Willie B's Birthday,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zoo Atlanta's Famous Gorilla Turns 30, Enjoys Fruits Of Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The banana split was for people, so Zoo Atlanta's
elder ape made do with a honeydew and other fruit at his 30th
birthday party.
   About 500 people turned out for the Fourth of July celebration
opposite Willie B.'s new outdoor habitat at the zoo's African rain
forest.
   For the human celebrants, there was a vast concoction billed as
the world's biggest banana split, whipped together under a circus
tent and handed out free to visitors.
   Willie B. received a generous basket of fruit, which he lugged
to the edge of a moat. ``Oooh,'' cried a child. ``Looka the big
monkey!''
   The great ape downed five bananas for starters, dropping the
peels carefully in front of him, then gobbled a few clusters of red
grapes, followed by an apple and a couple of handfuls of
strawberries.
   Surveying the onlookers with a benign air, Willie B. put away a
couple of cantaloupes, licking the rinds clean. Ignoring the onset
of a steady drizzle of rain, he dipped into the basket for a
cluster of green grapes, which he ate daintily, grape by grape,
with obvious pleasure.
   Some in the crowd sang ``Happy Birthday.''
   No one knows what day the 459-pound gorilla was born, since he
was captured as an infant in Africa. He's been at Zoo Atlanta since
he was about 3. Gorillas in captivity usually live to be about 45.
</TEXT>
