<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     07-05 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Studio Chief Criticizes Proposed Interim Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for striking writers say a
proposed interim agreement is the best hope for resuming
production, but the chief of Paramount Studios said the plan would
extend the 18-week-old strike.
   ``The latest interim agreement promulgated by the Writers Guild
of America indicates a strike-prolonging retrenchment at a time
when they should be seeking a solution,'' Frank Mancuso said in a
statement Monday.
   Mancuso, spokesman for the executive committee of the Alliance
of Motion Picture and Television Producers, is the first major
studio head to speak out against the strike that has paralyzed much
of the film and television industry.
   His statement came two days before 9,000 guild members are to
vote on an interim agreement already approved by the union
leadership that allows script writers to sign deals with
independent producers.
   ``There's a vote coming up Wednesday and he wants the writers to
take stock of where they are,'' alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg
said. ``And he also wants the independent producers to understand
that this interim agreement has some fishhooks in it.''
   Steinberg said his group warned independent producers that the
interim agreement would cost them more in residual payments than
the alliance offer now on the table.
   The proposed agreement would also allow writers to buy back
scripts that are not used for film production, Steinberg said.
   Two settlement proposals offered by the alliance have been
rejected by the writers.
   So far, 118 independent companies have signed deals with Writers
Guild members under both the old contract and the proposed interim
agreement.
   Guild spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said the interim proposal would
allow many production companies to resume work.
   ``We are unfortunately trying to negotiate with a leadership of
the companies that has chosen to spend more money to stay on strike
than it would cost to settle,'' Ms. Rhoden said.
</TEXT>
