<HEAD>Jackson Says He's Best Qualified For Veep Slot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with Jackson comments today, pickup graf 6
pvs, bgng, ``On Monday...; Adds byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson laid out a detailed case today for
why he should be offered the vice presidential spot on the
Democratic ticket and dismissed others under consideration as
``unknown quantities.''
   He refused to say whether he would accept the position if it is
offered, however.
   ``No one else has had to pass the same tests,'' Jackson told
reporters the morning after his Fourth of July meeting with
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, who is in the process of
selecting a running mate.
   ``I bring the sense of creativity, a new history,'' Jackson said.
   He refused to say whether he pushed himself for the vice
presidential nomination during his dinner meeting with Dukakis and
also refused, as he has for two weeks, to make public whether he
would accept the No. 2 spot.
   But he listed numerous attributes he said made him uniquely
qualified among the handful of people being considered to share the
ticket with Dukakis, principally his participation in the lengthy
primary season, during which he attracted nearly 7 million votes.
   ``The others under consideration are unknown quantities beyond
their districts and beyond their home states,'' Jackson said.
   He was departing for New York this morning but left behind top
aides who were to meet with Dukakis campaign aides to discuss
convention issues.
   Jackson spoke to reporters today after giving an
uncharacteristic ``no comment'' when asked Monday night if the vice
presidency was a topic of his discussions with Dukakis.
   Jackson and his wife Jacqueline had dinner with Dukakis and his
wife Kitty, and the two couples attended a Boston Pops concert and
watched a fireworks display.
   On Monday, before flying to Boston for his meeting with Dukakis,
Jackson said the Reagan administration should examine its ``failed
and vague policy'' in the Persian Gulf following the U.S. Navy's
downing of an Iranian airliner.
   Warning that the lives of American hostages in Lebanon are in
danger, Jackson appealed Monday to President Reagan to go on
television to apologize for the incident and ``offer reparations to
the (victims') families to ease some of their pain.''
   Reagan on Monday repeated his sorrow over the lives lost, but
said he would await the results of a Pentagon investigation before
making decisions on matters such as reparations.
   ``I am sincerely concerned that we make a gesture of goodwill
immediately so as to protect the lives of Americans who are in the
region, specifically the Americans who are held hostage there,''
Jackson said in Chicago .
   Jackson made his remarks during a brief news conference at his
Chicago home.
   Jackson said the shooting incident complicates the situation in
the gulf at a time when there are indications that forces in Iran
favoring negotiations are gaining strength.
</TEXT>
