<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VietnamMemorial     07-05 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam Memorial,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Immigrant Wins Competition To Design Memorial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLMDEL, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnamese immigrant selected to design
the state's Vietnam Veterans Memorial says he wants to show
veterans and his adopted country his gratitude.
   ``I want to thank the country for taking us in and making us
Americans,'' said Hien T. Nguyen at a ceremony Monday at the Garden
State Arts Center where the memorial will be built.
   ``I feel like I've done something good,'' said Nguyen, a
35-year-old architect from Marlboro whose entry was selected from
425 proposals.
   Referring to the nation's Vietnam veterans, he said, ``If not
for them, I might not be here today. They gave us new life. We are
the lucky ones.''
   He said he will donate his $5,000 award to efforts to return
MIAs to the United States and reunite Amerasian children with their
U.S. parents.
   Nguyen's award-winning design features an oval with a
200-foot-diameter set flat on the ground. A 9-foot high panel of
black granite lining the interior will be inscribed with the names
of 1,419 New Jersey residents killed in Vietnam and another 63
listed as missing in action. A New Jersey oak tree will stand in
the center of the two-tiered memorial.
   About 200 veterans and their families at the ceremony applauded
Nguyen's work. Some in uniforms embraced the architect.
   Nguyen, who become a U.S. citizen five years ago, was evacuated
from Saigon in an American airlift on April 30, 1975 with his
mother and sister. The family was taken to a refugee camp in
Arkansas before Nguyen moved to Blacksburg, Va., where his brother
Han was a student at Virginia Polytechnic Institute.
   Nguyen, an architecture student in Saigon, received an
undergraduate degree in the field from VPI and went to New Jersey
with his brother, who works for AT&T's Bell Labs. His parents live
in Montreal.
   Funding for Nguyen's $2.5 million design will come from a
variety of sources, including veterans' groups, private
corporations and the state, said state Sen. Edward O'Connor,
D-Hudson, chairman of the memorial committee.
   In Salt Lake City, meanwhile, ground was broken Monday for a
memorial to the 364 Vietnam War dead or MIAS from Utah.
   Utah County Commissioner Brent Morris, a Vietnam veteran and
Purple Heart recipient, said during a ceremony at the state capitol
that the memorial would help release years of bitterness.
   The Utah monument will feature an 8-foot statue of a young
infantryman slogging through a rice paddy, carrying his own rifle
and that of a fallen comrade. The monument will be 60 feet in
diameter with four polished black marble plaques listing the names
of Utah's MIAs and dead.
   The organization behind the monument, the Utah Vietnam Era
Veteran's Memorial Committee, has raised almost $70,000 to fund the
project and hopes to reach its goal of $231,000 by year's end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
