<HEAD>Shultz Leaves on Far East Trip</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First 3 grafs new material, picking up 3rd graf pvs, Shultz
plans</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George Shultz left today on
a 2{-week trip that will take him to nine Pacific and East Asian
nations, with defense and trade issues at the top of his agenda.
   The series of meetings begins with a three-day ministerial
summit of ASEAN, the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, in
Bangkok, Thailand, starting Thursday.
   The U.S. downing of an Iranian jetliner with 290 people aboard
is bound to come up in his meetings with foreign leaders. The
Persian Gulf is a strategically sensitive area, and governments
around the world are eager to see a negotiated settlement of the
Iran-Iraq war.
   Shultz plans to discuss issues including American military bases
in the region, U.S. trade deficits with the area's emerging
industrial powers and the future of Cambodia as it moves toward
independence following a 10-year Vietnamese occupation.
   Shultz' trip will be his last and longest to the Pacific rim as
secretary of state. After Thailand, he plans to visit Malaysia,
Indonesia, the Philippines, Hong Kong, China, South Korea, Japan
and the new Marshall Islands Republic.
   While in China, Shultz hopes to win assurances that the Chinese
will not support any attempt by the Khmer Rouge to regain control
of Cambodia. The communist group was blamed for the deaths of
millions of Cambodians in purges and forced relocations in the
1970s.
   The Khmer Rouge government was dismantled by Vietnamese
occupation forces, which have now begun to withdraw from Cambodia.
</TEXT>
