<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Germany-PlaneCrash     07-05 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Plane Crash,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Fighter Jet Crashes Into Field</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STADE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German Air Force F-4 Phantom
fighter jet crashed into a field and exploded today, seconds after
its two pilots ejected to safety, police said.
   The crash is the latest in a series of military flight accidents
in West Germany since March.
   Police said the jet went down 12 miles south of Stade, about 25
miles west of the northern port city of Hamburg.
   One pilot was slightly injured, officials said.
   The area where the jet crashed is the scene of frequent
low-level military training flights.
   Citizens and environmental groups have protested the flights. A
local newspaper recently reported that a man had to be buried
without final graveside services because the pastor could not make
himself heard over the din of low-flying jets.
   On Sunday, a West German army helicopter crashed into a cliff in
Bavaria state, killing all nine aboard.
   On Friday, a civilian-owned airplane under contract with the
West German army crashed into a house in northern Germany, killing
the pilot.
   Three U.S. Air Force F-16s crashed last Wednesday. One pilot was
killed when two of the jets collided in flight. F-16s also crashed
March 31 and April 18.
   The accidents led opponents of low-level military training
flights to renew calls that they be eliminated or sharply reduced.
   West Germany's new defense minister, Rupert Scholz, said last
week that he would make the problem of low-level flights a top
priority.
   U.S. officials said the F-16s involved in last Wednesday's
crashes were not on low-level flight missions.
</TEXT>
