<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Strike     07-05 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Strike,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Shoe Industry Workers Demonstrate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VUKOVAR, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 3,000 people chanting
``Down with the government!'' today marched through the streets of
this central Yugoslav town demanding higher wages, witnesses and
the Tanjug news agency said.
   Most of the demonstrators are workers at a major Yugoslav shoe
factory, Borovo, who went on strike Saturday to protest the partial
payment of their June wages, the agency said.
   The government in May linked wages to the low industrial
productivity as part of an austerity program designed to cut
Yugoslavia's 175 percent inflation rate and its $21 billion foreign
debt.
   Several witnesses in Vukovar, about 60 miles west of Belgrade,
told The Associated Press that the demonstrators, who carried
Yugoslav flags as well as Communist Party banners, demanded a
change in the country's leadership.
   The strike was the latest in a series of recent protests across
the country against the government's economic measures.
   Yugoslavia registered a record 1,600 strikes last year,
involving over 300,000 workers.
