<DOCNO> AP880705-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PeaceWalk     07-05 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peace Walk,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Help Celebrate July Fourth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORALVILLE, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and American peace walkers
journeyed westward across Iowa today after spending nearly a week
in the eastern part of the state and celebrating the Fourth of July
with a parade and cookout.
   Members of the American-Soviet Peace Walk carried Soviet,
American and Iowa flags in the two-mile parade Monday.
   ``This has been a great walk. American and Soviets do a great
deal of work for the cause of peace,'' said Valentina Belik, a Kiev
resident who joined about 220 other Soviets and 100 Americans on
the cross-country journey.
   Coralville Mayor Michael Kattchee, smiling broadly under a straw
hat, said the peace walk had a special significance for him.
   ``This is great. I was born in Lithuania, so for me it is a
great pleasure to see this happening,'' the 56-year-old mayor said.
``Maybe events like this will help open borders between the two
countries.
   ``I'm able to speak a little Russian, but I slip into German and
then I'm lost,'' Kattchee said.
   Lithuania was under Russian control from 1795 to 1918, under
Polish domination from 1920 to 1940, then was occupied by Soviet
troops and absorbed into the Soviet Union.
   The peace walkers have been in eastern Iowa _ the second leg of
their three-stage journey _ since last Wednesday and will continue
this week to Des Moines. From there, the group will be flown to Los
Angeles, where members will begin the last leg of their trek.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
