<2ND_LINE>PM-Developer Dies,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controversial Developer Awaiting Trial In Bank-Loan Fraud Dies in
Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A real estate developer awaiting trial in a
multimillion-dollar bank-loan fraud case apparently electrocuted
himself in jail, a sheriff's spokesman said.
   J.R. McConnell, 40, was discovered by a guard in a medical unit
at the Harris County Jail before 4 a.m. Monday, said sheriff's Lt.
G.L. Moore.
   ``It appears he had some type of electrical cord and inserted it
into one of the electric outlets that are of necessity in that
medical area and inserted the other end into another electrical
outlet and used himself to complete the circuit,'' Moore said.
   It was not known how McConnell obtained the cord, but inmates
usually purchase such items at the jail's commissary, Moore said.
   McConnell had been in the medical ward since he tried to hang
himself in his cell March 21. McConnell also had heart problems,
Moore added.
   Moore said that a note believed to be written by McConnell was
found on a table next to McConnell's bed.
   ``It's somewhat illegible and we're attempting to decipher what
it says. But it appears it might possibly be a suicide note,''
Moore said.
   Following his March suicide attempt, McConnell said he was
despondent over delays in his court proceedings. He was being held
on $750,000 bond pending trial July 19.
   McConnell surrendered to federal authorities last November when
he got off a plane from Mexico; he had been missing for more than a
year. He was indicted in October on charges that he and five
associates last year arranged loans for $4.2 million through fraud,
including false ownership papers for property posted as collateral.
   McConnell amassed hundreds of rental properties and development
projects in Houston and Galveston, court records show.
   In October 1986, he filed for bankruptcy. A court-appointed
trustee's report said McConnell and the 10 companies included in
the filing owed $427 million against $281 million in assets.
   Federal officials have said the two loans listed in the
indictment, one at a Houston bank and another at a savings and
loan, were only part of a larger scheme to defraud lending
institutions of at least $162 million.
</TEXT>
