<HEAD>Police Say Man Kills Two Sons, Mother-In-Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 28-year-old man allegedly killed two of his
sons and his mother-in-law and critically wounded a third son
before trying to kill himself by jumping in the Detroit River,
police said.
   The suspect, an unemployed man whose identity was withheld, was
rescued Monday from the river, said Officer Fred Zaharoff, a police
spokesman.
   Before he jumped, the suspect told Homer Ford, a security guard
at the Central Marine Terminal, that he wanted to make his
estranged wife suffer, according to Ford.
   Police found the bodies at a home, Zaharoff said. They were
identified as Jason Kent, 5, Sparticus Kent, 7, and Essa Mae Kent,
64, police Lt. Philip Foster said. Owen Kent, 4, was in critical
condition at Children's Hospital with a head wound, officials said.
   The suspect was in custody on suspicion of murder, Zaharoff
said. No arraignment had been scheduled.
   In West Memphis, Ark., meanwhile, authorities said Monday that
two children whose burned bodies were found near a dump were killed
by their mother and another woman.
   Barbara McCoy, 40, the mother, and Mary Delois Williams, 32,
were in jail without bond Monday pending a hearing Wednesday,
Crittenden County Sheriff's investigator Charles Walker said.
   The women were arrested Monday at a motel in West Memphis, where
they had apparently been staying, investigators said. Both were
charged with first-degree murder.
   The bodies of Bianca Tirado, 7, and Maximillion E. McCoy, 2,
were found in plastic bags off a gravel road leading to a dump. The
children were slain elsewhere and dumped and set afire,
investigator R.D. Clay said.
