<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SovietInspections 1stLd-Writethru a0547 07-05 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Inspections, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0547,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Conclude First Arms Inspections; Repeat Visits Expected</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to include states; deletes now-extraneous 5th
graf, `Facilities in...' and Subs 7th graf pvs, `Davis-Monthan...'
to CORRECT to Missile, sted Missing, and UPDATE with comments from
escort, general; picks up 8th graf pvs, `In Colorado...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Teams of Soviet inspectors who are returning to Moscow today say
they were satifisfied with their weekend visits to U.S. military
installations in four states.
   The Soviets conducted ``baseline inspections'' in California,
Arizona, Utah and Colorado for the On-Site Inspections Agency under
the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces Treaty. U.S. teams were in
the Soviet Union at the same time.
   ``Together with representatives of the OSIA and with cooperation
of representatives of the plant, the first unprecedented action was
fulfilled in verification of the compliance with the obligation
under the treaty between the U.S.S.R and the U.S.,'' said
Vyacheslav Kharlamov, who led a group which visited General
Dynamics Plant 19 in San Diego.
   ``Basically, there's nothing for them to see,'' said Lt. Col.
J.B. Kump, explaining that the plant no longer makes the missile
launchers. ``But they are verifying what we said in the treaty
about this place is true.''
   In Arizona, the Soviets inspected facilities at Davis-Monthan
Air Force Base in Tucson and the Fort Huachuca Army base in Sierra
Vista.
   Davis-Monthan is the home of Air Force's 868th Tactical Missile
Training Group, which trains cruise missile crews for deployment
for Europe. The unit does some training at a Fort Huachuca range.
   ``They were very thorough. They knew what they were doing. It
wasn't just a walk-through. They were very technical,'' said Lt.
Perry L. Nouis, an escort with the OSIA.
   ``At this point, they're happy and we're happy,'' Air Force Gen.
Larry B. Keith, commander of the 836th Air Division at
Davis-Monthan, said.
   Keith also said the Soviets ``were very cordial in their
departure. They presented our escort officers with small medallions
and we in turn gave them squadron and group patches of the 868th
Missile Group as mementos for having been here.''
   In Colorado, Soviet inspectors visited the Pueblo Army Depot to
inventory Pershing missiles which are to be destroyed under the
treaty.
   Another team visited the Hercules Aerospace Co. plant at Magna,
Utah, near Salt Lake City, to verify that Pershing 2 engines were
no longer in production.
   Soviet inspectors will be permanently based in Magna, but not at
the other sites.
</TEXT>
