<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Church 3rdLd-Writethru a0556 07-05 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Church, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0556,a0551,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anglican Church Adopts Draft Legislation To Ordain Women Priests</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with legislation on women
priests adopted. Picks up 4th grav pvs, ` The archbishop said...'
SUBS last grav pvs, ``Parliament has...' with 3 grafs to CLARIFY
role of Parliament in approving legislation. </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church of England leaders today voted in favor of
draft legislation to admit women to the priesthood, despite
opposition from their spiritual head, Archbishop of Canterbury
Robert Runcie.
   The vote at the annual General Synod of bishops, clergy and
laity was 299 to 216.
   Earlier, Runcie drew loud applause from the 574 participants
when he warned that the legislation would divide the church, and
many observers believed the proposal would be defeated.
   The synod today opened its three-day summer session at Church
House, Westminster.
   During the debate, Runcie said that although he favored the
principle of women priests, he believed the terms of the proposal
would cause ``a kind of legislative schism.''
   The archbishop said he believed theological arguments ``now tip
the balance in favor'' of women priests, but added that the wording
of the draft legislation ``would not serve the cause of women's
ordination or the spiritual health of the church.'' He was
referring to proposed rules which would allow parishes and dioceses
to refuse to be ministered to by women priests.
   The archbishop is the spiritual head of the Anglican state
church and leader of the world's 70 million Anglicans, including 3
million U.S. Episcopalians.
   Runcie said earlier that the priesthood actually may be weakened
by being solely male.
   ``I have come to the judgment that the ordination of women to
the priesthood would actually be an enlargement of the Catholic
(universal) priesthood, an opening up of priesthood, rather than
its overturning,'' he said.
   The English church still bars women priests, although Anglican
churches in other countries have ordained about 1,000 women,
according to England's Movement for the Ordination of Women.
Churches ordaining women include the U.S. Episcopalians and
Anglicans in Canada, New Zealand, Hong Kong, Brazil, Kenya and
Uganda.
   Opponents say there is nothing in the Bible to support women
priests, that Jesus Christ had only male apostles and for nearly
2,000 years the church ordained only men.
   Speakers in favor of women priests at today's debate outnumbered
opponents by four to one. A majority of the 53 diocesan and deputy
bishops are in favor of women priests but some, including sections
of the clergy and laity, are opposed.
   Law lecturer David McClean, in moving the proposals, said: ``The
idea of women priests is not going to go away _ there is nothing in
the experience of the Anglican Communion to support any such
notion.''
   McCLean, of Sheffield University, is chairman of the synod's
House of Laity and opened the debate in the crowded assembly hall.
   New proposals include giving a bishop who opposes women priests
the right to bar them in his diocese and to pay up to $51,000
compensation to priests who leave the church over the issue on
grounds of conscience.
   The draft legislation will be referred to revision committees
and then to all 44 diocesan synods. It will return to the General
Synod for another vote and must then be approved by Parliament.
   Parliament, which by law established the Anglican church and
made the British monarch its temporal head, has the final say on
such legislation and on all other matters of church doctrine.
   If all stages are passed without delay, the Church of England's
first woman priest may be ordained in 1992 or 1993.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
