<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya-Germans     07-05 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Germans,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three West Germans Held By Police in Kenya</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have detained three West German
television journalists after a tribal chief objected to their
photographing a traditional funeral, a colleague said Tuesday.
   No charges have been filed against the West Germans, who are
being held under house arrest at the New Imperial Hotel in the
western town of Kisumu, according to a spokesman for the ARD-German
TV crew.
   The spokesman, who requested anonymity, identified the three as
Helmut Grosse, 49, from Hamburg; cameraman Thomas Mittelstenscheld,
39, of West Berlin; and Bernd Longree, 48, from Bonn, a TV
journalist who accompanied the others in a private capacity.
   The crew had driven to a village near Kisumu, 140 miles
northwest of Nairobi, to photograph a traditional Luo tribal burial
Sunday at the invitation of relatives, the journalist said.
   A local chief objected to their shooting and they stopped, he
said.
   Before their planned return to Nairobi, however, police
questioned them, seized their car, identity papers and equipment,
and ordered them to stay at the hotel, where they were lodged.
   ``We've had no official explanation as to why they are being
detained,'' their colleague said. ``We only know they've been told
not to leave the hotel.'' West German diplomats in Nairobi are
investigating, he added.
</TEXT>
