<HEAD>Dukakis Associate Pleads Innocent to Theft and Forgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The highest-ranking associate of Gov. Michael S.
Dukakis to face criminal indictment pleaded innocent today to state
charges of theft, forgery, tax evasion and conflict of interest.
   Gerard T. Indelicato, who faces sentencing on federal corruption
charges later this week, was released without bail by Magistrate
William Walsh in Suffolk Superior Court.
   Defense attorney Steve Brooks said Indelicato would also plead
innocent to another set of state charges Wednesday in Plymouth
County. Brooks had no further comment.
   The former education adviser to Dukakis pleaded guilty to
separate federal charges of fraud and conspiracy before state
Attorney General James Shannon filed new accusations.
   The state indictments cover both Indelicato's term as Dukakis'
special assistant for educational affairs from 1983 to 1986 and his
term as president of Bridgewater State College, a position he held
from 1986 until his resignation last December.
   The indictments outline a pattern of alleged criminal acts by
Indelicato, 42, and associates to divert an undisclosed amount of
public funds for private gain.
