<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Tito     07-05 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Tito,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Literary Magazine Banned For Criticizing Tito</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most recent issue of a liberal
Serbian literary magazine was bannned temporarily Tuesday for
publishing an article criticizing late President Josip Broz Tito.
   A prosecutor imposed the ban on the bimonthly Knjizevne Novine
pending a court decision, the state-run Tanjug news agency said.
   The prosecutor ruled that the article ``Criminals and Victims''
by Dragoslav Mihajlovic ``could imperil public peace.''
   The article dealt with Tito's role in the Communist regime's
repressive measures against dissidents incarcerated in the Goli
Otok prison camp in the late 1940s.
   Goli Otok, an isolated rocky island off the central Adriatic
coast, was used as an internment camp for 13,000 alleged opponents
of the regime after Tito's break with the Soviet bloc in 1948.
   Several thousand are said to have died in detention from ill
treatment by the prison authorities.
   Tito was the undisputed leader of Yugoslavia for 35 years until
his death in 1980. He is still officially revered by Yugoslav
authorities, and any public criticism of his policies is considered
a criminal offense.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
