<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0560 07-05 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0560,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis to Meet With Potential Running Mates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with new meetings in veep search in top 10 grafs,
picking up in 6th graf pvs, He has</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis invited two prospective
running mates to his Statehouse office today and planned to meet
Wednesday with another candidate for the No. 2 spot, a source said.
   Sen. Albert Gore of Tennesee and Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri, both former presidential candidates who have endorsed
Dukakis since dropping out of the race, were to visit the
Massachusetts governor first. Rep. Lee Hamilton of Indiana was to
meet with Dukakis on Wednesday, said the source, who spoke only on
the condition of anonymity.
   Dukakis recently has met with four other prospective running
mates _ Sens. John Glenn of Ohio, Lloyd Bentsen of Texas and Bob
Graham of Florida as well as Jesse Jackson, who had dinner with
Dukakis on Monday night. Dukakis also met last week with Georgia
Sen. Sam Nunn, who later said he wasn't interested being offered
the post.
   Before leaving Boston today, Jackson renewed his contention that
he would be the best choice.
   While Dukakis met with prospective running mates in Boston, the
man helping him with the search, campaign chairman Paul Brountas,
was in Washington for four days of meetings to seek advice on the
selection, the source said.
   Gore, Gephardt, Hamilton, Glenn, Bentsen, Graham and Jackson all
have been asked by the Dukakis campaign for detailed background and
financial information, according to sources.
   Jackson declared at a news conference today that he ``would be
an asset'' to the Democratic ticket and was more qualified than
others being considered for the No. 2 spot. He declined to say
whether he pushed for the offer during his Monday night discussions
with probable presidential nominee Dukakis nor whether he would
accept such an offer.
   He did say, however, ``I am convinced that my presence would
unleash more hope in this country, regain more people. The fact of
the matter is, I would be an asset.''
   Jackson left for New York after the news conference but left
behind aides for negotiations with the Dukakis campaign over
convention issues.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, was spending the day at the
Statehouse tending to state business in addition to the meetings
with Gore and Gephardt. At the top of his state agenda was
balancing the budget for the fiscal year that ended Thursday and at
the same time balancing the budget for the year that began Friday.
   He has said Jackson is receiving ``very serious consideration''
as his running mate, but has also said Jackson's position as
runner-up in the Democratic primaries entitles him to nothing more
than that.
   ``The others under consideration are unknown quantities beyond
their districts or beyond their home states,'' Jackson said today.
``I bring the sense of creativity, new history.''
   Jackson said he had a ``thoroughly enjoyable evening'' with
Dukakis and said their relationship ``has grown immensely.''
   He said he discussed the vice presidential nomination with
Dukakis and added that he came away from the meeting with the
impression that the governor had not yet made up his mind on a
running mate. He said they did not discuss other potential
candidates for the second spot on the ticket.
   Jackson said two weeks ago that he had decided whether he wanted
to be the party's candidate for vice president but has refused to
make his decision public.
   Dukakis, who was Jackson's host for the Independence Day meeting
and celebration, refused to be specific about their discussions.
   ``We were talking about lots of things,'' was all Dukakis had to
say Monday evening as he and Jackson emerged from Dukakis'
Brookline home and headed to the banks of the Charles River for the
traditional Boston Pops concert and fireworks.
   About the only thing Jackson was willing to discuss at that time
was the menu of clam chowder, poached salmon and peas and chocolate
torte. ``Balanced meal; well cooked,'' he said.
   Dukakis and his wife, Kitty, greeted Jackson and his wife,
Jacqueline, outside the governor's home, where a crowd of nearly
200 people was waiting.
   Arriving to rousing applause, Jackson led Mrs. Dukakis over to
the crowd and Dukakis followed with Mrs. Jackson. There were cheers
again when the couples emerged from the house 90 minutes later and
climbed into a van for the ride to the concert, where they sat in
the front row among an estimated 250,000 concert-goers.
</TEXT>
