<HEAD>Dukakis Meeting Veep Prospects</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 8 grafs with veep meetings scheduled, picking
up in 6th graf pvs, He left; cuts last 4 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis set face-to-face meetings toda
with three vice presidential prospects, including two former
rivals. George Bush was in Washington after saying on a campaign
trip he could ``identify with the dilemma faced by the captain'y and Wednesday'
of
the ship that shot down an Iranian airliner.
   Dukakis talked politics with Jesse Jackson over dinner Monday
night, but neither of them would say afterward whether anything was
settled concerning Jackson's claims on the No. 2 position. Jackson
renewed those claims in comments to reporters today.
   Sen. Albert Gore of Tennesee and Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri, both former presidential candidates who have endorsed
Dukakis since dropping out of the race, werfended during a Midwestern campaign
swing on Monday's July
Fourth holiday.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor who is the all-but-certain
Democratic nominee, was at the Statehouse today after playing host
to Jackson and his wife for dinner and the Boston fireworks display
Monday night.
   Jackson said today at a news conference in Boston, ``I am
convinced that my presence would unleash more hope in this country,
regain more people. The fact of the matter is, I would be an
asset.''
   He left for New York afations with the Dukakis campaign
over convention issues.
   Today, Jackson still wouldn't say whether he would accept the
vice presidential nomination, but he went to great lengths to
distinguish himself from others being considered.
   ``The others under consideration are unknown quantities beyond
their districts or beyond their home states,'' Jackson said. ``I
bring the sense of creativity, new history.''
   On Monday, both Bush and Dukakis said they were saddened by the
shooting down of an Iran Air Airbus over the Persian Gulf. All 290
aboard were killed, Iran said.
   Bush, who waited a day before speaking out on the incident, said
Monday at a stop in Elmwood Park, Ill., that he could ``identify
with the dilemma faced by the captain of the USS Vincennes.''
   The vessel's captain, Will Rogers III, told the Pentagon he
believed his ship was under attack by an Iranian warplane.
   The vice president, who was a World War II pilot, was asked how
the Navy cruiser's sophisticated radar equipment could have failed
to distinguish between the wide-bodied airliner and a small F-14
fighter, which was believed to be the target.
   ``Ever been in combat?'' Bush snapped. ``Combat is quite
ifferent than the laboratory.''
   He said he did not expect U.S. policy in the gulf to change as a
result of the incident. ``Life goes on,'' the vice president said.
   Bush made campaign stops outside Detroit and Chicago, and in St.
Louis before heading home to Washington Monday night. He had spent
the weekend at his summer home in Kennebunkport, Maine.
   The vice president was in Kennebunkport when word of the gulf
incident was relayed to Washington Sunday. He spoke with President
Reagan in a conference call that afternoon, spokeswoman Sheila Tate
said, and was meeting with the president today at the White House.
   Dukakis, in a Fourth of July speech at the Navy's oldest
commissioned warship _ the USS Constitution, berthed near Boston _
called for an end to the Iran-Iraq war.
   ``I believe that the United States must take the lead ... to
stop this war permanently,'' he said. Dukakis also warned Iran that
``this is no time for acts of terror or revenge in response to the
incident.''
   Jackson reacted to the incident by criticizing Reagan
administration policy in the Persian Gulf, calling it ``failed and
vague.'' He urged the president to promptly offer reparations to
the families of the victims.
   Reagan said Monday he would await the results of a Pentagon
investigation of the incident.
   Jackson also said there was ``no evidence'' that the Vincennes
was under attack at the time of the incident, and compared the
shooting down of the Iranian airliner to the Soviet downing of a
Korean Air Lines jetliner in 1983.
   Both Reagan and the Pentagon have said such comparisons are
unfair, because Sunday's incident occurred in a war zone, and
because the Navy repeatedly radioed warnings to the approaching
Iranian plane. Neither was the case in the KAL incident.
   ``When the KAL was shot down, we did not accept those arguments
as being valid, and most people in the world will not accept our
arguments to this point as being valid,'' Jackson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
