<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jane Fonda, who already has apologized
on national television for her 1972 trip to Hanoi, will appear with
Robert DeNiro at a benefit for children with birth defects linked
to the defoliant Agent Orange.
   Fonda and DeNiro star in the upcoming ``Union Street,'' which
will be partly filmed in Waterbury.
   The July 29 benefit will aid the Brandy Schieb Children's Fund,
a project of the Stamford-based Vietnam Veterans Victims of Agent
Orange Inc., said the Rev. John A. McColley, rector of St.
Michael's Episcopal Church in Naugatuck and a Vietnam veteran.
   The benefit ``grew out of the spirit of reconcilation and good''
inspired during a meeting in June between Fonda and a group of
veterans at St. Michael's on June 18, McColley said.
   ``Afterward, a lot of us were standing around saying wouldn't it
be great if now we could all do somthing together,'' he said.
   Fund-raising activities at the benefit may include a booth where
people can get their pictures taken with Fonda and DeNiro, said
Stephen Rivers, a Fonda spokesman.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Topol, star of film and stage versions of
``Fiddler On the Roof,'' said Tuesday he is stepping in to try to
revive enthusiasm for the musical ``Ziegfeld.''
   Topol, who does not use his surname, said he was first
approached 10 months ago to play the title role of Broadway
entrepreneur Florenz Ziegfeld.
   ``Then they (the management) kind of disappeared ... I didn't
know what was going on behind the scenes,'' said Topol, who is
contracted for at least three months from July 25.
   Director Joe Layton and the original star, Len Cariou, left the
production soon after the opening on April 26 to nearly unanimous
pans. Since then, actor-director Tommy Steele has been revising and
cutting the show, with understudy Marc Urquhart playing Ziegfeld.
   ``I hope I can create an entertaining show and that I can
contribute,'' Topol, 52, said. ``But we will wait and see if
congratulations are in order.''
   He will receive $37,400 a week pay, believed to be a near-record
for London's West End theater district.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ZAVALLA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aron Kay used to toss pies to make a
political point, but these days he's organizing protesters to pack
the party conventions.
   Kay says he's thrown pies at Phyllis Schafly, Gordon Liddy and
William F. Buckley.
   ``You remember the guy who years ago used to throw pies into
politicians' faces,'' Kay, 38, said over the weekend. ``That was
me.''
   Each pie, Kay said, was a statement about its ``victim.''
   Sen. Patrick Moynihan was hit with a mocha cream pie for
allegedly making a racist comment; Schlafly and Liddy got apple
pies because of their ``pro-American'' ideas; mushroom-tofu pie was
used on Edward Teller, H-bomb inventor, Kay said.
   ``The mushrooms symbolized mushroom clouds, and the tofu
symbolized life,'' he said.
   But Kay, 38, says his pie-throwing days are over. His latest
project is to mobilize caravans of protesters to go to the
Democratic and Republican national conventions this summer in
Atlanta and New Orleans.
   Kay is advocating the legalization of ``safe drugs'' such as
marijuana and protesting U.S. intervention in Central America.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HAMDEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the Joe Namath football camp, youngsters
get more than a cameo appearance from the former New York Jets
quarterback.
   When he started the camp 17 years ago with former teammate John
Dockery, ``that's one of the basic rules John and I agreed upon _
the two of us being here,'' Namath said.
   The majority of this year's campers, ages 8 to 18, never saw
Namath play. But their parents did, and that is one reason why
enrollment at the camp remains strong. Each of the two one-week
sessions draws 300 to 350 kids.
   ``He is like a Joe DiMaggio. People will never forget him. He'll
be locked in time,'' said Dockery.
   Namath, a member of the Pro Football Hall of Fame, continues to
do commercials and is a football analyst for NBC-TV.
   Besides teaching football, the camp stresses character, Namath
said.
   ``Football is not the top priority here. It's an important
priority but the overall picture is life in general. John and I
have talked about this, and I've learned this through football, you
don't do much on your own.''
</TEXT>
