<DOCNO> AP880705-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Airliner-Confusion Bjt   07-05 0870</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Confusion, Bjt,0892</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mix-ups With Airliners Have Occurred Before</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least two other mix-ups with civilian
planes by U.S. warships occurred in the Persian Gulf air corridor,
one of the world's busiest, before the USS Vincennes shot down an
Iranian airliner, American sources said Tuesday.
   All 290 people on the Airbus 300 were killed when the plane was
hit Sunday. A six-man team of U.S. experts led by an admiral
arrived Tuesday to begin a confidential investigation.
   Dozens of aircraft fly over the gulf each day, many on
long-distance flights between Europe and Asia with stops at Dubai,
Bahrain or Kuwait. The Iran Air jet was on a regularly scheduled
short hop across the Strait of Hormuz from Bandar Abbas to Dubai.
   U.S. officials have said the Vincennes fired two anti-aircraft
missiles at the plane in the mistaken belief it was an Iranian F-14
fighter. Iran says the Navy shot the plane down intentionally.
   A U.S. officer said privately he knew of an incident ``about a
month ago'' in which an airliner thought an American warship was
trying to order it to change course when the ship was talking by
radio to a different plane.
   ``The problem was bleed-over from one frequency to another,
which sometimes happens because of harmonics,'' he said. ``The ship
was trying to determine the position and identity of an aircraft, a
non-commercial plane, and this other aircraft heard it and thought
the ship was talking to it.''
   He would not reveal the ship involved, but said he was unaware
of any incident involving the Vincennes. The officer said he did
not know what airline owned the jet involved.
   About 16 U.S. warships are in the gulf at a given time. People
on the bridge of one last month counted the lights of about 20
high-flying aircraft in an hour.
   Another U.S. military source described an incident in mid-June
in which a U.S. missile frigate, making its first trip into the
gulf through the Strait of Hormuz, briefly locked its weapons radar
on an airliner, but quickly realized the mistake.
   ``The best explanation for something like that is
inexperience,'' said the informant, who also insisted his name not
be used.
   ``These crews are always nervous when they come into the gulf
for the first time,'' he said. ``They know it's a war zone, but
they don't know exactly what to expect. And one thing they don't
seem to get the word on is how much commercial air traffic there is
out here.''
   The Washington Post said Tuesday the Vincennes, which arrived in
the gulf May 27, figured in an incident last month in which it
``attempted to redirect'' a jetliner in a way that caused United
Arab Emirates officials to fear a collision of two commercial
planes.
   Quoting an air traffic control official in the Emirates it did
not identify, the paper said the incident June 8 resulted in an
official protest to the U.S. Embassy in Abu Dhabi. It said the
embassy declined comment.
   The officer who said he had no reports of incidents involving
the Vincennes added: ``If it had happened, I would know about it.''
   U.S. Navy spokesmen refused comment on all the reports.
   American military sources said the investigating team had an
initial 15-day mandate but would remain ``as long as it takes to
find out what happened.'' They said the members would work in total
secrecy and make no public statements.
   ``They're going behind closed doors and stay there,'' said a
U.S. Navy spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Leading the investigation is Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty, who
once commanded the battleship New Jersey and now is plans and
policy director at U.S. Central Command in Tampa, Fla.,
administrative headquarters for U.S. military affairs in 19
countries of the Middle East and North Africa.
   A lawyer and technical specialists, all military officers, also
are on the team. One member is an expert on the ``Aegis'' system of
computer-linked radar and weapons aboard the Vincennes.
   Navy spokesmen said the itinerary was ``not yet set up,'' but
other officials said investigators would visit the Vincennes and
interview Capt. Will C. Rogers III and other officers under oath.
   Rogers, who has commanded the Vincennes for more than a year,
was reported by Pentagon sources to have told his superiors he
acted ``to defend my ship and my crew'' and would do it the same
again in the same circumstances.
   ``This is a burden that I will carry the rest of my life. ... I
alone am responsible,'' he said, according to the Washington
reports.
   Airborne observers said ship traffic in the southern gulf
appeared normal Tuesday and a convoy of U.S.-flagged tankers was
sighted off Ras al-Khaimah in the Emirates, heading for Hormuz.
   It included a Kuwaiti tanker with U.S. registration, the
81,283-ton Sea Isle City; the Navy-chartered tanker Patriot and the
missile frigate Robert G. Bradley, Associated Press photographer
Greg English reported. Eleven Kuwaiti tankers have U.S.
registration and the Navy has escorted them since last July.
   Other traffic included two three-ship groups of Japanese
tankers, one moving in each direction, and a Greek tanker sailing
parallel to the U.S. convoy.
</TEXT>
