<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Airliner, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0582,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Lodges U.N. Protest Over Attack On Airliner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner-Gulf, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs, Iran calls for Security Council meeting,
new quotes. Picks up 2nd graf pvs ``In a letter... ''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's U.N. ambassador called today for an
urgent meeting of the Security Council to condemn the United States
for shooting down an Iranian passenger jet.
   Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati also told a news
conference that contrary to assertions of U.S. officials, the
Iranian Airbus, with 290 people aboard, was sending out ``normal
signals ... to all radar that it was a civilian plane.''
   Mahallati said an apology from the United States ``cannot wash
away the blood,'' but said the Reagan administration should
apologize, withdraw immediately from the Persian Gulf and take a
neutral stand in the Iran-Iraq war.
   He said he met today with Security Council President Paulo
Nogueira-Batista of Brazil and requested an urgent meeting of the
council on Sunday's attack on the jetliner by the U.S. missile
cruiser Vincennes.
   The United States says the ship's commander mistakenly believed
the civilian aircraft was an F-14 jet fighter preparing to attack
his ship. President Reagan says the United States will not withdraw
from the gulf.
   Mahallati said the Security Council should call on the United
States to immediately withdraw its forces from the Persian Gulf
``to terminate this kind of barbarism.''
   He denounced the disaster as ``premeditated'' action by the
United States and condemned the ``awkward logic in the U.S. coverup
story about mistaken identity.''
   Mahallati said Iranian military officials told him that ``the
plane for... 14 minutes ... was disseminating the normal signals of
all civilian planes have which proves to any radar that this is a
civilian plane.''
   ``The question is how the most sophisticated American warship in
the Persian Gulf could not receive it,'' he said.
   The Iranian envoy said that the attack on the airliner would not
affect Iran's efforts to improve its relations with other
countries. ``We don't mix our relations with one country and
another, they are independent,'' he said.
   Earlier today, Iran formally demanded that the United Nations
condemn the United States for shooting down the Iran Air jetliner.
   In a letter lodging a formal protest with the world body,
Foreign Minister Ali-Akbar Velayati of Iran said the United Nations
should ``condemn this barbaric massacre of innocent civilian
passengers and take immediate measures to prevent further
occurrence of such carnage.''
   The letter, dated Monday and distributed today, said, ``This is
only possible through compelling the United States to remove its
expansionist naval forces from the Persian Gulf.''
   It said Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar immediately
should organize an investigation ``on the extent of this latest
American atrocity.''
   On Monday, Perez de Cuellar issued a statement in Geneva, saying
he ``cannot but condemn what appears to have been a tragic error''
and called ``for the greatest restraint in this difficult moment
for the peace and security of the region.
   ``The question of responsibility should not be ignored if a
repetition of such a tragedy is to be avoided,'' he said.
   He said he would continue his efforts to implement a Security
Council resolution that demands an immediate cease-fire in the
nearly 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
   The Iranian letter said the aircraft, on a scheduled flight from
the southern Iranian city of Bandar Abbas to Dubai in the United
Arab Emirates, was in the ``routine corridor used by civilian
airliners.''
   Iran, it said, repeatedly has protested ``the dangers of the
provocative, illegitimate and expansionist American presence in the
Persian Gulf and repeated acts of aggression against the
sovereignty of Iran.''
   In pursing its aggressive policy, the Iranian minister said,
``the United States has no shame in even targeting civilian
airliners and massacring its passengers in cold blood.''
</TEXT>
