<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GarveyLandmark     07-05 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Garvey Landmark,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcus Garvey Landmark In Peril</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An old mansion that was once the headquarters
of the Cleveland chapter of the Universal Negro Improvement
Association will be razed unless $300,000 can be raised soon to
save it, officials say.
   The building is one of the most visible legacies in Cleveland of
Marcus Garvey, the black nationalist who ran an international
shipping line in the 1920s.
   The 106-year-old mansion became vacant in 1982 when UNIA members
could no longer afford to pay utilities and other expenses.
   The Cleveland chapter, which once had thousands of members, now
draws fewer than 10 members at monthly meetings, one reason local
politicians feel no urgency to help Mason A. Hargrave, UNIA's
national president, save the building.
   Cleveland's Board of Building Standards wants to demolish the
building because it is a safety hazard and an eyesore. Arsonists
keep setting it on fire, and vandals have hit several times.
   Hargrave has appealed three rulings from the Board of Building
Standards placing the mansion on demolition lists. Each time he has
won a 120-day reprieve to come up with money to renovate the
building.
   The mansion is on the National Register of Historic places, but
city officials say they cannot wait for Cleveland's UNIA chapter to
raise $300,000 needed to restore the mansion.
   ``The building is not scheduled for demolition yet,'' said
Damian Borkowski, assistant administrator of the city bureau of
demolition. ``Building Standards is holding a meeting next week and
could rule on Mr. Hargrave's appeal.''
   Hargrave said he believes Cleveland owes UNIA a commitment to
save the mansion because of the work the group has done over the
years, including free lunches and tutoring for school children,
both of which were popular UNIA programs before the organization
fell on hard times.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
