<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrashSettlements     07-05 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash Settlements,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gander Crash Settlements Average $663,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Out-of-court settlements to survivors of
57 soldiers killed in a 1985 Arrow Air crash have averaged nearly
twice the amount paid in major airline crashes from 1970 to 1984,
The Courier-Journal reported Tuesday.
   The newspaper examined cases settled since January 1987 and said
the Arrow Air cases were settled for an average of $663,000,
ranging from $171,000 to $1.5 million.
   The litigation arose from a Dec. 12, 1985, crash at Gander,
Newfoundland, that killed all eight crew members and 248 troops on
board. The soldiers, members of the 101st Airborne Division, were
returning to Fort Campbell after six months in the Middle East.
   All 130 lawsuits filed in U.S. District Court for western
Kentucky have been settled, and one case, in Florida, is pending
for trial.
   Citing a court order and other reasons, Arrow's insurer has
declined to disclose the value of settlements. But the newspaper
calculated the size of some accords based on contributions by
plaintiffs' lawyers to a fund that covers litigation expenses.
Since Jan. 12, 1987, the lawyers have been required to place 0.5
percent of settlements in the fund.
   An extrapolation of those figures shows that since that date,
Arrow's insurer, Associated Aviation Underwriters, paid $37.8
million to settle the 57 cases, the newspaper said.
   John Martin, Associated Aviation Underwriters' attorney,
confirmed the settlement values calculated by the newspaper.
   Geneva Parris, liaison counsel for the plaintiffs, also
confirmed the figures. She said the accords struck after January
1987 were generally higher than those reached before then.
   A Rand Corp. study found an average of $362,943 was paid for
passengers killed in major airline crashes from 1970 to 1984.
Although that average has risen dramatically in the 1980s, the
Arrow settlements still exceed the $500,000 figure the National Law
Journal has reported was paid from 1980 to 1984.
   Martin said the Arrow settlements are generally in line with
those negotiated after other recent airline disasters.
   But plaintiffs' lawyers, including Richard Brown, a partner of
San Francisco's Melvin Belli and secretary of the aviation section
of the Association of Trial Lawyers of America, say the Arrow
awards exceed recent averages.
   Lee Kreindler, a leading aviation lawyer, said the settlements
are noteworthy because the Arrow passengers were soldiers with
lower earning potential than many other victims of air disasters
such as business executives.
   Members of the plaintiffs' team attributed the relatively large
Arrow settlements to the generosity of Associated and to a Kentucky
law that allows for liberal recovery of future earnings.
</TEXT>
