<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Bases     07-05 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Bases,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Begin Review Of U.S. Bases Labor Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Philippine officials Tuesday
began a review of the labor agreement covering six American bases,
whose closure would directly affect about 68,000 Filipino workers.
   The bases are the second-largest employer in the Philippines
after the government.
   The review of the Base Labor Agreement is to determine the wages
and rights of Filipino workers on the U.S.-run Clark Air Base,
Subic Bay Naval Base and four other smaller facilities in the
Philippines.
   In April, officials from both sides began an overall
re-examination of the 1947 agreement, which allows the United
States to operate the six military bases in the Phillipines and
expires in 1991. The officials agreed to discuss the labor issue in
a separate review.
   ``The future of the facilities in the Philippines is
uncertain,'' U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt said at opening
ceremonies to Tuesday's session. ``There are many, in both
countries, who believe the facilities should be removed. This will
have a direct impact on each worker, his family, and his
community.''
   The panel is expected to demand higher wages, the right of
workers to strike and bargain collectively, and the application of
Philippine labor laws to the Filipino workers in the bases, sources
at the Department of Foreign Affairs said.
   U.S. negotiators are expected to oppose the demands, citing a
provision in the agreement that allows Washington ``unhampered
operations'' in the bases.
   The United States Information Service says the six bases employ
68,514 Filipinos, for a total annual salary of about $96 million.
   The Manila government receives about $180 million annually in
military and economic aid from Washington in exchange for the use
of the bases. But Philippine negotiators are asking the United
States to increase the aid package for the remaining three years of
the agreement.
   Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus, who heads the Philippine
panel, said before the talks that $1.2 billion annually would be a
``realistic'' increase.
</TEXT>
