<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SexDiscrimination     07-05 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sex Discrimination,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Club To Pay Denied Female Applicant Damages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gun club must pay a woman $100 in damages for
denying her membership application in 1980 and admit her as a full
member, the Massachusetts Supreme Court ruled Tuesday.
   The Concord Rod and Gun Club Inc. had appealed a Massachusetts
Commission Against Discrimination order, affirmed by a lower court,
that Donna Page was unconstitionally excluded from the all-male
club.
   The club argued that it was not ``public'' under the definition
of state anti-discrimination laws.
   Membership in the club was limited to 300 people, 70 percent of
whom lived in or around Concord. Applicants had to be at least 21
years old or have parental permission to join, had to be eligible
for a state sporting license and, at least at the time Page applied
for membership, had to be male.
   However, the justices wrote there were no other stated
restrictions on eligibility, and noted a commission conclusion that
``obtaining sponsorship and co-sponsorship was easy to do and was
tantamount to acceptance of an applicant as a member of the club.''
   Every one of the 52 male applicants in 1980 _ the year Page
applied _ and 1981 were accepted, the court said.
   ``While it is true that several factors tend to show that the
club is not open to, and does not accept, the patronage of the
general public, the determinative factor in this case ... is the
total absense of genuine selectivity of membership,'' the justices
said in a unanimous decision by Justice Francis P. O'Connor.
</TEXT>
