<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LemonadeRobbery     07-05 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lemonade Robbery,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thief Takes Earnings From Girls' Stand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thief stole the profits from two girls'
lemonade stand, but one victim was prepared with an insurance
policy of sorts.
   ``My mom and dad are going to give me the $13 I had earned,''
said 11-year-old Heather Rahhal.
   Heather and her friend, 13-year-old Hanna Kemp, have sold
lemonade and iced tea at the fireworks display on the Arkansas
River for the past six years.
   ``They do real well,'' said Bonnie Rahhal, Heather's mom. ``It's
always been a pleasurable experience. This year they cried and
thought it seemed real unfair.''
   Sgt. John Bowman said three boys about 16 or 17 years old
approached the girls about 11 p.m. Monday and one ran off with a
cigar box containing the $26.
   ``Both dads tried to pursue but lost him,'' Mrs. Rahhal said.
   ``It just seems like a crummy thing to do,'' the mother added.
``It takes them about two or three days of work.''
</TEXT>
