<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Spence-Marriage     07-05 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spence-Marriage,0187</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Congressman Spence Marries in Mississippi Hospital Room</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., recovering from
a double-lung transplant, celebrated the Fourth of July weekend by
getting married in his room at the University of Mississippi
Medical Center.
   A spokesman for Spence said Tuesday that he married Deborah
Williams of Lexington in a private ceremony Sunday in Jackson, Miss.
   The 60-year-old Spence had the lung transplant in May. Hospital
spokeswoman Barbara Austin said Tuesday that Spence is continuing
to progress and is in satisfactory condition.
   ``He's been looking forward to the marriage since before the
surgery, it's one of the things he's been anxious to do,'' said
Randy Mashburn, a spokesman for the congressman.
   ``Barring any unforeseen circumstances, we're looking for
(Spence) to be discharged within 10 days to two weeks,'' said
Mashburn.
   ``He's about to come out of the hospital and get back to work
and back to Washington. He'll worry about getting back on the
campaign trail later,'' he said.
   This is the first marriage for Mrs. Spence, 37. Spence's first
wife died in 1977.
