<1ST_LINE>u a PM-People-Cuomo 1stLd-Writethru a0466 07-05 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Cuomo, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Covers Story As Rookie Reporter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Cuomo covering event.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMESTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo, notebook and tape
recorder in hage _ one elite, well-to-do and often associated with
government officials, the other poor and struggling.
   This city, long regarded as a pioneer for black progress and a
center for nearly every aspect of black culture and politics, is
faced with a deteroriating relationship between the two classes of
blacks.
   One source of the problem is that blacks do not control the
economic pursestrings in Atlanta, even though they hold top
political offices, according to Lyndon Wade, executive director of
the Atlanta Urban League.
   ``You cannot run a city with politics alone; you must have an
economic base to make it go. That's why there's a lot of pressure
in the older black community,'' said Wade.
   Tensions between the two classes begin early, according to
Morehouse College sociologist Anna Grant. In school, poor children
start to understand that some of their black classmates enjoy
material advantages inaccessible to them. Since the city's elected
black officials usually are among the elite, the poor come to view
government and the elite as one.
   Poor blacks feel especially betrayed at slights from a black
administration, said Mrs. Grant. And in May their mistrust showed
at the ballot box, when voters overwhelmingly defeated a $308
million proposal for improving roads, schools, police protection
and other major services.
   Elected black leaders who had heavily promoted the bond issue in
their own circles denounced the vote at a black-tie ``victory''
party. However, another group of black officials, who had pushed
for rejection in the city's poorer areas, celebrated with
cornbread, pig neckbones and Sprite.
   ``This is a new political day in Atlanta,'' shouted maverick
City Councilman Hosea Williams. ``This is the death of black elite
control of Atlanta.''
   Atlanta homeowners, already chafed by a sudden reassessment that
raised property taxes for thousands, said they voted against the
plan because they weren't told exactly where the $308 million would
go.
   The election was a slap in the face to members of the black
elite long accustomed to controlling the black vote, according to
Mrs. Grant, who said the message was: ``They can't assume that they
speak for all blacks.''
   Atlanta's black leadership had put forth a united front in 1972
to support Maynard Jackson's successful bid to become the city's
first black mayor. Two years later, disputes began to divide the
old guard of business and civic leaders and a newer class of young
professionals.
   Jackson's administration weathered a police cheating scandal,
the serial murders of young blacks and a crime rate that soared
each year, giving the city a national reputation for lawlessness.
These problems ravaged the black community, and by the end of the
Jackson administration poorer communities were accusing him of not
seeking solutions.
   History has repeated itself.
   The young professionals of the 1970s are now being lumped with
the old elite by young professionals of the 1980s, most of whom
migrated from other areas to create their own brand of Atlantan,
said Mrs. Grant, who advised Jackson on annexation issues.
   Those of the new group who live in the city now chide Mayor
Andrew Young about his globe-trotting and lack of attention to
municipal issues.
   His administration has endured a grand jury probe of the way
police handled charges of cocaine use among prominent blacks, a
series of police shootings of poor blacks and the extortion
convictions of two black Fulton County commissioners. Now the poor
accuse Young of a lack of concern for the disadvantaged.
   ``They were handed the same promises before blacks came to
power. But they expected blacks to keep their promises,'' Mrs.
Grant said. ``There's a struggle for greater accountability. It's
making people ask `Are we better off because we have blacks in
power positions? Or are we no better off?'''
   Wade, of the Urban League, said the city's blacks aren't helped
when suburban financial interests that wield economic control tout
the city as one with good race relations and a thriving black
community.
   Atlanta's glowing reputation as a New South capital brought
346,000 new jobs, $15 billion in new investments and 78,000 people
to the metropolitan area in 1987.
   However, newly arrived blacks find a confusing blend of Atlanta
_ the metro area, where 1980 census figures show 25 percent of 2.1
million residents are black, and the city itself, where the census
showed 67 percent of 430,500 residents are black and 27.5 percent
of residents live below the poverty line.
   ``It's not the case that all Atlanta blacks live good,'' Wade
said. ``Atlanta is very deceptive. Name three buildings over two
stories high that are owned by blacks. Yes, Atlanta has a long
history of blacks being involved in the core life of the city. But
when you talk about are we truly, truly making the kind of progress
that one would expect, then I would have to say the answer is no.''
   Still, he said, ``a lot of people get caught up in the potential
for change and the potential for great things. That keeps everybody
here.''
</TEXT>
