<1ST_LINE>r i AM-People-Kasparov     07-05 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Kasparov,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chess Champion Troubled by Ethnic Dispute In Azerbaijan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFORT, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World chess champion Garri Kasparov said
Tuesday he was troubled by the ethnic problems in his home republic
of Azerbaijan, and that they have been simmering under the surface
there for 20 years.
   Kasparov also said Mikhail S. Gorbachev has ``played
brilliantly'' in setting his reform programs in motion, and said
that if chess terms were applied to politicians, the Soviet leader
would be rated a grandmaster.
   Kasparov, who is half Armenian but lives in Baku, the capital of
Azerbaijan, says he is ``always trying to find a compromise, an
acceptable solution for both sides'' in the dispute between
Armenians and Azerbaijanis.
   Armenians are predominantly Christian and have clashed with
Azerbaijanis, who are mostly Shiite Moslem. The Armenians demand
that the region of Nagorno-Karabakh in Azerbaijan be annexed to
Armenia.
   Speaking in English, the 25-year-old chess champion said the
regional dispute was ``a real problem for 20 years,'' but had been
kept ``underground'' until recently.
   He suggested one acceptable solution might be to ``give the
biggest posible autonomy for Nagorno-Kabarakh within Azerbaijan.''
   He said allowing the region to secede could be seen by Soviet
authorities as too dangerous since similar problems exist in Soviet
Central Asia, the Baltic republics and western Ukraine.
   Kasparov, in an interview with The Associated Press following
his victory in the World Cup chess tournament that ended Monday,
said he kept up with events from the national Communist Party
conference in Moscow by telephoning the capital and listening over
the receiver to speeches from the meeting that were broadcast on
Soviet TV.
   Kasparov said many people in Moscow are ill-informed about the
the southern republics.
   ``It's another world,'' he said. ``How can you understand people
in Rio de Janeiro when you are living in New York?''
   Kasparov denounced the violence committed by Azerbaijani mobs
against Armenians in the coastal city of Sumgait on Feb. 28. At
least 32 people were killed, mostly Armenians. One rioter was
sentenced on May 16 to 15 years in prison and others are expected
to be tried on charges stemming from the riots.
   ``Sumgait was a big criminal event, maybe one of the biggest in
our history,'' Kasparov said, adding that he supported the
punishment of those involved in the violence.
   Gorbachev, in a speech at the beginning of the conference,
denounced demands for border changes in Armenia and Azerbaijan.
</TEXT>
