<1ST_LINE>u a PM-OrangeJuice-Poison 1stLd-Writethru a0532dworldtitlelastsummeratRomeInOrangeJuiceCartonWithThreateningNote
07-05 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Orange Juice-Poison, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0532,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lab Test Finds No Poison In Orange Juice Carton With Threatening
Note</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with no poison found in juice and no
syringe found in carton. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laboratory tests found no poison in an orange
juice carton on which a note was pinned with an intravenous drug
needle threatening contamination, officials said today.
   The discovery of the 64-ounce carton in a Woodland Hills
supermarket on Monday prompted company officials to pull the Vons
store's supply of the product, said Vons spokeswoman Mary McAboy.
However, no other stores will take the product off its shelves
while the investigation continues.
   ``We believe it to be an isolated incident,'' said Ms. McAboy.
``There was no indication of anything like this in any other
store.''
   No injuries were reported after a customer alerted store
officials about 2 p.m. Monday of the carton, said Lt. Lee Lorenze.
   ``The note threatened contamination,'' Ms. McAboy said.
Authorities refused to release its exact wording.
   Earlier police reports that a syringe was in the carton were
incorrect, she said.
   The store voluntarily pulled the orange juice and hired a
company to conduct a preliminary test of the product with the note,
Ms. McAboy said.
   Although the preliminary test indicated poison might be present,
a more thorough test found no contamination, she said.
</TEXT>
