<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--TeenShocked     07-05 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Teen Shocked,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Burned by 11,000 Volts While Playing Atop Parked Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drunken teen-ager was critically injured when
he struck an overhead electric cable while playing atop a parked
Long Island Rail Road train in Penn Station, a spokesman said
Tuesday.
   LIRR spokesman Grian Dolan said 11,000 volts of electricity shot
through Humerto E. Diaz's body, setting his clothes on fire.
   Diaz's friend, John Zokowski, suffered minor burns to his hands
while pulling his friend from the train's roof and trying to
extinguish the fire.
   ``We really haven't been able to talk to Diaz at great length so
we don't know what led him to climb on top of the roof,'' Dolan
said. ``But blood tests from the hospital show he had consumed an
awful lot of alcohol.''
   Both teen-agers, who live in suburban Port Washington, were
taken to New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center's burn unit.
   Diaz was in critical condition with second and third-degree
burns over 40 percent of his body, said hospital spokesman Jonathan
Weil. Zokowski was in stable condition with first-degree burns on
his hands.
