<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DWI-Rights     07-05 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DWI-Rights,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge To Decide Whether Alcoholics Anonymous Violates Religious
Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CENTREVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An atheist who was convicted of drunken
driving claims that his constitutional rights were violated when he
was ordered to attend meetings of Alcoholics Anonymous.
   AA's reference to ``a higher spirit'' and ``spiritual
fellowship'' during meetings is at the heart of the dispute.
   John Norfolk, 47, contends that being forced to attend AA
meetings violates his rights under the First Amendment, which says
that ``Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of
religion, or prohbiting the free exercise thereof.''
   Queen Anne's County District Judge John T. Clark had given
Norfolk the choice of attending AA meetings once a week as part of
his probation from his conviction or spending 20 days in jail.
   The American Civil Liberties Union, which is representing
Norfolk, maintains the meetings preach religious healing and the
state can't force anyone to to attend a religious gathering. The
group has asked Clark to review the sentence.
   Ellen Luff, Norfolk's attorney, said, ``We are not attacking AA
at all. What we're saying is that the state has no right to send
someone who is an atheist to a theist meeting.''
   ``They don't talk about drinking. They talk about God 50 percent
of the time,'' said Norfolk. ``I might as well be going to church
on Sundays or listening to Jimmy Swaggart.''
   However, Myrna McCusker, clinical supervisor at the alcohol
services division of the county health department, said the program
is not religious. Having gone through the program herself, she
said, ``AA is what works best for most people. I tried everything
else but nothing worked.''
   McCusker said she complained about the reference to God at AA
meetings 15 years ago when she went for treatment and ``it allowed
me to keep on drinking.''
   Stuart Comstock-Gay, ACLU director in Maryland, said there have
been a few cases in Maryland where the AA treatment program has
been challenged in lower courts and the judge has ordered the
driver to attend an alternative program. ``That's what we're hoping
the judge will do in this case,'' he said.
   Clark, who is expected to rule sometime this month on the case,
said he was not aware of any religious references at the meetings.
   Annette Rentz, coordinator of the state Alcohol and Drug Abuse
Administration treatment program, said AA was not religious. ``It
is a support group that works and is effective,'' she said.
   ``We're in the process of reducing the problem of drunk driving.
This would definitely be a setback.'' said Ms. Rentz. She said some
10,200 motorists convicted of drunk driving who were treated in
state outpatient programs last year were required to attend AA
meetings as part of their probation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
