<DOCNO> AP880705-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1438EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Presser     07-05 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presser,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters Leader In Fair Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKEWOOD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters president Jackie Presser was
reported in fair condition Tuesday at Lakewood Hospital, where he
will undergo physical and respiratory therapy during the next few
days.
   Presser, 61, who is suffering from brain tumors, was rushed to
the hospital by ambulance June 28 complaining of dizziness and
weakness. The symptoms were caused by a blood clot that reached
Presser's right lung, physicians say.
   Doctors said last week that the clot had stabilized and should
eventually dissolve. A screen was implanted in a vein below
Presser's kidneys last week to block additional blood clots from
moving to his lungs, the hospital said.
   Presser was hospitalized just hours after the U.S. government
filed a lawsuit in New York to break alleged Mafia domination of
the 1.6-million member Teamsters, the nation's largest labor union.
   On May 4, Presser relinquished his duties as union president for
four months because of poor health. Teamsters Secretary-Treasurer
Weldon L. Mathis has assumed those duties.
   Presser had been scheduled to go on trial July 12 in Cleveland
on federal charges of embezzlement and racketeering. Because of his
health problems, a federal judge postponed the trial indefinitely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
