<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Newsstands Bjt   07-05 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newsstands, Bjt,0658</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Extra! Extra! City Spars with Newsies!
^By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For generations, New Yorkers have relied on the
sidewalk newsstand for daily doses of truth (``BLAZE KILLS 5
FIREMEN''), beauty (``BEAUTY SECRETS FROM A TOP MODEL!'') and
street smarts.
   Vito Gasparo has been dispensing all three from the corner of
47th Street and Sixth Avenue for 41 years, and right now his street
smarts tell him that Mayor Edward I. Koch is ``crazy in the head.''
   Gasparo's concern for the mayor's sanity stems from a Koch
administration proposal that could put as many as 80 percent of the
city's newsstands out of business.
   The proposal would change the requirements for newsstands so
that they would have to be, for example, at least 25 feet from the
nearest subway entrance and two feet from a curb, manhole, parking
meter or telephone pole.
   City planners say the newsstands block pedestrian traffic and
contribute to congestion on the sidewalks _ a charge that few would
dispute.
   ``We're concerned if a newsstand blocks the free egress of a
crosswalk,'' explained Victor Ross, a city Transportation
Department spokesman. ``We're also concerned if the stand so
constricts space that people don't have anyplace to walk on the
sidewalk.''
   A casual inspection of Manhattan newsstands suggests that few
could comply with the new rules.
   ``The impact would be incredibly disastrous on what is left of
the newsstand industry in this city,'' said Robert S. Bookman, a
lawyer who represents the New York City Newsstand Operators
Association.
   New York's 280 or so newsstands dispense more than a sometimes
staggering selection of newspapers and magazines. Many also sell
candy, sodas, maps, baseball caps or cheap jewelry.
   Newsstand operators give directions to tourists, provide a
comforting beacon of light on dark streets and, some people
believe, help deter crime.
   Once, newsstands were the exclusive province of the blind and
disabled military veterans; recently, their ranks have been joined
by immigrants, particularly from India, Pakistan and Bangladesh.
   ``What're they gonna do, put these people back on welfare?''
asked Tom DeSanto, an optician who is a regular customer at a Sixth
Avenue newsstand operated by Edward Lanigan, who is blind.
   Another blind newsstand operator lost his stand in Brooklyn last
week when city sanitation crews mistakenly razed it. Although Koch
publicly apologized and the man was given a replacement, the case
helped focus attention on the city's newsstand campaign.
   The more cynical of Koch's critics see political motives in the
plan.
   ``I am particularly outraged that these new and onerous
regulations ... come at a time when the complexion of those who own
the newsstands in this city is changing,'' said Wilbert Tatum,
publisher of the city's largest black newspaper, the Amsterdam
News. Tatum said the elimination of newsstands would ``decimate''
his profits, which are heavily based on street sales.
   The free-standing sidewalk stands, which range from shabby to
seedily ornate, represent only a fraction of the news outlets in
the city. Stan Getleson, circulation manager of the New York Post,
said Tuesday, that there are about 4,500 sellers including stands
in the subways, cubbyholes in buildings, lobby newsstands and
bookstores.
   Still, the newsstands have adamant defenders.
   ``The only legal thing on the streets seems to be the
newsstands, so it is naturally the newsstands that the city is
attempting to curb,'' wrote New York Daily News columnist Gail
Collins.
   City officials seem slightly taken aback.
   ``The mayor has by no means accepted'' the regulations, mayoral
spokesman Larry Simonberg said, adding that Koch had no intention
of eliminating newsstands.
   ``They might have to move,'' Simonberg insisted, ``but we are
not seeking to oust anybody.''
   And if, as Bookman suggested, the regulations would outlaw 80
percent of the city's newsstands?
   ``I don't believe any such thing would be acceptable,''
Simonberg said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
