<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WestfieldState     07-05 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Westfield State,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College President Repays School for Questionable Expenses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Westfield State College
has reportedly repaid the school $1,259 for meals with educators
who don't recall dining with him, dinners with professors who don't
exist and other expenses.
   State records obtained by the Union-News newspaper of
Springfield indicate that Irving Buchen also billed the school at
least $1,200 in travel expenses for his wife, Devy, saying she
often participated in conferences he attends.
   The records, however, showed no registration fees for Mrs.
Buchen, an opera singer, according to the account published Tuesday.
   Buchen said through his secretary Tuesday that he would have no
comment on the report, but he told the newspaper: ``I never
deliberately misled anyone.''
   A spokesman for the state Board of Regents, which hired Buchen
to replace a president who resigned in a scandal, said Chairman
Edward Lash and Chancellor Franklyn Jenifer would ``be in touch
with the trustees'' of the college.
   He added that the regents have no legal authority over how
public college presidents spend school trust funds. Under state
law, the presidents are free to draw on the funds for any purpose
that promotes the school.
   ``Clearly we're concerned about this issue,'' said regents
spokesman Terry Zoulas.
   The head of Westfield State's board of trustees, Jane Berry, was
at meetings Tuesday and her secretary said she could not be reached
for comment. Ms. Berry has said, however, that trustees ``had
questions about whether some of Dr. Buchen's expenses were
legitimate.''
   Buchen, 57, earns $77,000 yearly and receives $1,000 monthly in
living expenses. He became president 15 months ago, replacing
Francis J. Pilecki, who resigned after being indicted in 1986 on
sexual assault charges. Pilecki was found innocent in one case
brought by a male student and charges were dropped in another case
after settlement of a civil suit.
   Among the questionable expenses cited was a $26 business meal
with Helen Popovitch, president of Florida Atlantic University, who
told the newspaper she never dined with Buchen. He later said he
had made a bookkeeping error.
   Two other college presidents listed on meal vouchers totaling
$76 _ Harold Eichoff of Trenton State College in New Jersey and
John Van de Wetering of the State University of New York at
Brockport _ also didn't recall dining with Buchen.
   Buchen said the bills were actually for dinners with his wife
that he considered legitimate business expenses.
   Buchen was praised in a preliminary report issued last month by
the New England Association of Schools and Colleges for helping
Westfield State recover from the trauma suffered by the Pilecki
allegations, but he has also come under fire for using $16,000 in
trust funds to renovate his office.
   In January, he acknowledged that he waived the college's
entrance requirements to allow his 16-year-old daughter to enroll
as a student, but later took her out of the school and apologized
to trustees.
</TEXT>
