<HEAD>Police Chief Killed; Two Suspects Caught</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `Authorities in ..., with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with suspects' names, details of shooting. Picks up in 6th graf,
`Troopers recovered ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CLAREMONT, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The police chief of this small city in
southeastern Minnesota was shot and killed early today, and two
suspects were arrested later in Missouri, authorities said.
   Police Chief Gregory Lange was dead on arrival at St. Marys
Hospital in Rochester at 3:30 a.m., Olmsted County Coroner Kathryn
Berg said.
   Authorities declined to comment in detail this morning on the
circumstances of the shooting as they cordoned off a city block
near Lange's home in Claremont, a city of about 600 about 25 miles
west of Rochester.
   The suspects were arrested without incident on Interstate 35 in
Clinton County, Mo., about 300 miles from the Minnesota city, said
Trooper Londell Jamerson with the Missouri Highway Patrol.
   Missouri Patrol Sgt. William Monahan identified the suspects as
Andrew Salinas and Robert Salinas, adding he didn't know whether
they were related.
   Monahan said Lange responded to a report of a domestic dispute
at the home of Andrew Salinas and his wife and that the two men
scuffled briefly before the chief was shot once in the chest. The
body of the chief, he said, was found outside the Salinas home,
about 50 yards away from his own house.
   Troopers recovered a handgun and what appeared to be a police
radio from the car, Jamerson said. Earlier, Lange's patrol car was
found in Blooming Prairie, about 10 miles south of Claremont, said
Major Richard Steffen of the Minnesota State Patrol.
   Lange, police chief since January 1986, admitted last October to
stealing most of his grandmother's estate, forcing her to mortgage
a farm to pay her nursing home bills, according to Iowa officials.
Lange pleaded guilty to first-degree theft last month and was to be
sentenced July 25, County Attorney Bruce Green of O'Brien County
said.
   Lange admitted that he took more than $60,000 from the woman's
account for his own use, Green said.
   The police chief faced up to 10 years in prison and a $10,000
fine. Green said he had planned to make no sentencing
recommendation because the other beneficiaries of the woman's
estate asked that Lange not be prosecuted.
