<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeacherReinstated     07-05 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher Reinstated,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Wins Nine-Year Battle in TB Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher fired nine years ago because
she had tuberculosis has been ordered reinstated by a federal judge
who found that she was a victim of discrimination, her attorney
said Tuesday.
   The lawsuit of Gene Arline, 45, became a landmark case when the
U.S. Supreme Court on March 3, 1987, ruled 7-2 that
anti-discrimination laws cover people suffering from AIDS and other
contagious illnesses.
   The high court ordered a new fact-finding trial for Mrs. Arline,
which was held here in May before U.S. District Judge John Moore.
   Moore, in an order filed Friday, found that Mrs. Arline was a
victim of discrimination and ordered her reinstated with four years
back pay totaling more than $100,000, said Patricia Fields
Anderson, Mrs. Arline's attorney.
   ``We are ecstatic,'' Ms. Anderson said Tuesday. ``It has been a
long nine years.''
   The judge said the Nassau County school board must either
reinstate Mrs. Arline or pay an additional $768,000 in ``front
pay'' to take her up to retirement, Ms. Anderson said. The board's
attorney indicated Tuesday that the district will rehire her, the
attorney said.
   ``She is going to be, hopefully, back on the payroll and
teaching by mid-August,'' said Ms. Anderson. ``She's ready to go _
she's rarin' to go.''
   Craig Marsh, superintendent of schools for Nassau County, said
Tuesday he had not yet seen the decision and could not comment, but
understood that the county would have to provide the back pay. The
board, he said, would discuss the case next week.
   The Supreme Court ordered the May trial after it found Mrs.
Arline's TB fit the definition of disabilities included in a 1973
federal law forbidding discrimination against the handicapped.
   Mrs. Arline was fired in February 1979 from her job as a
third-grade teacher because she had contracted the disease.
   She filed suit, but a federal judge threw the case out in 1983.
Then in 1985, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta
reinstated the case, saying a judge must determine whether her
firing was the result of medical necessity or unfounded hysteria
about the disease.
   Nassau County appealed the case to the Supreme Court. It argued
that a ruling in her favor would effectively make it impossible to
fire anyone with a contagious disease.
   Moore limited the back pay to four years because he found that
after 1983 Mrs. Arline had not made sufficient effort to find other
work or tried to qualify herself for teaching higher grades, which
the district would have allowed.
</TEXT>
