<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Church Bjt   07-05 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Church, Bjt,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Of England Takes Another Step Toward Women Priests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church of England leaders voted Tuesday in favor
of proposals to admit women to the priesthood, despite opposition
from their spiritual head, Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie,
who warned it could split the church.
   The General Synod of bishops, clergy and laity voted 299-216 for
draft legislation allowing the ordination of women. Each group
voted separately: the bishops voted 28-21 in favor; the clergy
voted 137-102; and the laity voted 134-93. There was one abstention.
   But a lengthy process must be followed before the Anglican state
church might get its first woman priest in 1992 or 1993.
   The legislation will be debated and voted upon by all 44 of the
church's dioceses. It then goes back to the General Synod for final
approval and must then by approved by Parliament.
   Runcie had no comment after the four-hour debate at Church House.
   Opponents of women priests estimate that at least 1,000 of the
10,660 clergy will leave the church if women are ordained. The
draft legislation allows for them to be paid up to $51,000 if they
quit on grounds of conscience.
   The legislation also allows bishops the right to refuse to
ordain women or have them in their dioceses.
   Runcie referred to the proposals as a ``legislative schism.'' He
said there was no consensus in the church for the historic step,
although the theological balance was now in favor.
   One prelate who voted for the proposals, Bishop of Peterborough
William Westwood, said later he thought the vote signaled the
``kiss of death'' for women's ordination.
   ``When it comes back to the synod in four years' time it will
need a two-thirds majority because it will be at a decisive stage.
It certainly didn't get that today and I detected a clear change of
mood among the bishops voting,'' Westwood said.
   ``Up to now they have been very much in favor. But their mood is
definitely changing because the church is getting tired of this
perpetual debate.''
   The issue was first debated 37 years ago but the first decisive
step was taken in 1975 when the synod said there were no
fundamental objections to women priests.
   Since then, Anglican churches in other countries _ which are
self-governing but look to the archbishop of Canterbury for
guidance _ have ordained about 1,000 women priests, most of them in
the U.S. Episcopalian Church.
   Runcie said he would continue to recognize women priests
ordained outside England and he would like to see them allowed to
exercise their ministry in England ``under special conditions,''
which he did not specify.
   Speakers in the debate were carefully selected to give equal
time to supporters and opponents.
   Archdeacon of the Royal Navy Noel Jones said: ``I appeal to the
synod not to take on board an issue which is so totally divisive.
Many people see us as a church limping along aimlessly _ are we now
hell-bent on shooting ourselves in the foot as well?''
   But the church's second-ranking prelate, Archbishop of York John
Habgood, said: ``We should allow the church at large a chance to
discuss this issue without giving a signal to the nation that we
are irrevocably committed to it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
