<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Airliner-Pentagon 3rdLd-Writethru a0633 07-05 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Pentagon, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0633,530</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 6th graf bgng: Indeed, Sen. ... to
UPDATE with Iran's U.N. ambassador saying plane sending signals it
was civilian aircraft. Picks up 7th graf pvs bgng: Howard told ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iranian airliner shot down by a U.S. Navy
missile was transmitting information on two radio channels,
including one ``identified with F-14s'' flown by the Iranian air
force, the Pentagon said today.
   The fact the plane's transponder was using a military channel
helped lead to the conclusion aboard the cruiser Vincennes that the
ship was about to be attacked, said Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard.
   That knowledge, Howard said, was a ``substantial factor'' in
Capt. Will C. Rogers III's decision to launch two missiles toward
the jet.
   ``The signals that the Vincennes were receiving were signals
previously identified with F-14s,'' Howard said.
   He said he was releasing the information about the transmission
on a military channel to support the statements of Adm. William J.
Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, that the
Vincennes fired its missiles because it throught it was attacking a
military target.
   Indeed, Sen. John Warner of Virginia, senior Republican on the
Senate Armed Services Committee, told a Capitol Hill news
conference that giving a civilian plane a military transponder code
``defies all reasonable understanding.''
   However, Iran's U.N. Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati told
a news conference in New York today that contrary to assertions of
U.S. officials, the Iranian Airbus was sending out ``normal signals
... to all radar that it was a civilian plane.''
   Howard told reporters that there are still a large number of
unanswered questions about Sunday's incident, in which the Iranian
Airbus A-300 was shot down over the Strait of Hormuz.
   The Iranian plane, with 290 persons aboard, had just taken off
from Bandar Abbas, an airfield also used by Iranian military
planes, Howard noted.
   As the Iranian jetliner flew toward the Vincennes, the plane's
transponder was sending out signals through two channels, Howard
said. He identified them as ``mode 3'' and ``mode 2.''
   According to Howard, ``mode 3'' is a commonly used commercial
channel which is also sometimes used by military planes. Howard
said he did not specifically know what information the jetliner was
transmitting on ``mode 3.''
   But ``mode 2,'' according to Howard, ``is peculiar to military
aircraft.'' He said ``no commercial airlines use mode 2.''
   The ``mode 2'' transmitting device ``is a specific piece of
equipment that has to put on'' a plane, Howard said.
   The signals received by the Vincennes through ``mode 2'' had
been identified with Iranian F-14s in the past year, Howard said.
   Iran has a handful of U.S.-built F-14s that it purchased during
the reign of the shah. Some of the remaining F-14s were moved to
the Bandar Abbas airbase in recent days, according to Pentagon
officials.
   Howard also said there are ``conflicting reports'' about the
altitude and path of the Iranian plane before it was struck.
   Crowe had said the Iranian plane was at about 7,000 feet and was
descending directly toward the Vincennes when the order was given
to fire the ship's missiles.
   But the USS Sides, a frigate operating in the area at the same
time, reported that the airliner was above 12,000 feet. Asked if
the Sides' after-action report showed whether the plane was
descending or ascending, Howard said the report didn't indicate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880705-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Airliner-Vincennes     07-05 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Vincennes,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missile Cruiser is a Lot of Ship for a `Lake in a Desert'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS Vincennes, the first cruiser of
the high-tech Aegis type to serve in the Persian Gulf, is a lot of
ship for what an American skipper once called ``a lake in a
desert.''
   It was ordered here with such speed that some officers seemed to
have only a hazy idea of its mission. When the billion-dollar
warship entered the Persian Gulf on May 27, however, the night-time
passage through the narrow Strait of Hormuz left its 385 crewmen in
no doubt they were in a war zone.
   Off Oman, salvage tugs battled fire on a Norwegian ammonia
tanker attacked by Iranian gunboats the day before. On the Iranian
side, flames licked at ships still burning from an Iraqi air raid
on two weeks earlier on Iran's big Larak Island oil terminal.
   The assignment began in mid-April with a rush departure from
home port in San Diego.
   It is scheduled to last about three months, but the Vincennes
could be withdrawn earlier as a gesture to reduce tensions caused
by its shooting down of an Iranian airliner Sunday. U.S. officials
say the Airbus A300 was mistaken for an Iranian F-14 fighter.
   Members of a Pentagon news pool taken aboard the ship before it
entered the gulf found some officers and crew somewhat puzzled over
the orders that brought them 13,000 miles in 32 days, on a million
gallons of fuel.
   Some officers noted it was the first tour in the narrow confines
of the gulf by one of the Navy's Aegis cruisers, which have
computer-linked radar and missile systems designed for fleet
defense in open sea.
   The shallow waterway, 600 miles long and no more than 120 miles
across for commercial shipping purposes, was described last year by
the captain of an older cruiser as ``a lake in a desert'' with many
threats, all close at hand.
   One officer of the Vincennes was asked what he thought the gulf
mission would be for a ship whose phased-array ``Spy'' radar and
weapons are designed to fight an enemy hundreds of miles away. He
replied: ``You tell me.''
   Even Capt. Will C. Rogers III, the skipper, seemed to have
trouble with the question, suggesting the multiple functions of his
supership might enable the Navy to reduce the strength of its gulf
force. That has not happened.
   Rogers told reporters the next day the Vincennes would provide
``a lot of battle management'' and ``maybe we will be able to
reduce the force level in the gulf and back away from the recent
tensions in the area.''
   Gen. George B. Crist told reporters in Manama on June 1 the
cruiser's air defense radar could cover the entire gulf and called
it a ``quantum leap forward'' in detering a new Iranian anti-ship
missile site nearing completion in the strait. The four-star Marine
genral heads the U.S. Central Command in Tampa, Fla., which is
responsible for the gulf.
   This is the fourth Navy ship named for the 1779 Revolutionary
War battle at what is now Vincennes, Ind., a university town on the
Wabash River. The first sailed around the world and a voyage in
1839 established that Antarctica was a land mass. The second and
third were World War II cruisers.
   The current Vincennes, launched at the Ingalls shipyard in
Pascagoula, Miss., three years ago Wednesday, is the third of 10
Aegis cruisers planned for the Navy.
   It originally was to be the USS Valley Forge but the name was
changed after a lobbying campaign by the Vincennes Association,
made up of veterans who served on the World War II cruisers,
Indiana politicians and Vincennes civic leaders.
   Cruiser No. 49 became the Vincennes and No. 50 got the name
Valley Forge.
   Since its arrival, the 567-foot warship has operated almost
exclusively in the soutehrn gulf, where air and surface activity is
most concentrated.
</TEXT>
