<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--StolenFlags     07-05 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Stolen Flags,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thieves Cause Town To Decide To Stop Flying Flags</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ODENVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. flags flying on Main Street may
have been just too grand, and because of thieves they'll not be
high-flying on any more national holidays.
   Five were stolen over the Independence Day weekend, bringing the
total to 11 stolen in four years.
   ``We're just not going to put them up anymore,'' Mary Banks, who
has been in charge of the display since 21 flags were donated four
years ago, said Tuesday.
   ``People can't leave them alone for other people to enjoy,''
Mrs. Banks said.
   Mrs. Banks on Monday persuaded Odenville to offer a $200 reward
for information leading to the arrest of the flag thieves.
   ``I don't think they wanted them because they are patriotic,''
she said.
   Two years ago, Mayor James Moreland said, the town put up a
40-foot pole and a large flag in Odenville Park. ``In less than 30
minutes they had cut the rope and taken the flag ... in broad
daylight,'' he said.
