<DOCNO> AP880705-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan-Bush     07-05 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Bush,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan: Democrats Hide Liberalism Behind ``Trench Coats,
Sunglasses''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, urging Americans to do ``a
little comparison shopping'' in the presidential race, praised
George Bush on Tuesday while accusing Michael Dukakis and the
Democrats of hiding liberalism behind ``political trench coats and
sunglasses.''
   In his strongest pitch yet for his vice president, Reagan called
Bush ``the kind of man I want to follow me.''
   The president, in an address to a group of conservatives at the
Old Executive Office Building, portrayed the November elections as
crucial for his conservative legacy.
   ``All we've achieved ... could be lost in just a few months,''
he said.
   Referring to the likely Democratic presidential nominee only as
``a governor,'' Reagan derided Dukakis as an ``out-and-out
liberal'' who has no interest in controlling government spending
and instead raises taxes.
   In contrast, Reagan lauded Bush as his standard-bearer for
conservative anti-tax, anti-abortion and tough law-and-order
policies.
   Less than two weeks before the Democrats gather in Atlanta for
their convention, Reagan accused the party of ``putting together a
campaign that is subtle and clever.''
   ``The American people understand what liberalism means and don't
like it, so our opponents plan to go to the voters incognito _
they're putting on political trenchcoats and sunglasses,'' Reagan
said.
   Evoking laughter from his audience, Reagan quipped the Democrats
``will never even in the lowest whisper mumble the `L' word again.''
   ``How other than liberal would you characterize a governor who
in the last five years increased his state's spending twice as fast
as the federal government's and more than a third faster than the
average for all the other states?'' Reagan asked.
   ``And what do you call a governor who raises taxes $115 million
and declares it a victory? An out-and-out liberal,'' Reagan said.
   ``Yes, all that the American people need to do is a little
comparison shopping to see the truth,'' he added.
   Reagan said that while Dukakis ``has fought for weekend
furloughs for dangerous convicts, including drug dealers,'' Bush
``has led the fight against drug smugglers.''
   ``Their candidate has opposed requiring the Pledge of Allegiance
and allowing prayer in schools. Our candidate _ well, he and I both
find it hard to believe that anyone could take these positions,''
Reagan said.
   The president credited Bush with converting European
governmental officials who had opposed NATO's deployment of a new
generation of medium-range nuclear missiles _ the missiles that
have been ordered removed under the U.S.-Soviet arms treaty signed
by Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   After Bush's 1983 London speech advocating deployment, Reagan
contended, ``the tide in Europe shifted and thanks to him,
deployment went forward.''
   The bulk of Reagan's 15-minute address was devoted to extolling
Bush's virtues.
   ``It's no secret who I believe should pick up the lease around
here in January. Again and again these past eight years I've
admired George Bush's strength. Again and again his leadership has
been a key to our successes,'' Reagan said.
   ``Yes, this is the kind of man I want to follow me, someone who
will take our battle forward, who will speak our gospel truly and
will do the work that is yet to be done,'' Reagan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
