<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-05 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie B., Zoo Atlanta's famous gorilla,
celebrated his 30th birthday with a big basket of fruit, while the
guests higher up the evolutionary ladder enjoyed what was billed as
the world's largest banana split.
   About 500 people jammed the viewing area opposite Willie B.'s
new outdoor habitat at the zoo's African rain forest to wish the
459-pound lowland gorilla a happy birthday Monday. The date was
arbitrary, since Willie was captured in the wild.
   While the people had ice cream, Willie B. downed five bananas
for starters, dropping the peels carefully in front of him, then
gobbled a few clusters of red grapes, followed by an apple and a
couple of handfuls of strawberries.
   Willie B. savored a moment of applause, then downed a couple of
cantaloupes and a cluster of green grapes, one grape at a time.
Then, he shredded the basket.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An enterprising ape propped a tree limb
against a wall and climbed over to join startled visitors at the
Kansas City Zoo.
   ``I didn't know what to expect,'' said Karen Maness, who walked
out of the restroom Sunday to see the 200-pound gorilla running
toward her family. ``I didn't know whether he was going to attack
them.''
   The gorilla avoided the family, went around the camel and wooly
monkey exhibits and ambled back to the Ape House, where she was
caught about five minutes later.
   ``The other gorillas were screeching,'' Mrs. Maness said. ``They
knew something was happening that shouldn't be.''
   The gorilla was eating bark from the tree limb when she propped
it against the wall, said Gene Tryon, manager of public services at
the zoo.
   Mrs. Maness said zoo officials tried to route visitors to safe
places until the gorilla could be caught and tranquilized with a
dart gun. About 8,000 people were at the zoo.
   Tyron said gorillas, which are naturally shy and timid, have
been fed tree bark for years at the zoo. He said the zoo will make
sure branches will be escape-proof in the future.
   ``We've never had a gorilla loose in the zoo before,'' Tryon
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ELKINS, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jeff Harris bills himself as the biggest
small-business man in town, but it isn't just his 400-pound frame
that's unusual.
   Harris, a vegetarian, runs a hot dog stand.
   ``Most folks don't know about my vegetarianism,' Harris said
recently. ``When they hear about it, some even doubt that a
400-pound man who runs a hot dog shop doesn't get into the
inventory.
   ``Sometimes I'll grab a bun and go into the kitchen and put some
cheese and relish on it and eat that so people will think I'm
eating hot dogs, but actually I'm not.''
   His vegetarian beliefs began in 1971 when he was in the fifth
grade.
   ``I was a very religious little person,'' he said. ``The church
I was going to said there are clean and unclean types of meat. So I
thought I'd be better off not trying any of them. I've been a
vegetarian ever since.''
   He said he has never tried his own hot dogs or chili and said
his employees test the food for him.
</TEXT>
