<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyTrial     07-05 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Trial,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Clears Way for Military Murder Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy officer who could face
the death penalty goes on military trial Wednesday on charges he
fatally shot a ship paymaster and stole the $94,000 payroll.
   A Navy judge Tuesday cleared the way for trial by rejecting
defense challenges to search warrants in the case.
   The warrants, for three bank safety-deposit boxes, ``were
properly issued'' despite wrong dates and other erroneous
information supplied to the issuing judge by Naval investigators,
Judge John A. Studer ruled.
   The selection of a court-martial jury of at least five Navy
officers was scheduled Wednesday, and opening statements were
expected Thursday in the trial of Petty Officer 1st Class Ruben
Colon, 34, of Vega Baja, Puerto Rico.
   Colon is accused of killing Lt. j.g. Ratish Prasad, 24,
disbursing officer aboard the destroyer John Hancock, while it was
docked at Mayport, last March 15. He is charged with murder,
kidnapping, robbery and receiving stolen property.
   According to court records, Prasad was taken at gunpoint from
his office to a lower deck, where he was bound, shot dead and
stuffed in a locker.
   The judge had earlier refused to rule out the death penalty as a
possible punishment for the murder charge. But the Navy has not
executed anyone since a mutiny in 1849.
   Colon's lawyer, Lt. Matthew J. Michels, argued Tuesday that the
affidavit in support of a request for the search warrants was
``carelessly prepared'' and then ``negligently reviewed'' by
federal Magistrate Harvey Schlesinger.
   But Schlesinger testified that conflicting dates about the
criminal activity and resulting investigation ``don't mean
anything'' because they had no bearing on the crime itself, or
Colon's alleged role in it.
   The prosecutor, Lt. Daniel J. Glary, contended the errors and
inconsistencies had ``no bearing on probable cause'' of guilt and
the justification for a search of Colon's safety deposit boxes.
   The judge agreed.
   The break in the case came when the bank that rented Colon the
largest safety deposit box available tipped off investigators.
   The court-martial is being held in a windowless classroom at the
Fleet Trainer Center at Mayport. About 10 members of the
destroyer's crew have been flown from the Middle East to testify.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
