<HEAD>W.Va. Farmers Urged to Sell Hay, Not Give It Away</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGWOOD, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Virginia farmers should not donate
their hay crop to drought-stricken Midwest farmers but should sell
it instead, Preston County's extension agent said Tuesday.
   ``We have the hay those guys need,'' said Tom McConnell. ``We
shouldn't feel guilty at all about sending hay to the Midwest _ to
sell.''
   McConnell was responding to appeals from state agricultural
officials attempting to organize a hay giveaway program similar to
one conducted by Virginia farmers.
   ``When corn is in short supply here no one is sending corn to
us, and the price goes up,'' McConnell said.
   McConnell said the first cutting of hay in Preston County has
been good, but the continued drought has been hurting grass hay.
Deep-rooted alfalfa is doing fine.
   The extension agent said he has been receiving calls from Ohio
farmers wanting to buy hay.
   The price of hay in Preston County is 50 cents per bale higher
than this time last year and is rising, McConnell said. It normally
costs about $1.00 to $1.25 a bale.
