<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Decaturs     07-05 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Decaturs,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nebraska Entry May Have to Withdraw from Decatur Charity Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While most communities named Decatur are
gearing up to help the needy, officials in this parched town say
they may be having to ask for aid.
   Organizers in Decatur, Ill. _ the nation's largest Decatur with
94,000 residents _ had challenged other U.S. Decaturs to collect
one can of food per citizen to help the needy.
   The mayor of Nebraska's Decatur accepted the challenge and
joined ``Cans Across the County,'' but now he doesn't think he will
be able to approach his citizens to ask for help.
   This northeastern Nebraska village is entirely dependent on the
farm economy and for the last 22 days has received little rain,
said Mayor Jack Maryott.
   ``We've got no factories or anything here,'' he said. ``If we
don't have a crop here, it's bad, and it doesn't look good for us
right now.''
   There is a ``90 percent chance'' the town will bow out of the
competition unless rain falls soon, Maryott said Monday.
   Organizers in Illinois were hoping the drought doesn't force
other Decaturs to withdraw from the challenge, which could provide
hundreds of thousands of cans of food for the poor.
   Mayor Gary Anderson of Decatur, Ill., kicked off the contest on
Memorial Day weekend by mailing a white glove to each of the other
Decaturs _ officials believe there are 28.
   Part of the idea was to answer the question posed on T-shirts
being handed out in Illinois, ``Where the heck's Decatur?''
</TEXT>
