<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietInspectors     07-05 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Inspectors,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Begin Missile Site Inspections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials fanned out across
West Germany on Tuesday to inspect U.S. nuclear missile sites
covered by the superpower arms treaty.
   The 19 Soviet specialists, who arrived Monday, split up into two
teams and traveled to a U.S. Pershing II missile site in Mutlangen
near Stuttgart and a cruise missile site at Hasselbach south of
Koblenz, said an Air Force spokesman at the Rhein-Main U.S. Air
Force Base near Frankfurt.
   ``They have up to 24 hours to complete their inspections. Should
there be a reason for further inspections and both sides agree, an
additional eight hours can be permitted,'' said the spokesman.
   The inspections are being conducted under the new superpower
arms treaty, in which the United States and the Soviet Union agreed
to scrap their medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles.
   American inspectors have gone to the Soviet Union to examine
intermediate-range nuclear missile sites there, while other Soviet
specialists are checking sites in the United States.
   The U.S. Air Force spokesman at Rhein-Main said he did not know
how long it would take for the Soviet teams in West Germany to
check the two missile sites they were visiting Tuesday.
   ``Because of time constraints under the treaty, it is reasonable
to expect they will approach their duties in an expeditious
manner,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``There are rest facilities for them at the sites, and a place
for them to take a nap if they choose. There are also private
meeting rooms where they can discuss their inspection activities,''
said the official.
   There are four other U.S. sites in West Germany that fall under
the superpower arms treaty. The Soviets have not yet announced
whether they will be visiting those sites as well, the spokesman
said.
   The inspections in West Germany, the United States and the
Soviet Union are to make sure that items found at the missile sites
correspond to what has been listed by the superpowers in the treaty.
</TEXT>
