<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Cuomo-Reporter Bjt   07-05 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuomo-Reporter, Bjt,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Becomes Reporter for a Day, with Help</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Phrasing in graf 5 cq.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XJT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMESTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He can't type and his editors rewrote his
lead, but Gov. Mario Cuomo said playing cub reporter for a day
Tuesday was fun and taught him it's not easy getting all the facts.
   The governor, to fulfill a promise made during his last
campaign, worked for a day for the Jamestown Post-Journal. He was
assigned to cover Lt. Gov. Stan Lundine presenting a check to help
build a research center.
   Here's what Cuomo wrote:
   ``A local boy who made good came back to Jamestown yesterday and
demonstrated the economic development skills that earned him and
the city a national reputation when he was Jamestown's mayor from
1970 to March 1976.
   ``Stan Lundine, now lieutenant governor, presented the
Blackstone Corp. with a symbolic check for $4 million, under an
agreement with Blackstone that will keep the 1,000 jobs it now
creates, and at least 35 and probably many more.''
   Here's the edited version:
   ``A symbolic $4 million check was given to Blackstone yesterday
to preserve 1,000 jobs and create at least 35 more.''
   Cuomo said later the story was hard to humanize because ``there
was no sex in this thing.''
   ``I'll know print press better now, the difficulty of it,''
Cuomo said. ``Getting all the salient facts down when people are up
on that stage talking a mile a minute and you don't have time to
hear it all back on the recorder.''
   On a flight from Jamestown back to Albany, Cuomo told Lundine,
``It looks different from down there (with the reporters).''
   After a news conference at Blackstone, Cuomo returned to the
newspaper and began writing his story as dozens of visiting
reporters and Post-Journal employees watched.
   It wasn't quite like real life. For one thing, there was the
matter of typing. For another, there was the deadline.
   Cuomo, who doesn't know how to type, reviewed his notes and then
summoned another reporter to type the story while he dictated.
   Cuomo, with reporter Manley Anderson's help, needed about 45
minutes to finish his story, to be published under his byline
Wednesday in the Post-Journal, an afternoon newspaper with a
circulation of 29,000.
   Unlike most reporters covering a late-morning event for an
afternoon newspaper, Cuomo was not required to file his story for
Tuesday's editions.
   Post-Journal editor Cristie Herbst briefly conferred with Cuomo
when he returned to the newsroom.
   ``He came up with the lead himself. I maybe had to refine it a
little,'' Herbst said.
   Anderson said Cuomo would ``be near the top'' as far as cub
reporters go.
   ``He seems to have a fair idea of what it's all about,''
Anderson said.
   The governor, who has published two diaries about his public
life, agreed to work as a reporter after a Post-Journal columnist
issued a challenge when Cuomo severely criticized coverage of his
1986 re-election campaign.
   ``It's fun,'' Cuomo said. ``I'd like to do more of it. I won't,
but I'd like to do more of it.''
   During the news conference, Cuomo attracted most of the
attention of reporters and television crews.
   Cuomo quizzed Lundine and company executives about a state
assistance program and whether it would actually help save 1,000
jobs as Lundine and the officials claimed.
   The grant, from the state Department of Economic Development
which Cuomo oversees, is designed to help Blackstone develop new
cooling systems for automobiles.
   ``How can you assure us that it wouldn't have happened without
taxpayer assistance?'' Cuomo asked. But the mild-mannered Lundine
assured his boss that Blackstone proved it needed the money to make
sure it got the project.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
