<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Telephone-VDT     07-05 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Telephone-VDT,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Telephone Reacts to Suffolk VDT Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing Suffolk County's new VDT bill, New York
Telephone announced Tuesday a hiring freeze on VDT jobs in the
county and said it would close a directory assistance bureau there
that employs about 125 persons.
   Thomas Calabrese, general manager, said in a statement that the
company regrets the decision but that the VDT bill ``imposes
unnecessary costs'' that will eventually be passed on to customers.
   He said the VDT-equipped Babylon directory assistance office
will close when its lease expires Dec. 31 and the company will
review other leases on a case-by-case basis. Babylon employees will
be reassigned to other locations.
   The VDT bill, which is the first of its kind in the nation,
requires businesses with 20 or more terminals to meet safety
standards, such as non-glare screens and rest breaks.
   The Suffolk County Legislature passed the law June 14,
overriding a veto of the measure by County Executive Patrick Halpin.
   The bill was opposed by local business groups who said they
feared the county would lose 3,000 jobs.
   Valerie Scibilia, spokeswoman for the Long Island Association,
which plans to file a suit challenging the law later this week
said, ``It should really not be a surprise that New York Telephone
did this because they said they would consider doing it if the bill
became law.''
   Scibilia said, ``it's a unique law that singles out Suffolk
County and we feel the legislature has exceeded its authority.''
   Greg Blasso, who cosponsored the bill said, ``to blame it on the
VDT bill is to indulge in overreaction _ the telephone company
should understand that the bill is reasonable.... is it a burden to
provide detachable key boards and proper lighting?''
   According to Blasso, the telephone company has nothing to worry
about until after l990, because ``the only thing they are required
to do now is provide eye examinations and pay for 80 percent of the
cost for corrective glasses if needed.
   Halpin said in a statement, ``I think it is unfortunate that New
York Telephone Co. has made this decision because I think Suffolk
workers are among the finest in the region and the major reason why
businesses and industries of all types have chosen to locate here.''
</TEXT>
