<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Democrats-Satellite     07-05 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Satellite,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Satellite News Service To Provide Additional Convention Coverage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The television networks may be content to
carry a mere two hours of Democratic convention coverage a night,
but party officials are betting that local stations will want more
_ and they'll happily supply it.
   The Convention Satellite News Service will begin 46 hours of
transmissions July 16, two days before the Democrats open their
parley in Atlanta's Omni arena.
   Manager Paul Byers said the material, available to any
television station with a satellite dish, will include packaged
interviews with party officials, live coverage of convention
proceedings, both on and off the floor, and opportunities for local
stations to interview area politicians attending the convention.
   Four mobile crews in Atlanta will cover newsworthy events, Byers
said. He said former CBS newsman Ike Pappas was hired to conduct
advance interviews with party chairman Paul G. Kirk and convention
chairman Don Fowler.
   A plethora of Democratic groups _ the national committee, the
convention committee, the House and Senate campaign committees,
mayors, governors and state chairmen _ have been allocated
satellite time and are preparing video packages that range from a
look at labor issues to an interview with House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas.
   Wright, presiding over the convention as a House panel
investigates some of his financial dealings and other matters, was
interviewed in a segment prepared by the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee.
   Asked whether it is wise under the circumstances for the
Democrats to showcase Wright on their satellite, Byers replied,
``Wright is playing the leading role in the convention. Hopefully
the interview has some teeth in it _ asks the questions that any
journalist would ask.''
   Convention Satellite News Service originally planned to offer 38
hours of transmissions, Byers said, but added another eight hours
``based on feedback from the stations that they wanted it.''
   During the four-day convention the service will beam live and
taped material from 2 p.m. to midnight. All stations, including
about 330 that will be represented in Atlanta, are being encouraged
to use it.
   CBS and NBC have said they will carry convention coverage from 9
to 11 p.m. the first three nights and 8 to 11 p.m. on the final
night. ABC has similar plans.
   ``We're not trying to compete with the networks or other news
coverage. We're seeking to supplement, not supplant,'' Byers said.
   One of the primary functions of the satellite feed will be to
enable local news people to interview congressmen, senators and
others for their own audiences. Stations also will be offered
footage of the arena for use in advance pieces and live events they
can excerpt to fit their own needs.
   ``We want them to maintain editorial control. That's the
difference between this and a press release,'' said Byers. ``There
are always risks, but you take those risks and hope that the net
effect is positive.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880705-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1718EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietInspectors     07-05 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Inspectors,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>INF Treaty Verification Teams To Return To U.S.S.R.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRAVIS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teams of Soviet inspectors
left for home Tuesday after inspecting five U.S. missile facilities
to verify compliance with the historic Intermediate-Range Nuclear
Forces Treaty.
   The 48 weapons experts and linguists boarded their IL-62
Aeroflot jetliner and left about noon, one day after conducting
24-hour spot checks at missile plants in Utah, Arizona, Colorado
and California, said Capt. Tom Dolney, spokesman at Travis.
   They returned to the base late Sunday and early Monday in time
for a July Fourth air and fireworks show. ``They couldn't help but
see it,'' Dolney said.
   ``They rested up when they got here because they went pretty
hard during their inspections,'' he said. ``There was so much to do
and so little time to do it in.''
   The inspectors conducted the first of five types of inspections
allowed under the INF treaty signed by President Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev in December.
   The ``baseline inspection'' is designed to verify the exact
number of medium-range missiles and related components to be
destroyed under the treaty.
   ``It's basically to count and record,'' said Lt. Col. Joseph
Wagovich of the Department of Defense's new On-Site Inspection
Agency.
   Another 22 inspectors who arrived with the five teams will
remain up to 13 years at the Hercules Aerospace Co. missile plant
in Magna, Utah, to monitor the gates of the facility where Pershing
missile rocket motors were made.
   The Soviets had arrived Friday as 20 American inspectors
departed for Moscow and the Soviet city of Votkinsk for reciprocal
inspections.
   Friday marked the first of 60 days allowed under the treaty for
24-hour spot checks at designated missile facilities in the U.S and
Western Europe and the Soviet Union, East Germany and
Czechoslovakia.
   Armed with tape measures, scales and Polaroid cameras, the
Soviets visited five sites: the Pueblo Army Depot Activity in
Pueblo, Colo.; a General Dynamics plant in San Diego, Calif.; the
Dugway Proving Ground, a remote Army installation in the Western
Utah desert; a cruise missile testing and training site at Fort
Huachuca, Ariz., about 60 miles south of Tucson; and Davis-Monthan
Air Force base near Tucson, a missile training center.
   Under the complex provisions of the treaty, the Soviets had the
right to conduct spot checks at any of the five sites this weekend,
and they didn't have to say how many of them they wanted to visit
until the last minute.
</TEXT>
