<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HolidayTraffic     07-05 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holiday Traffic,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 460 Killed in Traffic Accidents over Holiday Weekend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 460 people died on the nation's
roadways during the Fourth of July holiday weekend.
   At least 463 people were reported killed in traffic accidents
over the three-day period, according to authorities in all 50
states.
   Before the holiday began, the Chicago-based National Safety
Council had estimated that between 400 and 500 people could die in
holiday traffic accidents. The council said 400 traffic deaths
might be expected during a three-day, non-holiday period at this
time of year.
   California reported the highest state toll with 57 dead,
followed by Texas with 31 and Florida with 27.
   Five states _ Alaska, Maine, Montana, Vermont and Wyoming _
reported no traffic fatalities.
   For counting purposes, the weekend began at 6 p.m. Friday and
ended at midnight, local times, Monday.
   During last year's Independence Day weekend, 390 people were
killed.
   The highest toll on record for a three-day Fourth of July
weekend was logged in 1971, when 638 people died.
</TEXT>
