<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia     07-05 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Supports Talks Among Factions, But Sees No Easy Solution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian resistance leader Prince
Norodom Sihanouk said Tuesday he supports plans for informal talks
among the warring factions in his country, but sees no easy
solution to the conflict.
   Sihanouk told foreign ministers of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations that the talks, scheduled for July 25 in Indonesia,
marked a turning point in the search for a peace settlement.
   But he pointed to the negative outcome of meetings he held last
winter with Prime Minister Hun Sen, head of the Vietnam-backed
communist Cambodian government.
   Sihanouk warned: ``Don't expect that (the informal meeting) is
going to be easy and that it will reach a constructive
conclusion,'' Thai Foreign Ministry spokesman Saroj Chavanaviraj
told reporters.
   Discussions of the Cambodian issue dominated the ASEAN annual
conference in Bangkok, which concluded Tuesday. Ministers expressed
optimism that the informal talks will lead to a peace accord
between Cambodian resistance groups and Vietnam, which invaded
Cambodia in late 1978.
   Vietnam on Tuesday reaffirmed its support for the informal talks.
   A July 29, 1987, Vietnamese-Indonesian agreement calls for
two-stage discussions, with Vietnam, Laos and the ASEAN members
stepping in after the Cambodian groups have met.
   All ASEAN members _ Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia, Brunei,
Singapore and the Philippines _ reportedly have said they will
attend the meetings.
   In a joint statement Tuesday, the ASEAN ministers called on
Vietnam to withdraw its troops from Cambodia and said the
international community should keep denying Vietnam any aid that
support its occupation.
   However, several delegates said the bloc has shifted its
strategy from isolating Vietnam to trying to encourage it to take
part in negotiations.
   ASEAN strongly supports the three-party Cambodian resistance
coalition headed by Sihanouk that is battling the Vietnamese
forces. Vietnam says it now is in the process of withdrawing its
troops from Cambodia. It invaded its neighbor after fierce border
clashes with the radical communist Khmer Rouge government which
then ruled Cambodia.
   Tuesday's ASEAN statement also urged other nations to contribute
to a multilateral aid package for the Philippines, the most
troubled economy in ASEAN.
   On Thursday, the ministers will begin three days of talks with
ASEAN ``dialogue partners'' _ the United States, Japan, Australia,
Canada, New Zealand and the European Community.
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz and West Germany's
deputy chancellor and foreign minister, Hans-Dietrich Genscher, are
to attend. Shultz is expected in Bangkok Wednesday and will go on
to visit seven other Asian nations.
   Local newspapers said Tuesday that security was tightened at
Bangkok's international airport to block possible terrorist attacks
against Shultz, following the downing Sunday of an Iranian
passenger jet by U.S. naval forces in the Persian Gulf.
   ``All appropriate security measures will be in place for
Secretary Shultz's visit,'' U.S. Embassy spokesman Ross Petzing
said.
   Shultz is expected to get a sympathetic hearing on America's
Middle East stance and general foreign policy, but the ASEAN
ministers signaled in their joint statement that they would exert
pressure on growing protectionism in industrialized nations.
   They also criticized the failure of Western nations to
adequately resettle Indochinese refugees, who receive initial
asylum in Southeast Asian countries and then often languish for
years in refugee camps awaiting permanent resettlement elsewhere.
   But the statement said only Vietnam could resolve the problem of
the flight of its ``boat people'' into the region.
   The ministers called for cooperation in the battle against
increased drug trafficking and abuse, which they said pose ``a
threat to all ASEAN societies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
