<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-CentralAmerica     07-05 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Central America,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fitzwater Says Consensus Building for New Contra Aid Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Tuesday the Reagan administration believes there is ``a growing
consensus'' for further humanitarian aid to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   But Fitzwater, discussing Secretary of State George P. Shultz's
trip to four Central American countries, deflected questions about
new military assistance to the Contra rebels.
   Fitzwater said the Shultz visit to Costa Rica, El Salvador,
Guatemala and Honduras last week was aimed at gaining the general
views of Central American leaders about U.S. policy in the region.
   Asked whether Shultz had found support or acquiescence to a
resumption of U.S. military aid to the rebels in view of the
collapse of peace talks with the ruling Sandinistas in Managua, the
spokesman said, ``Well, he didn't go down there seeking that kind
of information.''
   Shultz left Tuesday on a 15-day tour of several Asian countries,
and Max Kampelman, a special ambassador who had accompanied the
secretary on the Central American tour, briefed President Reagan,
Fitzwater said.
   Reagan and Shultz discussed the visit by telephone after the
secretary returned, the spokesman said.
   Nicaraguan resistance leaders had met with Shultz in San Jose,
Costa Rica, last Thursday, as the secretary was winding up his
trip. They said they discussed with him ways to win congressional
approval of new support for the Contras.
   The Congress has steadfastly refused to approve military aid to
the rebels, although lawmakers did give the OK in late March to a
$48 million package of humanitarian aid, to be disbursed during the
remainder of the current budget year, which ends Sept. 30.
   Only $17 million of that sum actually was earmarked for the
rebels. Another $17 million was designated for children victimized
by the war, while $10 million was set aside for a commission to
monitor compliance with a peace agreement and about $4 million for
administrative costs.
   Rebel leader Adolfo Calero said that in the San Jose meeting,
Shultz and Contra leaders discussed a $30 million aid package,
including the possibility of setting aside $7 million in an escrow
account for military assistance if the Sandinistas do not meet
promises for greater democracy.
   Fitzwater declined to specifically discuss what sort of aid
package is being bandied about within the administration, Congress
and the Contra resistance movement.
   ``I'm certain the secretary expressed our view that we want to
support the Contras to the best of our ability and that we have
continually supported humanitarian assistance for them,'' he said.
``But at this point, we have not reached any specific decisions on
the nature of that support and certainly no decisions on lethal aid
of any kind.''
</TEXT>
