<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-05 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Forces Bomb Town Near Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan government forces bombed a
provincial capital in Afghanistan near Kabul after its brief
capture by Moslem guerrillas, Western diplomats said Tuesday.
   Bombs pounded Maidan Shahr after the insurgents occupied the
town June 24, the diplomats said, speaking on condition of
anonymity. They did not give a date for the air raids.
   Diplomats claim the bombing raids caused extensive damage.
Maidan Shahr, the capital of Wardak province, is 15 miles southwest
of Kabul, the Afghan capital.
   Ikram Gran, spokesman for the seven-party Afghan resistance
alliance that has headquarters in Peshawar, Pakistan, said reports
from Maidan Shahr are sketchy but indicate there were ``a lot of
civilian and mujahedeen (guerrilla) casualties.''
   The Afghan guerrillas are hoping for mass defections from
government forces after Soviet troops withdraw. Soviet forces,
which intervened to support the pro-Moscow Afghan government in
1979, began a nine-month pullout May 15 under a U.N.-sponsored
accord signed a month earlier in Geneva.
   Diplomats said guerrillas are massing less than 20 miles west of
Kabul in the Paghman area. They claimed guerrillas are arriving
from the Panjshir valley in the Hindu Kush range north of Kabul and
guerrilla teams have infiltrated Kabul.
   U.N. special envoy Diego Cordovez was expected to arrive in
Kabul from the Pakistani capital of Islamabad Tuesday to push for a
political settlement between the government of President Najib and
the guerrillas.
   Cordovez negotiated the Geneva accord and has conducted further
talks seeking a broad-based Afghan government to replace the
communists now in power. He has gone to Tehran, where he met with
Iran-based guerrilla leaders, and Pakistan, where he met with
government officials and Afghan refugees.
   Cordovez did not meet with the Afghan guerrilla leaders in
Pakistan. He said, however, a proposed coalition government devised
by the guerrilla alliance lacked mass support.
</TEXT>
