<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Duarte,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Pays Visit To Duarte</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan visited ailing Salvadoran
President Jose Napoleon Duarte on Tuesday, who is described as
undergoing intensive chemotherapy but displaying ``a pretty good
attitude.''
   The Salvadoran president, who is suffering from liver cancer,
was visited for 15 minutes by Reagan and Vice President George Bush
at the Walter Reed Army Medical Center complex in the capital city.
   The president traveled by helicopter from the White House to
Walter Reed, where he was greeted by the vice president. After
shaking hands and waving at the crowd of residents across the
street from the hospital, the two men took a presidential limousine
into the complex for the visit with Duarte.
   Hospital spokesman Peter Esker, asked about Duarte's condition,
said, ``He's got a pretty good attitude.''
   Esker said Duarte had re-entered the hospital June 26 for ``an
intensive dose of chemotherapy.'' He was first admitted to Walter
Reed on May 31 and underwent three hours of cancer surgery on June
7.
   The spokesman said that after the chemotherapy ends within the
next several days, Duarte's doctors would decide whether he would
go home to El Salvador or possibly return for additional treatment.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan invited
Duarte to visit the White House before departing Washington and the
Salvadoran president ``said he would like to, if it's possible.''
   Fitzwater added that Reagan offered Duarte a U.S. government
plane for his return home to El Salvador and Duarte accepted.
   The spokesman said there was no word on when Duarte would leave
the hospital.
</TEXT>
