<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-LowRiver     07-05 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Low River,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dredging Slows River Traffic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: With AM-Drought Rdp</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,000 Mississippi River barges
were backed up by shallow water Tuesday at Greenville and Natchez,
Miss., as towboat operators tried working in a convoy to pick their
way to Memphis.
   The Army Corps of Engineers has pledged to keep the
drought-diminished Lower Mississippi open to commercial traffic,
but a Corps spokesman said more barge backups will occur as dredges
work on shallow areas of the river.
   ``There'll be spotty stoppages probably all summer,'' said
Michael Logue, a Corps spokesman from Vicksburg, Miss.
   Southbound barges were stacking up at docking areas, and a
convoy of four towboats with 12 barges each set out Monday from
Cairo, Ill., said Cmdr. Michael Donohoe, commander of the Coast
Guard's Memphis district.
   A second group, with three to five towboats, was scheduled to
leave Wednesday.
   ``If one boat has a problem, the others will help out,'' Donohoe
said.
   Barges coming into the Memphis zone, which runs from
Caruthersville, Mo., to Greenville, are restricted to drafts of 8.5
feet, but Donohoe said the southbound convoys will have barges
drawing nine feet of water.
   By traveling together, he said, the workboats can pull each
other off sandbars or team up to push barges through tricky bends
of the low river.
   Dredging to deepen the channel from 7 feet began Sunday at
Greenville and delayed towboats with about 800 barges, while low
water just south of Natchez had about 1,200 barges backed up, Logue
said.
   Dredging at both sites was expected to take two to four days, he
said.
   The Mississippi, registering record lows, is more than 22 feet
lower at Memphis than it was this time last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
