<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Meese-Bush     07-05 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Bush,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Camp Relieved Over Meese's Plans To Depart</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The announcement by Attorney General Edwin
Meese III on Tuesday that he would resign brought expressions of
relief from George Bush's presidential campaign and a terse
statement from the vice president himself.
   ``Ed did the right thing and I wish him well,'' Bush said in
remarks read over the phone by a staff member.
   The vice president's comment came shortly after Meese announced
in California that he would resign this summer, saying a special
counsel's report, filed Tuesday with a federal court in Washington,
had vindicated him. The report said there was no basis for a
criminal indictment of the attorney general.
   Meese's legal difficulties had been a source of constant concern
to the Bush campaign and two of his advisers had even publicly
called Meese ``a liability,'' although the vice president himself
had declined to say whether Meese should resign.
   In recent weeks, Bush and other Republicans who had spoken on
his behalf had sought to deflect the criticism by referring to
possible conflict-of-interest allegations concerning House Speaker
Jim Wright.
   Still, Tuesday's announcement came as a welcome surprise to Bush
supporters and campaign workers.
   ``He (Meese) got what he needed, not leaving town under the
cloud that he was guilty. On the other hand, the question now of
what are you going to do about Ed Meese certainly isn't going to be
asked any more,'' said Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., who is national
co-chairwoman of Bush's campaign.
   ``I will disagree that there was a cloud over Bush, but there
were questions and this removes them, certainly,'' said Mrs. Martin.
   Bush campaign officials indicated they were caught by surprise
by Meese's announcement, made in Sacramento, Calif.
   ``Of course we are relieved. He did the right thing. Confidence
in him (Meese) had eroded,'' said one official, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
   As to Meese's assertion that he might be willing to work with
Bush should Bush be elected president, the same campaign worker
broke into laughter. ``No comment,'' said the official.
   Bush previously has said that he would not reappoint Meese as
attorney general in his administration if elected, or any other
current Cabient member for that matter, claiming he wanted to have
``a new team.''
   Bush in campaign appearances has stressed the importance of
ethics of government, claiming that he has personally been
untarnished by conflict-of-interest allegations and proposing the
establishment of a new White House office of ethics.
   However, while aides suggested privately that Bush would be
relieved if Meese would step down, the vice president never made
such a recommendation to either Reagan or Meese, Bush campaign
sources said.
   Meese and Bush met privately in May to discuss the situation.
Bush later told reporters that the embattled attorney general had
promised not to do anything to jeopardize his campaign.
</TEXT>
