<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-05 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Soak Gulf Coast, Causing Street Flooding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy thunderstorms continued to soak parts of the Gulf Coast
Tuesday and flooded streets in Alabama, while hot, humid air baked
a large part of the nation from the Rockies to the Appalachian
Mountains.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms extended from southeast
Texas to Alabama, with the southern half of Alabama receiving the
heaviest rainfall.
   In Alabama, more than 4 inches of rain fell at Auburn in the 24
hours ending early Tuesday afternoon, Newell got nearly 3 inches,
and 2{ inches fell at Pine Level, Hackneyville and Horseshoe Bend.
   Streets flooded in Tuscaloosa during the morning after more than
5 inches of rain fell in parts of the city and in Demopolis, which
received 1{ inches.
   Strong thunderstorms developed over parts of western Montana,
while widely scattered showers and thunderstorms developed over the
southern and central Rockies.
   A hot and humid air mass sent temperatures well into the 90s
over much of the area between the Rockies and the Appalachians,
with a sprinkling of readings over 100 degrees in the northern
Plains.
   Record highs for the date included 105 degrees in Fargo, N.D.;
99 in Fort Wayne, Ind.; 98 in St. Cloud, Minn.; and 97 in South
Bend, Ind., and Flint, Mich.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 52 degrees at Spokane,
Wash., to 106 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz., and Palm Springs, Calif.
The nation's low Tuesday morning was 39 degrees at Yakima, Wash.
   Wednesday's forecast called for mostly sunny and hot weather
across much of the nation. Scattered showers and thunderstorms were
forecast for most of the Gulf Coast from Texas to Florida, and for
parts of the northern Plains, the upper Mississippi Valley and New
England. Widely scattered thunderstorms also were forecast for a
large part of the Rockies.
   Highs were predicted to be in the 80s or 90s across much of the
nation. Highs were expected to stay in the 60s and 70s in the
Pacific Northwest and northern Plateau, while rising to between 100
and 110 degrees in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
