<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 2009EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FBIAgent     07-05 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI Agent,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White FBI Agent Admitted He Discussed Retribution Against Black
Agent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white FBI agent admitted he wanted to put
``a burr under the saddle'' of a black fellow agent through a
campaign of harassment but asserted he meant his colleague no harm,
according to court documents.
   The admission, made in a 1985 affidavit by the white agent, Gary
W. Miller, was filed in U.S. District Court here on Friday in
connection with a lawsuit by Donald Rochon.
   Rochon, a black FBI agent, alleges he was the victim of a
campaign of racial harassment by white colleagues in field offices
in Omaha, Neb., and Chicago. Rochon has said that while living in
Chicago, where he was assigned from 1984 to 1986, his family's
safety was repeatedly threatened in anonymous telephone calls and
obscene, racist letters from white FBI agents.
   Documents provided to Rochon's lawyer as part of pre-trial
discovery include Miller's sworn admission that he forged Rochon's
signature on an application for death and dismemberment insurance
for Rochon's family. Rochon has charged that the unsolicited
insurance policy he received as a result of the mailing amounted to
a death threat.
   Miller, who was suspended without pay for two weeks as a result
of that and other incidents aimed at Rochon, stated in the July 30,
1985, affidavit that he did not intend to send Rochon anything
other than junk mail.
   ``At the time, I had no intention of harming Rochon by any of
this,'' he said in the affidavit. ``I did not think there would be
any repercussion. I did not think he would get anything but junk
mail.''
   In the affidavit, Miller said he and agent Thomas J. Dillon
discussed ``retribution against Rochon'' for his allegations of
harassment by agents. ``We discussed having his public utilities
turned off and sending coupons soliciting magazine subscriptions
and other items.''
   In the affidavit, Miller said he embarked on his campaign
against Rochon ``as personal revenge'' for making allegations
against Dillon, who worked with Rochon in Omaha and later in
Chicago.
   ``It was my way of putting a burr under his saddle,'' Miller
said.
   Miller acknowledged that he followed Rochon home one night after
work in order to discover his address, which had been kept secret
from other agents because of the harassment complaint that Rochon
filed within the agency.
   In a separate affidavit, Dillon said he had heard of ``many
incidents that have occurred against Rochon'' but denied
participating in any harassment.
   Members of Congress have sharply criticized the bureau over the
Rochon case and other discrimination claims. More than half the
FBI's Hispanic agents have joined in a separate lawsuit against the
bureau, charging discrimination in hiring and promotion.
   The Justice Department and the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission have already found that Rochon was the victim of
``blatant racial harassment'' in the FBI's Omaha office in 1983 and
1984. A federal grand jury is investigating the later incidents in
Chicago, which Rochon has contended were more serious than those in
Omaha.
   The white agents have called Rochon a troublemaker who brought
unfounded charges of racism against other agents in an effort to
get transferred to his hometown of Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880705-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1916EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Airliner     07-05 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Airliner,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Calls For Urgent Security Council Meeting Over Airliner
Downing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner-Gulf, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Tuesday that the Iranian
airliner shot down by U.S. missile fire had signaled it was a
civilian plane, and called it ``a premeditated, terrorist attack.''
   Iran requested an urgent meeting of the U.N. Security Council to
condemn the American action.
   Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati met council
President Paulo Nogueira-Batista of Brazil on Tuesday. Mahallati
later said he expected the 15-member council, the highest U.N.
body, to meet early next week.
   U.N. officials said consultations on the Iranian request were
under way.
   A council meeting would embarrass the United States, which says
the missile cruiser USS Vincennes shot down an Iranian Airbus with
290 people aboard because the commander believed it to be an F-14
jet fighter on an attack course.
   Mahallati said Iran expects the council to issue ``an
unequivocal and direct condemnation of the United States for this
aggression'' and to call on the United States to immediately
withdraw its forces from the Persian Gulf.
   ``This kind of barbarism, a premeditated, terrorist attack is
thanks to the American presence,'' he said.
   Mahallati also said it is ``the undeniable obligation of U.S.
authorities to make an apology. But can an apology wash away the
blood of 290 innocent passengers? No.''
   He told a news conference that contrary to U.S. assertions, the
Iranian Airbus' transponder continuously ``was disseminating normal
signals ... to all radar that it was a civilian plane.''
   At the Pentagon, chief spokesman Dan Howard said Tuesday that
the Iranian airliner had been broadcasting a radio identification
signal on a frequency used only by military aircraft, leading the
skipper of the Vincennes to believe he faced attack.
   Earlier Tuesday, Iran lodged a formal, written U.N. protest,
accusing the United States of ``massacring passengers in cold
blood'' and demanding a U.N. condemnation and probe.
   In 1983, the United States had requested such a Security Council
meeting to condemn the Soviet downing of a South Korean airliner
with 269 people aboard. But the resolution of condemnation was
vetoed by the Soviet Union, one of the five permanent council
members with veto power.
   The United States also would be expected to veto a measure
critical of actions it called necessary self-defense. The five
permanent council members are the United States, the Soviet Union,
Britain, China and France.
   Diplomats said Moscow was expected to use the session to call
for withdrawal of U.S. forces from the gulf and to promote its idea
of an international naval peacekeeping force under U.N. command to
replace the American presence.
   The United States and some of its allies oppose such a force and
say the Western presence is needed to protect strategic interests
in the oil-rich gulf and freedom of navigation in the waterway.
U.S. officials have said the downing of the Iranian Airbus will not
prompt the United States to leave the gulf.
   Iran's foreign minister Ali-Akbar Velayati, sent a letter
Tuesday to Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, condemning
``this undoubtedly premeditated act of aggression.'' He said the
U.N. chief and Security Council must condemn the attack and compel
the United States to remove ``its expansionist naval forces'' from
the gulf.
   In Geneva, Perez de Cuellar indicated he had faith in the U.S.
inquiry into the incident and saw no need for a U.N. probe. He
earlier condemned ``what appears to have been a tragic error'' and
called for restraint by all parties.
   Perez de Cuellar has been trying to negotiate with Iran and Iraq
and persuade them to accept a cease-fire in their nearly 8-year-old
war. The Security Council demanded such a truce nearly a year ago.
   Mahalatti told reporters Tuesday that Iranian air force
commander Brig. Gen. Sallari, not further identified, informed him
that ``the plane for ... 14 minutes ... was disseminating the
normal signals of all civilian planes ... which proves to any radar
that this is a civilian plane.''
   ``The question is how the most sophisticated American warship in
the Persian Gulf could not receive it,'' Mahallati said.
   U.S. naval officials said the Vincennes sent seven radio signals
to the jetliner before firing, but received no reply.
</TEXT>
