<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Airliner-Reparations 1stLd-Writethru a0648 07-05 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Reparations, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Urge Compensation for Victims' Kin; Complications Seen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``The idea ...'' to
include expectations decision will be delayed; INSERTS 1 graf after
5th graf pvs, bgng: ``White House ...'' with skepticism of some
lawmakers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two senior members of Congress urged President
Reagan on Tuesday to pay compensation to families who lost
relatives aboard an Iranian jetliner downed by a U.S. missile, but
officials said the absence of diplomatic relations between the two
countries complicated such an effort.
   The idea was under active consideration at the State Department,
the Pentagon and the White House, acording to sources, and one
congressional source said it was likely the White House would make
some sort of offer to compensate victims within the next few days.
   Others, however, predicted no decision would come until after a
Navy investigative team completes its review of the incident in two
to three weeks.
   ``I think it would be a wise idea,'' said Sen. John Warner,
R-Va., the ranking Republican on the Senate Armed Services
Committee. ``There's a clear admission by our president that this
was an unfortunate accident,'' and Congress likely would provide
the money for such payments, he said.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, speaking in London, raised
the possibility that a sincere U.S. apology and an offer to
compensate bereaved families of the 290 victims of Sunday's missile
attack in the Persian Gulf might ``assuage the grief'' and would be
supported by Congress.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, asked about the
compensation issue, said ``it's a matter that has not been raised
yet'' and said it was too early to say what might happen.
   Some on Capitol Hill urged caution. ``Talk of reparations is
premature,'' said Rep. William Broomfield, R-Mich. ``They ought to
cool their heels until we have all the information.'' And Rep. Tom
Downey, D-N.Y., suggested any compensation ought to be linked to
the release of U.S. hostages being held in Lebanon.
   One congressional source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said administration officials are recommending a quick aid offer on
a humanitarian basis to differentiate the United States from the
Soviet Union, which rebuffed all requests for compensation
following its 1983 shootdown of a Korean Air Lines jetliner with
269 people aboard.
   The White House may make a public offer to compensate families,
but it is unclear how such an offer could be carried out.
   Because of the touchiness of relations between the United States
and Iran, the lack of clear precedent and the uncertainty of legal
issues involved, such an effort could take many months and is far
from certain to succeed, said legal experts in Congress and the
administration.
   Congress would take a major role in any payment, particularly in
providing the millions of dollars such a move would likely cost. In
addition, the administration would want strong backing from
lawmakers before taking a step so heavy with foreign policy
implications, officials said.
   But ultimately, the decision on whether to pay reparations would
almost certainly have to be made by President Reagan because of the
foreign policy implications of such a move, said a senior State
Department official who demanded anonymity.
   ``You've got a basic policy choice, with a very high profile,''
said another administration legal expert.
   There also is the question of legal authority for making the
payments. Under international law, no nation has to compensate for
damages that result from legitimate military operations. But the
Pentagon does have authority to make payments of up to $100,000 per
person in accidents.
   Most recently, the United States denied liability for damages to
neutral embassies in Tripoli, Libya, in a 1986 bombing raid. And
similar requests were turned down when neutral shipping was struck
during the bombing of Haiphong harbor during the Vietnam war.
   But if the damage resulted from a clear mistake, such as the
missile attack on the USS Stark by an Iraqi warplane last year that
killed 37 sailors, compensation may be paid. Iraq admitted error
almost immediately, and negotiations are continuing on the proper
amount of damages.
   The United States has compensated individuals for damage done by
troops on maneuvers in Central America, and is paying owners of a
fishing boat shot up by mistake in the Persian Gulf.
   In another incident, Israel paid reparations to the United
States following what Israel said was a mistaken attack on the USS
Liberty in 1967 during the Arab-Israeli war.
   In that case, the payment was what lawyers term ``ex gratia'' _
made out of professed sympathy, but without admitting fault or
liability. That could well be the form of any U.S. payment to
Iranian families, one official said.
   In any case, payment of reparations would require some sort of
formal contact with Iran to negotiate amounts and terms. Because
there are no diplomatic relations, such talks would be difficult to
arrange.
   The only forum where the two sides currently have regular direct
contact is a tribunal meeting in The Hague, the Netherlands, to
settle claims by both sides stemming from the 1979 Iranian
revolution.
   Any discussion of reparations would be well outside the scope of
that tribunal's official duties, said one State Department official.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
