<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Democrats-Convention 1stLd-Writethru a0702 07-05 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Convention, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson, Other Democratic Contenders May Deliver Tuesday
Convention Speeches</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new grafs 5-7 to UPDATE with comment from Jackson
aide</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic officials are discussing a plan
under which Jesse Jackson would give a prime time televised speech
on the second night of the party's national convention, as would
the other Democrats who lost out to Michael Dukakis in the fight
for the party's presidential nomination.
   Under the outline being discussed, former President Jimmy Carter
would speak during prime time on Monday night, the same evening as
a keynote speech by Texas treasurer Ann Richards and remarks by
party chairman Paul Kirk, according to officials who spoke only on
condition of anonymity.
   Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis will be formally nominated during
Wednesday night's session, and his running mate the night after.
Both Dukakis and his vice presidential partner will deliver their
acceptance speeches during Thursday's night's convention finale, as
is customary.
   Kirk met with top officials from Dukakis' and Jackson's
campaigns in Boston on Tuesday to discuss a schedule for speakers
during the four-day Democratic convention beginning July 18. The
three commercial television networks are expected to provide live
coverage for two hours on each of the four nights of the convention.
   ``We had a good meeting, a good session,'' said Ron Brown, who
is heading Jackson's convention operation.
   Brown said further meetings were planned to ``get the convention
put together.''
   Asked if any agreement had been reached on outstanding platform
issues on which Jackson has threatened to carry his fight to the
convention floor, Brown said, ``The decision is that we have no
present intention of dropping any of them.''
   Carter's prime time address would come before an audience in his
home state of Georgia, and mark a continuation of his political
rehabilitation since his 1980 defeat at President Reagan's hands.
   In addition to Jackson, officials said it was possible that
former Democratic presidential contenders Sens. Albert Gore Jr. of
Tennessee and Paul Simon of Illinois; Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri and former Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt would speak Tuesday
night. One-time front-runner Gary Hart is not expected to address
the convention; associates say he will write a newspaper column and
provide commentary for Italian television during the gathering.
   The presidential nomination roll call is expected to dominate
the Wednesday night session. Dukakis has announced that his name
will be placed in nomination by Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton. Jackson
has not yet said who will nominate him.
   Democrats will ratify Dukakis' running mate on the fourth and
final night of the convention, with Dukakis aides hoping to avoid
any rebellion by Jackson forces against their selection.
</TEXT>
