<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 2033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RotundaFacelift     07-05 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rotunda Facelift,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Capitol Rotunda's $500,000 Improvement Is Complete</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX10</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A restoration team on Tuesday finished the
year-long, $500,000 task of cleansing a century of grime from a
famous fresco on the ceiling of the Capitol rotunda.
   The cleaning was the first for ``The Apotheosis of George
Washington,'' the 4,664-square-foot work by Italian immigrant
Constantino Brumidi completed in 1865 at the apex of the then-new
rotunda.
   ``This has become a very colorful painting,'' said conservator
Bernard Rabin of Cranbury, N.J., who headed the five-person
restoration team. ``It will have almost a jewel-like quality.''
   The fresco _ a painting made on a wall as the plaster is drying
_ depicts Washington surrounded by several maidens, Greek gods,
American inventors and a host of others.
   One previous cleaning was commissioned in 1957. But officials
said the job resulted in a darkening of the fresco because the
mural painter, Allyn Cox, simply repainted it to match the dirty
colors that had accumulated over the years.
   Rabin's work has left the fresco several shades brighter than it
was.
   Workers constructed 180-foot-tall metal scaffolds to reach the
painting. Atop the scaffolds was a wooden platform just below the
fresco that the conservators stood on and which has obscured the
art from viewers.
   Conservators planned to begin Tuesday night to remove the
scaffolds, erected in June 1987, and are expected to have them
completely removed in 10 days.
   Rabin estimated that he and his helpers retouched about 5
percent of the fresco in spots where the original paint had flaked
off. The rest of their work involved removing dirt and Cox's paint,
accomplished with sponges and a solution of water and detergent.
   ``It wasn't like washing windows,'' Rabin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
