<1ST_LINE>u i AM-HongKong-Earthquake     07-05 0125</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hong Kong-Earthquake,0128</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Severe Earthquake Recorded Near Papua New Guinea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A severe earthquake was recorded Wednesday near
Papua New Guinea in the Pacific Ocean, the Hong Kong Royal
Observatory reported.
   It said the quake, which measured 6.7 on the Richter scale,
occurred at 4:40 a.m. Wednesday (4:40 p.m. EDT Tuesday), and was
centered 260 miles north-northeast of Port Moresby, the capital.
   No other information was immediately available.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph.
   An earthquake of magnitude 6 on the Richter scale can cause
severe damage in populated areas, while one measuring 7 is
considered a major quake, capable of widespread, heavy damage.
</TEXT>
