<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DefenseProbe-Chappell     07-05 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Chappell,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consultant's Dealings With Congressman Detailed On Wiretaps,
Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conversations that were secretly taped as part
of the government's investigation of Pentagon contracting show a
defense consultant raising money for projects of a powerful Florida
congressman, according to a report broadcast Tuesday.
   NBC News said it had obtained transcripts of federal wiretaps of
Charles Gardner, a former official of Unisys Corp. now working as a
consultant for defense contractors.
   Gardner organized a charity golf tournament in the district of
Rep. Bill Chappell Jr., chairman of the House defense
appropriations subcommittee, that raised nearly $100,000 from
defense contractors, NBC said.
   The FBI is investigating the tournament, which was held this
spring to raise funds for Daytona Beach Community College, the
report said.
   It is not clear if Chappell acted illegally, but it was clear
that he knew Gardner was asking the defense contractors to
contribute to the tournament, the report said.
   ``You're selling four tickets for each hole?'' the transcript
quotes Chappell as saying.
   ``No. We're selling one ticket for each hole and that admits
four people. ...,'' Gardner replies. ``That way, it is not a
donation, it's an admissions fee.''
   On the tapes, Westinghouse executive Milton Borkowski, asked to
give $5,000 to the golf tournament, complained to Gardner that
``this kind of stuff is out of control ... all this money that goes
to charities.''
   Gardner notes that Westinghouse helps make the $9 billion Aegis
ship radar system, and says it needs Chappell's support. ``Put it
in and we get the $100 million and get the ... program going,'' he
said.
   In the end, Westinghouse gave $5,000, as did 18 other defense
contractors, NBC reported.
   Calls by The Associated Press to to Chappell's offices in
Daytona Beach and Washington went unanswered Tuesday night.
   Chappell refused to grant an interview with NBC News when told
about the contents of the report, said NBC correspondent Fred
Francis.
   The wiretapped conversations also reveal that consultants knew
the Navy considered a $178 million system of electronic equipment
called CORTS, or Coherent Receive Transmit System, ``useless and
obsolete.''
   But Gardner was recorded as saying, ``We are going to rely on
Chappell not to give an inch to the Navy.'' Later, another
consultant is quoted as telling Gardner that Chappell ``dug his
heels in'' and backed the system.
   Executives of Unisys, which makes CORTS, donated $20,000 in
political contributions to Chappell in the last four years. He
insists it didn't influence his actions, NBC said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
