<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SlainAttache     07-05 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Slain Attache,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains of Slain U.S. Navy Captain Flown to United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER AIR FORCE BASE, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of U.S. Navy Capt.
William E. Nordeen, the military attache in Greece killed by a
terrorist bomb last week, arrived here Tuesday to be prepared for
burial.
   The C-5B transport plane arrived at Dover Air Force Base at 5:47
p.m. EDT to a brief planeside ceremony. Nordeen will be buried
Wednesday in Arlington National Cemetery.
   The Navy Band from Washington played the ``Navy Hymn,'' before
pallbearers slowly carried the flag-draped coffin from the plane
and loaded it into a waiting hearse.
   A 19-sailor honor guard was on hand, as well as a four-sailor
color guard.
   Vice Adm. L.A. Edney expressed his condolences to Nordeen's
family.
   ``We in the Navy are determined that Capt. Nordeen's loss not be
forgetten,'' Edney said in a statement.
   ``Bill Nordeen knew risk throughout his career. He faced it
daily in thousands of hours of flying, and he faced it again when
he volunteered for attache duty in Greece, where one of his
predecessors had been shot to death in an ambush.''
   Nordeen's wife, Patricia, and 12-year-old daughter, Annabel,
accompanied the remains on the flight. Also on board were his
brother, Navy Capt. Michael Nordeen, commanding officer of the USS
Mars in San Francisco; his brother-in-law, Michael Lilly, from
England; and Thomas J. Miller, a friend and State Department
employee in Greece.
   Nordeen's mother, Edna H. Capello, of Centuria, Wis., and other
friends and relatives also witnessed the return.
   Nordeen, 51, was killed June 28 when a bomb in a parked car
exploded, hurling his armor-plated car off the road as he was
driving to work, authorities said.
   A leftist terrorist group called November 17 took responsibility
for the attack, as it has for 13 other political assassinations in
Athens since 1975, including the murders of two other American
diplomats.
   None of the killings has been solved. Greek police, who are
being assisted by FBI and State Department investigators, say they
have made no progress in the Nordeen case so far.
   Nordeen, of Centuria, was to retire in August after 30 years in
the Navy, said his sister, Carla Anderson. He had been stationed in
Greece for three years.
</TEXT>
