<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Airliner-Flights     07-05 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Flights,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airliner Service Disrupted After Downing of Iranian Jetliner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner-Gulf, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NAZZAL YOUSSEF</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commercial flights to the
United Arab Emirates were canceled, delayed or diverted after a
U.S. warship shot down an Iranian jetliner headed to the Persian
Gulf country, airport sources said.
   Iran Air has stopped its daily flights from the Iranian airport
of Bandar Abbas across the gulf's Strait of Hormuz to Dubai
airport, airline sources said.
   It is the same flight the Iran Air aircraft was making when it
was hit Sunday by missile fire from the USS Vincennes, which U.S.
officials said mistook the Airbus 300 for an Iranian F-14 fighter
jet. Iran said all 290 aboard were killed.
   Dubai airport has canceled all flights of other airlines using
the same route over the strait, and declared a state of alert since
the downing of the Iranian plane, airport sources said.
   Air traffic to Abu Dhabi airport, 105 miles from Dubai, was
altered, causing great confusion among passengers.
   In addition to delays of several hours, flights by the region's
major carrier, Gulf Air, which were scheduled to arrive at the Abu
Dhabi airport did not come in. Passengers instead had to disembark
at Sharjah airport, about 120 miles to the south, without advance
notice, said the sources, who spoke on condition they not be
identified.
   Several passengers told The Associated Press they planned to sue
the airline or the travel agencies that were responsible.
   Japan Air Lines said Monday that its twice-weekly flight from
Tokyo to Athens has changed its Persian Gulf route to avoid the
area where the Airbus was shot down. A JAL official said the planes
will begin flying over Abu Dhabi instead of over Dubai. The route
is farther south and will add five minutes' flight time, the
official said.
   There was also conflicting information on the number and
nationalities of passengers and crew aboard the downed Airbus.
   Iranian official reports said there were 290 people aboard the
Airbus and the figure was repeated by Mustafa Foumeni Haeri,
Iranian Ambassador to the United Arab Emirates at a news conference
on Monday.
   But a manifest provided by the Iran Air office in Dubai showed
there were only 288 people, including crewmembers on board. The
list, in English, did not give nationalities for most of the
victims, who included Arabs, Pakistanis, Indians and Italians in
addition to the Iranians.
   Haeri told reporters that among the victims were Japanese and
Koreans. But the Japanese and South Korean embassies in Abu Dhabi
said that, judging from the manifest, they did not believe there
were any Japanese or Koreans on the plane.
</TEXT>
