<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Teachers-Ruckus 1stLd-Writethru a0763 07-05 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teachers-Ruckus, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0763,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Considers Strange Case of Geronimo Pratt _ And Strange
Things Happen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to restore time element</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Teachers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It started out like just another of the
myriad of social causes that teachers debate when they gather for
their annual convention.
   The 8,227 delegates gathered for the National Education
Association's annual meeting were deadlocked Tuesday on a
resolution in support of Elmer ``Geronimo'' Pratt, a convicted
murderer and former Black Panther who has been in prison since
1972. His supporters argue he didn't get a fair trial because of
FBI interference. His case has been publicized on CBS's ``60
Minutes.''
   His sister happens to be a teacher in Los Angeles, and an NEA
member.
   The voice vote was too close to call. So NEA President Mary
Hatwood Futrell ordered a roll-call vote, which the union hasn't
done in years because it is so time-consuming.
   For the next hour, as delegates awaited the results of this
somber vote, strange things began to happen in the Superdome where
the teachers were seated.
   Teachers erupted in human waves to pass the time. They tossed
beach balls, Futrell included.
   The teachers asked Futrell to sing or dance. She demurred. ``Why
don't you do the wave again?'' she asked, and they obliged,
followed by a brisk chorus of ``When the Saints Go Marching In.''
   Futrell then boasted that she had been a cheerleader in college.
This brought a loud demand for her to demonstrate her skills.
   She led a chant: ``We want a pay raise! How 'bout you?''
   After an hour, the vote was in, and it was indeed close:
   For the resolution: 3,219. Against: 3,415. Abstentions: 293.
   ``I'll tell you what,'' said Futrell. ``Now you see why we don't
have roll-call votes very often.''
</TEXT>
