<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoatCapsizes 2ndLd-Writethru a0762 07-05 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boat Capsizes, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0762,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Drowned, 1 Missing in Boat Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 2nd to UPDATE with search suspended.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-foot boat flipped over, drowning
four of 15 passengers as they returned from a Fourth of July
fireworks display, and the Coast Guard said Tuesday the craft was
overloaded and vulnerable to capsizing.
   The bodies of three of the victims were recovered and the search
of New Bedford Harbor continued for the body of a 5-year-old boy
presumed killed in the accident, New Bedford Police Officer Ray
Furtado said.
   The search was suspended because of darkness Tuesday evening,
Coast Guard Petty Officer Scott Whalen said, adding that local
authorities would resume it Wednesday without Coast Guard
assistance.
   Furtado said the boat was headed to the dock when ``two boats
passed them, one on each side, at a high rate of speed, causing
large waves.'' He said the overloaded boat flipped over.
   ``It was definitely overloaded, definitely over capacity,'' said
Coast Guard Petty Officer David Foley of the number of people on
the boat.
   The manufacturer's recommended capacity for the fiberglass boat
was 2,000 pounds, according to a plate attached to it. Empty, there
would be between two and three feet between the water and the top
edge of the boat, said Coast Guard Lt. Robert Campbell.
   With 15 people aboard ``at best it would have been half that,''
Campbell said. ``All it would take would be a foot and a half of
sea'' to tip the boat.
   Petty Officer 1st Class Brandy Ian said there were about 100
boats in the area when the accident occurred. Other boaters rescued
the 11 survivors.
   Federal maritime law does not set limits on boat occupancy, but
negligence can be penalized with a $1,000 fine, Ms. Ian said.
   The owner and operator of the boat was Barry Constant, 31, of
North Dartmouth. He told police that none of his passengers wore
lifejackets, although the boat was equipped with them.
   The dead were Jean Fauteaux, 49, Maria Carvalho, 27, and her
daughter, Melissa, all of North Dartmouth. The missing boy is
Kenneth Carvalho.
   State police and the Bristol County district attorney's office
also were investigating the accident.
</TEXT>
