<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-France     07-05 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-France,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Ambassador Presents Credentials In Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France's newly appointed ambassador to
Iran presented his credentials in Tehran, ending a one-year
diplomatic rupture, Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency
said Tuesday.
   But Iran said Paris should be more critical of the downing of an
Iranian airliner by the U.S. Navy.
   IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, said Ambassador Christian Graeff
presented his documents to Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati on
Monday.
   In his meeting with Velayati, Graeff expressed ``deep regret''
over the U.S. downing Monday of an Iranian jetliner in the Persian
Gulf. Iran says all 290 aboard died. The French Foreign Ministry
also commented on the incident.
   But IRNA quoted Iran's amabassador to France, Ali Ahani, as
telling a news conference in Paris Monday that ``Iran expects
France to be a little more candid in its official statement on the
incident and show less reservation in reacting to it.''
   The two countries broke off relations July 17 last year after
Iranian Embassy officials in Paris refused to let French
authorities question an embassy translator suspected of terrorist
involvement.
   French police surrounded the embassy. In turn, Iranian troops
sealed off the French Embassy in Tehran. France said Iran had
effectively severed relations.
   Iran and France named ambassadors to each other's capitals on
June 23, a week after they announced resumption of relations
following the May 5 release of the last three Franch hostages held
by Iranian-backed Moslem militants in Lebanon.
   Sources have said the conditions for the hostages' release
centered on repayment of $1 billion loan made by Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi of Iran before the Islamic revolution in 1979.
