<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims New Heights Liberated in Kurdistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said Tuesday its forces recaptured
two mountain peaks in a 16-hour battle with Iranian troops in
northern Kurdistan province.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said the
Balgha and Dobzah mountaintops, 7,805 feet and 7,591 feet above sea
level, respectively, were ``liberated, marking a new defeat for the
rotten heads in Tehran.''
   There was no immediate Iranian comment.
   Both heights overlook Tikrit, President Saddam Hussein's
hometown, which is about 60 miles north of Baghdad.
   Iraq's 5th Army Corps recently has mounted assaults to dislodge
Iran from lands it occupies in Kurdistan, a mountainous region
inhabited mainly by Iranian-backed Kurdish rebels fighting the
Baghdad government for autonomy.
   But the Iranians still hold the key border towns of Halabja,
Panjawin and Hajj Omran.
   Since April, the Iraqis also have recovered the Faw peninsula
and the oil-rich Majnoon islands in southern Iraq and claim to have
retaken heights in the central sector of the the 730-mile warfront.
   The battles shifted the balance in Iraq's favor and marked a new
turn in the nearly 8-year-old Persian Gulf war in which Iraq was
mostly on the defensive.
   Iranian officials have claimed the United States was helping
Iraq and called for general mobilization along the front.
   INA said thousands of Iranians were killed, wounded or captured
in the latest battle that began at 4 a.m. Tuesday (8 p.m. EDT
Monday) and continued through the day.
   ``These events prove that the defeat of the Iranian regime is
imminent, God willing,'' the agency quoted an unidentified military
spokesman as saying.
</TEXT>
