<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Candidates-Teachers 1stLd-Writethru a0798 07-05 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidates-Teachers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0798,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis And Jackson Speak Via Satellite At Teachers' Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 4 grafs with Dukakis comments to NEA in New Orleans</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 3,000 delegates of the American
Federation of Teachers gave their unofficial nod to Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis, but it was Jesse Jackson's praise of teachers
that brought the crowd to its feet on Tuesday.
   Both presidential candidates addressed the convention via
satellite as the four-day gathering was ending.
   ``If we are going to take on our foreign competitors, we have to
make teaching an honored and valued profession again,'' said
Dukakis, who spoke from Boston.
   The Massachusetts governor, the likely Democratic nominee,
called for an educational venture capital fund to improve teachers'
pay and training. He said the cost would be a fraction of the
budget for the Reagan administration's Strategic Defense Initiative.
   Dukakis told representatives of the 677,000-member union that
the election ``will be the most important and closest since 1960.''
   The AFT, like other AFL-CIO unions, refrained from endorsing
anyone before the Democratic and Republican conventions. But it
will send more than 150 delegates to the Democratic convention _
three-quarters of them for Dukakis and the rest for Jackson.
   ``Obviously we're leaning toward Dukakis because he's the
front-runner candidate,'' said Steve Hahn, publicist for the AFT.
   Dukakis's remarks followed Jackson's impassioned appeal for
doubling teachers' pay and his call for all of society to take
responsibility for educating children.
   ``The mass media, the churches and temples have a broader
responsibility,'' said Jackson, speaking from New York City.
   ``If the schools give homework, the parents must have the child
home to do the homework. We must pay for better educational
services ... by doubling the pay of teachers, as our most
fundamental investment in the future of America.''
   He called the relationship between his mother, his teacher and
his principal a ``love triangle'' that helped him succeed.
   Jackson recalled his strict sixth-grade teacher promising the
class, ``I will never teach down to you'' and telling the students
that ``one of you...may become governor or president someday.''
   Also on Tuesday, the delegates passed a resolution seeking
protection for gay and lesbian teachers against discrimination in
hiring, promotion and all aspects of teaching.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis also hooked up by satellite with the National
Education Association, meeting in New Orleans, and apologized for
not being there in person.
   ``But with a little luck, we should be able to visit each other
often in Washington after November,'' he told the more than 8,000
teacher delegates.
   NEA president Mary Hatwood Futrell told Dukakis that ``we've
always considered you to be a friend of working men and women,
especially those in the public sector.''
   Last week, at Futrell's urging, the NEA board of directors
endorsed Dukakis for the Democratic nomination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880705-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 2225EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0789 07-05 0877</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0789,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Talks To Former Rivals In Veep Search; Reagan Praises Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf pvs with Gore meeting over</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis picked up the pace in his search for a
running mate Tuesday, bringing in former rivals Albert Gore Jr. and
Richard Gephardt for face-to-face talks. Gephardt said he'd take
the job, but Jesse Jackson dismissed contenders other than himself
as ``unknown quantities.''
   President Reagan promoted George Bush as his White House
successor, suggesting voters would choose the vice president over
``out-and-out liberal'' Dukakis if they did ``a little comparison
shopping.''
   Dukakis, meeting briefly with reporters in Boston, criticized
the administration for ``one scandal after another'' after Attorney
General Edwin Meese III announced his resignation.
   Vice President Bush, out of the public eye at the White House
all day, said through a spokesman, ``Ed did the right thing and I
wish him well.''
   Bush was mentioned by Meese, who spoke to reporters in
California after the independent counsel investigating his conduct
in office filed a report concluding there was no basis for criminal
indictment.
   Meese thanked Bush ``for his fairness and decency in regard to
this matter.'' Republican strategists, including several Bush
aides, had said Meese's legal problems were hurting Bush, who has
campaigned on the Reagan administration's record, but the vice
president never publicly criticized Meese or called for his
resignation.
   Dukakis, however, said, ``I think the Meese resignation is long
overdue. I never thought he should have been appointed in the first
place.''
   He added, ``The Meese resignation itself is not going to solve
this administration's problems. ... This administration has had one
scandal after another, one resignation after another.''
   In Boston, Dukakis met for more than an hour with Gephardt in
his Statehouse office.
   When the Missouri congressman was asked afterward whether he he
would accept a spot on the ticket, if offered, he said, ``I would
do that.''
   ``I want Mike Dukakis to be elected president and I want him to
be a great president and I will do everything I can to that end,''
he said.
   Gore met with Dukakis at the governor's Brookline hme for just
over an hour Tuesday evening. He made no comment to reporters as he
arrived, and when he emerged, he said only, ``I don't have a
statement.''
   The president told a conservative gathering in Washington, ``The
American people understand what liberalism means and don't like it,
so our opponents plan to go to the voters incognito _ they're
putting on political trench coats and sunglasses.''
   Reagan quipped that the Democrats ``will never even in the
lowest whisper mumble the `L' word again.''
   Gore, the Tennessee senator, and Gephardt flew to Boston at
Dukakis' invitation. The vanquished rivals treated Dukakis harshly
during the heat of the primary campaign but both men eventually
endorsed the Massachusetts governor.
   In addition, Dukakis scheduled a meeting with Indiana Rep. Lee
Hamilton on Wednesday. The private sessions fueled speculation that
the certain Democratic nominee was moving closer to naming a
running mate.
   Jackson, who dined and watched fireworks with Dukakis and his
wife Monday night, said Tuesday he was the most qualified for the
vice presidential nomination but continued to duck questions about
whether he would accept the spot if it was offered to him.
   ``The fact of the matter is, I would be an asset,'' Jackson
said. ``I'm convinced that my presence would unleash new hope in
this country, regain more people.''
   ``The others under consideration are unknown quantities beyond
their districts and beyond their home states,'' Jackson said in
Boston before leaving for New York, where he held a series of
editorial board meetings.
   Aides to Jackson and Dukakis, meanwhile, began discussing their
pre-convention differences, with party chairman Paul Kirk at hand.
The two campaigns remain apart on several platform issues but
Jackson painted a picture of unity and predicted a convention ``far
less hostile and rancorous than past years.''
   The Democrats' keynote speaker, Texas treasurer Ann Richards,
paid a courtesy call on Dukakis and came away with a
``comfortable'' impression of him. But the feisty Richards, asked
if Dukakis had any recommendations for her speech, smiled and said,
``Michael Dukakis isn't going to tell me what to say.''
   Democratic officials were discussing a tentative convention
framework in which Jackson would deliver a prime time television
speech on Tuesday night, the second night of the party sessions,
sources said.
   These sources, who asked not to be identified by name, said
several other vanquished primary contenders would likely speak
during prime time on the same evening, including Gore, Gephardt,
Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois and former Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt.
   Former President Carter is expected to make a prime time
appearance on Monday night, the first night of the convention.
   Dukakis will be nominated on Wednesday night, as is customary,
and he and his vice presidential running mate will deliver
acceptance speeches on Thursday night, the final night of the
convention, the sources said.
   Dukakis is scheduled to return to Washington next week to hold
pre-convention meetings with House leaders. Some Dukakis aides held
out the possibility that a decision on a running mate might be made
by then although they insisted there was no timetable.
</TEXT>
