<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 2257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SalemExplosion     07-05 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salem Explosion,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Perplexed After Finding 13 Incendiary Devices in Salem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bomb squads temporarily sealed off parts of
Salem Tuesday as three incendiary bombs exploded and 10 others were
found outside buildings and under bridges leading to the city.
   The bombs that exploded caused only small fires and no one was
injured. Bomb disposal experts managed to defuse the other devices.
   ``We have no indications of any motive at this time. We have no
suspects,'' said Sgt. Marvin Jenkins of the Indiana State Police.
``Due to the fact no one has been injured and there's no property
damage yet, we're very strongly hoping that this is just a poor
joke.''
   But Mayor Frank Newkirk Sr., who found one of the bombs next to
a bridge, said the planting of the devices ``was obviously an act
of terrorism in my book, certainly done by a wacko.''
   This quiet, southern Indiana community of 6,000 residents is
surrounded by the Blue River and Brock Creek. Bombs were laid under
all six bridges leading into the city.
   Portions of the town were sealed off temporarily as bomb
disposal squads from Fort Benjamin Harrison in Indianapolis and
Fort Knox in Kentucky defused 10 devices, each of which contained
timers attached to as many as 26 sticks of dynamite and were
concealed in paper grocery sacks.
   The Washington County Courthouse was evacuated as were several
businesses, said Paul Lyles, emergency management director for the
county Department of Civil Defense.
   The bombs were hidden under sticks and other debris, Lyles said.
   The devices that went off produced only smoke and small fires,
and their construction indicated the person responsible was not
experienced in handling explosives, he said.
   ``They used black powder as the cap, and it didn't detonate.
Luckily, the guy who put it there didn't know much about
explosives,'' Lyles said.
   ``The incendiary devices were not set so much to go bang but to
set fires,'' said Lt. Ken Hollingsworth of state police.
   All of the bombs were turned over to agents of the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, which was investigating along with
the FBI, Indiana State Police, Army experts and local officials.
   A spokesman for the sheriff's department said a transient
believed to be from Arkansas was picked up for questioning Tuesday
morning. However, there was no word Tuesday night on any arrests.
   Most of the devices were found during the morning, with the
first discovered about 3 a.m., the sheriff's department said.
   Although people were allowed to return to the business district
during the afternoon, Lyles said: ``We're still cautious. ...
People should continue to look because they may not all be
located.''
   Morris Strange, who lives across from a service station where
one device was found, said he arrived home to find officials
surrounding it. ``Of course I was scared. You don't expect this to
happen in any town in the U.S. This isn't the Middle East.''
</TEXT>
