<HEAD>Prime Minister Undergoes Surgery, Reported In Good Spirits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister David Lange
underwent surgery Wednesday to remove a lesion from a coronary
artery, and was resting comfortably after the operation, a
spokesman for his office said.
   Lange, 45, was admitted to Auckland's Green Lane Hospital last
Saturday after suffering from chest pains. The pains returned on
Tuesday and the surgery took place early Wednesday, said the
spokesman, who was not identified.
   The spokesman said the surgery, called a balloon angioplasty,
involved using a catherer inserted through the armpit to place a
small balloon across the narrow part of the coronary artery.
   The operation was performed under local anaesthetic without
complications.
   Lange's condition was ``comfortable'' and he was in good
spirits, the spokesman said.
   A spokesman for the hospital's cardiology department said full
surgery was ``not being seriously considered.'' He said it was
hoped Lange would be discharged around the middle of next week.
   Deputy Prime Minister Geoffrey Palmer is acting as prime
minister during Lange's hospitalization.
