<2ND_LINE>AM-ABC-Israel,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC Protests Impersonation of Its Reporters by Israeli Security
Forces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli security forces impersonated an ABC news
television crew to trick a Palestinian youth into coming with them
and then arrested him, the network charged Tuesday.
   ABC President Roone Arledge sent a telex Tuesday to Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir protesting the incident 1{ weeks ago,
said Elise Adde, ABC's director of news information.
   As of Tuesday evening, there had been no response from the
Israeli government, she said.
   ABC World News Tonight on Tuesday aired a report saying Nizar
Dakdouk was arrested by Israeli civilians posing as ABC News
personnel.
   Dakdouk's family home in Bethlehem was demolished June 16
because the Israeli army said he had thrown a firebomb at a bus,
according to the report. The next day, the youth and his mother
complained on Israeli television that if he was suspected of
something the army should have arrested him before blowing up the
house, ABC said.
   A week after the television appearance, two carloads of Israeli
civilians posing as ABC News personnel arrived at the Dakdouk
family's temporary housing in the village of Salfit and said they
wanted to interview Dakdouk and his brother on the site of the
destroyed house, the report said. The boys agreed to go.
   Once they were at the site, one of the cars sped off with
Dakdouk, and he was later arrested, ABC said.
   ``ABC News is deeply distressed by this and insists that an
investigation be conducted immediately to ascertain who authorized
such an action,'' said Arledge in the meessage to Shamir.
   ``There are no circumstances that could justify security forces
impersonating ABC News personnel,'' he said. ``Such activity
presents grave perils to the safety of legitimate journalists.''
   ABC News reported in Tuesday's broadcast that it had learned
that ``the impostors were members of the Israeli secret security
service, Shin Bet.'' It said a Shamir spokesman, who was not
identified, said he knew nothing of the incident.
</TEXT>
