<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Strike,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10,000 Yugoslavs Rally, Shouting `Down with Government!'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VUKOVAR, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 10,000 Yugoslavs demonstrated
in this central town on Tuesday, shouting ``Down with the
government!'' and demanding higher wages, witnesses and the Tanjug
news agency said.
   Most were workers from a major shoe and rubbber factory, Borovo,
who went on strike last Saturday, Tanjug said. They want 100
percent pay increases and full instead of partial payment of wages
for June.
   Current wage scales were not available.
   The strike was the latest in a series of recent actions in
different parts of communist Yugoslavia protesting new economic
measures.
   The government in May linked wages to productivity as part of a
severe austerity program designed to cut inflation, now running at
about 175 percent, and improve economic performance.
   Government officials claim no alternative to the program exists
if the country wants to pay off its $21 billion foreign debt.
   Witnesses told The Associated Press by telephone from Vukovar,
about 60 miles west of Belgrade, that demonstrators carrying
Communist Party and Yugoslav flags demanded changes in the
country's leadership.
   They refused to return to work despite repeated appeals and
promises by local officials, Tanjug said.
   Yugoslavia listed a record 1,600 strikes last year, involving
over 300,000 workers, but most of those work stoppages did not go
beyond factories.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
