<HEAD>Parliament Endorses Roh's Nomination Of New Chief Justice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition-controlled National
Assembly on Tuesday overwhelmingly approved President Roh Tae-woo's
nomination of noted moderate Lee Il-kyu as new chief justice,
ending a prolonged dispute.
   The unicameral parliament endorsed the 68-year-old Lee as chief
justice of the Supreme Court and head of the judicial system by a
vote of 275 to 14, with three absentions.
   His term will be limited to two years, since the legal age limit
for chief justice is 70. Lee, a former Supreme Court justice, is
known for his lack of involvement in politics.
   The assembly last week rejected Roh's first nominee for the job,
Chung Ki-Sung, in a major setback for the president, who took
office in February for a five-year term.
   Lee succeeds Kim Yong-chul, 60, who resigned last month under
pressure from hundreds of junior judges demanding democratic reform.
</TEXT>
