</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Democratic National Convention throws
its spotlight on Atlanta, two distinct black communities will share
the stage _ one elite, well-to-do and often associated with
government officials, the other poor and struggling.
   This city, long regarded as a pioneer for black progress and a
center for nearly every aspect of black culture and politics, is
faced with a deteroriating relationship between the two classes of
blacks.
   One source of the problem is that blacks do not control the
economic pursestrings in Atlanta, even though they hold top
political offices, according to Lyndon Wade, executive director of
the Atlanta Urban League.
   ``You cannot run a city with politics alone; you must have an
economic base to make it go. That's why there's a lot of pressure
in the older black community,'' said Wade.
   Tensions between the two classes begin early, according to
Morehouse College sociologist Anna Grant. In school, poor children
start to understand that some of their black classmates enjoy
material advantages inaccessible to them. Since the city's elected
black officials usually are among the elite, the poor come to view
government and the elite as one.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court on Tuesday recessed the
trial of a Lebanese Shiite Moslem accused in the 1985 hijacking of
a TWA airliner, after he refused to take part in the first day of
proceedings.
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi, who is charged with murder and air piracy,
cited disputes over his interpreter and his legal representation
