<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Shanghai'sSlump Adv12   07-05 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shanghai's Slump, Adv 12,0815</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs July 12 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fallen from No. 1 Spot in China, Shanghai Finds Comeback is Hard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANGHAI, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shanghai doesn't look like a city in a
slump.
   It's streets are alive with well-dressed shoppers. Its
commercial lifeline, the Huangpu River, is jammed with freighters
and fishing craft.
   The Bund, the riverfront avenue lined with massive banks and
hotels built by European traders early in the century, remains a
symbol of Shanghai's longtime status as China's commercial and
industrial capital.
   But the city of 12 million people lost its position as China's
No. 1 industrial power in 1985 to neighboring Jiangsu province. It
lost its rank as the No. 1 export earner to southern Guangdong
province, which benefits from being next door to Hong Kong.
   Shanghai's revenues have fallen steadily for the past three
years, and worker productivity also has dropped. Industry grew 6.8
percent last year, well behind the national pace of 16.5 percent.
   Roads, sewers and water pipes built early in the century are
inadequate for present needs. Its industrial technology is outdated
and half the housing predates the 1949 communist takeover.
   Just one telephone is available for every 63 residents; it can
take hours to get a line to call across town.
   Shanghai's planners and business leaders also have not been
agile enough to keep up with China's shift from central planning
and insularity to freer markets, competition and growing trade.
   Jiangsu province and Canton, the capital of Guangdong province,
took advantage of the new policies after 1978 to set up thousands
of small, trade-oriented enterprises.
   Shanghai, bastion of centrally controlled heavy industry,
remained mired in the old system with the state making production
decisions and acting as trade go-between.
   Yang Zhihua, deputy director of the city Planning Commission,
noted in an interview that Shanghai's gross production of goods and
services is still No. 1 nationally, at the yuan equivalent of $14
billion, and that hundreds of Shanghai's products, from steel to
toothpaste, dominate domestic markets.
   ``We're not lagging behind in everything, just in some things,
such as exports and absorption of foreign investment,'' he said.
``We can easily catch up.''
   But the city's performance in the past two years indicate that
might not be easy. In early 1986, city leaders announced plans for
a subway, a new airport terminal, a new railroad station, a tunnel
and other projects to stimulate growth and attract foreign business.
   Only the rail station has been completed. The subway is stalled
by red tape and scarce funds, leaving Shanghai's 15,000 buses and
taxis to carry more than 15 million riders a day through narrow
streets where traffic crawls at a norm of less than five miles an
hour.
   A year-end city report said the problems in housing, traffic
congestion and pollution were acute.
   ``The reason lies in our thinking,'' Yang said. ``We were used
to the past planned economic model.''
   Three-fourths of Shanghai's factories are owned and controlled
by the central government in Beijing. Bloated workers and dependent
upon the state for bailouts, they have not kept up with China's new
atmosphere of competition.
   Central planning also has forced Shanghai to give most of its
revenue to Beijing, retaining little for itself. Its annual
contribution to Beijing of more than $2.7 billion is 10 times that
of Guangdong, which has less state-owned industry.
   ``The central government owes Shanghai a big debt,'' said a
local economist, Zhou Jianming.
   Mayor Zhu Rongji took office in April determined to reverse
Shanghai's decline.
   He speaks fluent English and has a salesman's manner. At a
recent trade conference in Beijing, he assured nearly 1,000
American businessmen they will be able to repatriate profits if
they invest in Shanghai, promising in English, ``No matter how much
money foreign investors make in Shanghai, we won't be jealous.''
   The audience, after listening to jargon-larded translations of
Chinese-language speeches by other officials, laughed and applauded.
   Zhu's plan calls for attracting billions of U.S. dollars in
foreign investment and borrowing millions more to revive the
infrastructure projects and import updated technology.
   He has formed a commission with himself as chairman to
investigate ways of attracting capital and simplifying investment
procedures.
   Shanghai's state-owned factories also have begun slowly to adapt
to new economic realities. Seven television and electronics
factories recently formed their own export corporation to increase
foreign sales.
   Shanghai also is trying to catch some of the rough-and-tumble
enterpreneurial spirit that has worked so well in Canton and the
rest of Guangdong, which racked up a 17 percent growth rate last
year.
   ``Shanghai follows the (state) regulations,'' Yang said. ``In
Canton, they don't worry about the regulations.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs July 12</NOTE>
