<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv08   07-05 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 08,0671</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, July 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 400 plans exist among various
Christian organizations to evangelize the world by the end of this
century, says a key figure in steps to coordinate the efforts.
   The Rev. Thomas Wang, steering committee chairman of a
consultation planned by the different groups for next January, says
many of such past efforts have failed because of disorganization,
isolation and competition.
   ``What's happening now is very different,'' he said at a program
committee meeting at headquarters of one of the major groups, the
Southern Baptist Foreign Mission Board, to plan an agenda for the
world consultation.
   ``All of a sudden it seems many of God's servants all over the
world have begun to take the end of this century, not as a magical
number, but as a target, a goal, a stimulation for world
evangelism,'' he said.
   ``There has never been an age in the history of the church that
is more qualified to tackle this task of world evangelization in
terms of manpower, resources, technology, communications and
transportation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Claire Randall, for 11 years general secretary
of the National Council of Churches, was installed here as national
president of Church Women United for the 1988-92 quadrennium.
   A Presbytertian, Ms. Randall left the council post in 1984,
succeeded by the Rev. Arie Brouwer of the Reformed Church in
America.
   Church Women United is a national ecumenical body of about
500,000 Protestant, Eastern Orthodox and Roman Catholic women.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Presidents of Major American
Jewish Organizations says the Arab-Israel violence in Gaza and the
West Bank can be ended through territorial compromise if
Palestinians accept Israel's right to exist.
   Moris B. Abram told a Sabbath congregation that ``Israelis must
convince the Palestinians that if they recognize Israel and
forswear their covenant of violence, territorial compromise becomes
a realistic goal.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ann N. Beardslee has been appointed acting
executive director of Church World Service, a post from which J.
Richard Butler resigned in May in a conflict with the Rev. Arie
Brouwer, chief executive of the National Council of Churches.
   CWS is the council's relief arm. Ms. Beardslee has been its
assistant executive director.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teen-agers are using drugs less and
volunteering extensively for charitable work, according to a Gallup
poll conducted for the Religious Research Center.
   Only 11 percent of teen-agers admit to using marijuana, compared
to 39 percent who did so in 1978.
   The survey also found that 24 percent of America's teens are
volunteering for charitable causes or social services. Those who
attend church regularly are twice as likely to volunteer time as
those who don't attend regularly _ 31 percent versus 16 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The general synod of the Reformed Church in
America in June voted 139-132 to encourage congregations to include
``baptized children at the Lord's Table.''
   Previously, only professed members were invited to receive Holy
Communion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly of Religious Women has
commended the decision of the Notre Dame Sisters de Namur not to
dismiss two sisters who question Roman Catholicism's ban on all
abortions.
   The two sisters, Barbara Ferraro and Patricia Hussey, run a
shelter for the homeless in Charleston, S.C.
   The NARW applauded them for upholding the right of responsibile
dissent, and calling for dialogue on a controversial moral issue.
   They were among 26 nuns who came under a Vatican ultimatum to be
ousted or recant their signing of a 1984 New York Times ad terming
diverse Catholic views of abortion legitimate.
   Cases of the others were resolved earlier, and the order of the
two recently declined to dismiss them despite their refusal to
condemn all abortions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, July 8</NOTE>
