<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv10   07-05 0889</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 10,0916</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release Sunday, July 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   TV audiences will soon get their first real
chance to hear pianist Vladimir Feltsman, who emigrated to America
last summer after much publicized difficulties in getting out of
Russia. On Wednesday, July 13, he will perform in a ``Live from
Lincoln Center'' telecast on PBS.
   ``This will be my first purely musical TV event,'' says the
36-year-old Feltsman. ``Playing in the White House (Sept. 27) and
my debut at Carnegie Hall (Nov. 11) were shown on the news, a
little. I was on the `60 Minutes' show. It was more talking than
music.''
   The Mostly Mozart Festival, now in its 22nd year at Avery Fisher
Hall, will open with Feltsman on Tuesday, July 12. The program will
be repeated on Wednesday night and televised live.
   ``Mostly Mozart is one of the leading music festivals in the
world. I am very pleased I have been invited,'' says Feltsman. ``I
will play Mozart's `Piano Concerto in B flat major,' the last by
Mozart. He was composing it at the same time he was composing `The
Magic Flute.' It is an absolute masterpiece.
   ``Then Frederica von Stade will sing something, and then we will
do an aria by Mozart together, so I think it will be fun.''
   Since arriving in America, Feltsman has played 60 performances.
``This season has been very special for me,'' he says, ``because I
am doing everything for the first time _ the first time in
Philadelphia, Israel, New York, Chicago, Los Angeles.''
   Feltsman was considered one of the Soviet Union's best young
pianists when he applied, in April 1979, for an emigration visa.
That year, he says, 52,000 Soviet Jews emigrated. But his
application was denied. Two hours after he applied, Moscow radio
and TV stations were ordered not to play his records. All his
concerts were canceled for two years. Then for the next six years,
Feltsman was allowed to give a few concerts, one such in a factory
where machinery all but drowned out his music.
   On June 14, 1982, Feltsman supporters, who knew him through
recordings and European concerts, scheduled his ``New York debut,''
to publicize his plight. Misha Dichter played that evening.
   Five years later, Feltsman's emigration was approved. Alice
Chandler, president of the State University of New York in New
Paltz, who had looked up Feltsman when she visited Russia,
telephoned to offer him a job. Feltsman, his wife Anna and son
Daniel arrived in New York last August.
   Their 5-year-old son is settled into nursery school and already
finds it easier to speak English than Russian. As for his and his
wife's adjustment, Feltsman says, ``We came here more or less well
prepared. We were not looking for some miracles. We understand that
it is a beautiful country with many problems, which we all know.
   ``Paradise does not exist in the world, as we also know. For
people of my occupation, my mentality, my psychology, my ability,
I'm certain it is still the best place in the world.''
   Feltsman's debut with symphony orchestra was in February with
Zubin Mehta and the New York Philharmonic. ``From then till this
fall I'm playing 10 different concertos and three different recital
programs. It's a little bit tough.''
   In May, Feltsman played a piano sonata by Alfred Schnittke. The
Soviet composer and his wife were allowed to travel to New York for
the occasion. ``This single fact assured me about glasnost much
more than speeches made by Soviet officials,'' he says. ``A few
years ago such a visit of a leading Soviet composer and playing by
a Jewish immigrant was unimaginable. Now it is real. I hope such a
normal attitude will go forward.''
   In addition to his concerts, Feltsman is cutting records and
talking about a special school for budding American pianists. He
has made two recordings already and soon will make two more.
   ``I think recording is one of the most important parts of the
life of a musician,'' he says. ``The performing artist plays, and
it is disappearing in air. Now I'm already thinking, not about
success, but about leaving some legacy.''
   Part of that legacy, too, could be a special program for
promising young American pianists. Of those he's worked with, he
says, ``Their main trouble, even for the best I heard, is their
training at a very early age. If you miss something at 6, 7, 8 or
9, technically, physically, psychologically, you will never get it
back later.''
   Feltsman has talked with some wealthy people about endowing a
school, free but available only to the most gifted.
   ``With such things as music, if you want to get good results you
have to be very tough at the beginning,'' he says. ``And the
principle has to be talent, not ability to pay. You cannot buy a
musical gift with money.''
   Asked whether he'll be nervous about the Mostly Mozart opening
and televised concert, Feltsman says, ``I am very nervous always.
   ``Probably that's the way you have to pay for the joy to play
the music.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 10</NOTE>
