<DOCNO> AP880705-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--EuthanasiaIII Adv17-1stAdd   07-05 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Euthanasia III, Adv 17-1st Add,0553</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>EVANSVILLE: and frustration.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``We have residents still afraid he might come,'' Barbara
Walters, director of nursing at Crestview Manor, said in a recent
interview while Carlson was free on bail to go wherever he wanted
except to the nursing home and to friends' homes where he once had
been invited but was now unwelcome.
   ``I went through every stage of grieving, and I still feel very
angry,'' said Walters, looking out over the lounge area where
pitiful residents sat, one a 102-year-old woman, her head buried in
her hands. Two other residents in the room with Agnes when she was
shot also suffer from Alzheimer's. Other residents followed the
tragedy on the television set in the lounge and in the newspapers.
   ``The staff is still angry,'' says Mrs. Walters. ``I think we
feel kind of violated. How would you feel if someone came into your
home and shot somebody. It's a small facility, 70 beds. We pretty
much feel like all family.''
   Jennie Harjes, assistant director of nursing, remembered that
two days before Agnes was shot, she recognized a visitor and called
her by name. ``That's the way Alzheimer's is,'' she says.
   Both staff and residents of the nursing home have suffered
nightmares.
   ``I dream that I'm here at work and that I'm trying to do my job
and I see Oscar,'' says Harjes. ``He's interfering with my being
able to do my job. It has interfered in all our lives, made it
uneasy for all of us. He's just there, his presence is there.''
   ``When it first happened,'' says Judy Berg, ``I'd wake up in the
middle of the night. When I tried to go back to sleep, I'd see it
... To me, it wasn't a mercy killing. The woman was in no pain
except she'd broken her hip. She wasn't the one suffering. It was
Oscar watching her state of Alzheimer's.''
   Says Bonnie Champeau, director of Crestview Manor: ``A murder
was committed here. Mercy killing or euthanasia is basically done
to relieve pain. It's usually not done to relieve the mental pain
of family members. It's usually not done with four shots from a gun
for other people to witness and live with.''
   Many of the elderly people, particularly women, feared Carlson
while he was free awaiting sentencing. Friends who know him well
welcomed him even though they were angry with him at first. His
family felt he needed daily supervision. Eight nursing homes turned
him away because they feared he would upset other residents. His
attorney, Thomas J. Reif, finally found one willing to accept him
in the interim.
   The issue, says Ann L. Carrott, the Douglas County prosecutor,
is whether Carlson had the right to decide whether his wife
couldn't take it anymore. She says she had to treat the shooting as
a murder and that she is opposed to lessening the degree of guilt
in mercy killings.
   ``Where do you draw the line?'' she asks. ``What type of illness
would warrant that kind of a defense? Is it going to be based on
illness or age or disability? I don't know that society wants to
start drawing those kinds of lines.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
