<DOCNO> AP880705-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--EuthanasiaIII Adv17-2ndAdd   07-05 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Euthanasia III, Adv 17-2nd Add,0813</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>EVANSVILLE: of lines.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Agnes Carlson was 72 years old. Her mental condition had
worsened to the point where her mind often was fixed in the '40s
when Oscar came home from World War II. She thought he was her
father and began calling him grandpa. Agnes' family name also was
Carlson, and her father's first name was Alven.
   ``She would make up an extra bed in the evening, like on the
sofa. Either she should sleep there or I should sleep there,'' says
Carlson. ``That often happened. If she would lie down there, I
said, `You better come to me,' and we would lie down and say our
prayers, and then I'd say, `You can go back if you want to,' but
she never did.''
   She hid his mail. ``Those letters that had money and the checks
like Social Security, they were to Oscar Carlson and I was supposed
to be Alven Carlson so I wasn't supposed to have anything to do
with them.''
   She longed to visit apple orchards that had vanished with her
memory. Says Carlson: ``A lot of times in the evenings she would
say, `Why don't we take a drive down to my folks' place.' And I
would tell her that there's no place there anymore. The house was
burned down and they plowed down the apple orchard. So there was
nothing to go for, but I would usually take her down there.''
   She sometimes didn't bathe for weeks. ``She was kind of shy so
she done the best she could on that herself.''
   Sometimes Oscar helped her wash her hair. ``I always set her
hair every week.''
   This wasn't the Agnes that Oscar and their three daughters
remembered. Oscar met Agnes in April 1940 when Agnes'
brother-in-law, a customer of a butcher shop in Miltona where Oscar
worked, asked him to give her a ride to Evansville one Sunday.
Oscar told his brother, ``That's one girl I got to take out again.''
   He made a date with her for the following Wednesday night. Six
months later they were married on the farm where he was born. He
and Agnes ran a meat market until 1942 when he went into the Army.
After his discharge in 1945, they started farming 80 acres they had
bought before he went into the service.
   When his three daughters finally persuaded him she should be
placed in a nursing home in June 1987, things got worse for him
instead of better. Filled with guilt and depression, he no longer
felt like pulling the weeds in the garden, as he put it.
   Reif, his attorney, says he intentionally avoided referring to
the shooting as a mercy killing.
   ``We do not think what Oscar did was premeditated, thought out
or planned in the type of detail that a mercy killer would normally
do,'' he says.
   But according to Bruce Montplaisir, Carlson's son-in-law, Oscar
had told people Agnes would be better off dead.
   ``The morning when we put her in the nursing home,'' Montplaisir
recalled, ``he'd said, `I'm a hundred percent for that. You know,
I'm the kind of guy that could shoot his own dog.' I think he felt
that he was almost to the point that his only relief would be to
get her into the nursing home before something like that would
happen.''
   Shortly before Agnes was shot, nursing home officials expressed
concern to one of his daughters, Mary Beth Montplaisir, telling her
that Carlson had said, ``Maybe if you don't feed her so much she
wouldn't live so long.''
   Mary Beth says that about two weeks before the shooting, she had
talked to nursing home officials about removing two guns from her
father's home. But before the three daughters could meet with a
social worker to discuss it, their mother was dead.
   ``I feel kind of an anger at the whole system,'' says the
daughter, a grade school remedial reading and math teacher. ``I
feel more frustration because I wanted to keep something like this
from happening, and I was not able to do it ... I guess I don't
really feel so angry at my father as I feel sorry for him. I just
don't think it should have happened.''
   They buried Agnes on March 3. Millie Penuel, the youngest
daughter, has said:
   ``It was probably a couple of years ago that I really
acknowledged that my mother was not my mother anymore. It felt like
she had died and we were left with this little lady who looked like
her ... So, yes, it had felt like we maybe lost her earlier, but we
were not able to have a funeral then.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 17</NOTE>
