<DOCNO> AP880705-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--ScientificJournals-PublishorPerish Adv17   07-05
0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Scientific Journals-Publish or Perish, Adv 17,0498</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>WITH BC-APN--Scientific Journals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There seems to be no end to the proliferation of
scientific journals, and most of them are widely unread. Then what
accounts for the steadily increasing volume? In part, it's the need
to be published.
   Experiments rarely turn up products to be manufactured or ideas
to be patented. A few pages printed in a journal are all that most
researchers ever have to show for months in labs and libraries.
   Getting published is essential for people in science. It is how
they keep score. Impressive lists of published articles weigh
heavily in decisions about who will be hired and promoted by
universities and industry, and they are a factor when government
agencies decide where to give money for research.
   Some people argue that an emphasis on quantity, not quality,
encourages unhealthy and deceptive practices. Although faking
results is probably rare, they contend that other abuses are more
common, such as recycling the same data to different journals,
cutting the findings of an experiment into small chunks and
publishing them piecemeal, and adding the names of co-authors who
had nothing to do with the research.
   ``As the results get smaller and smaller, the discussion and
ballyhoo get more and more grandiose, because editors and other
people have to be convinced that this is an important study,'' says
Dr. Marcia Angell, senior deputy editor of the New England Journal
of Medicine.
   This system has advantages, too, she concedes. Little of
importance gets hidden because people constantly tell the world of
their latest discoveries, no matter how trivial. But in the end,
she believes the harm outweighs the benefits.
   ``The source of it is the system of rewards within the academic
community,'' Angell says. ``The journals are parasites. They are
taking advantage of that. The engine is driven by the system of
rewarding people for large numbers of publications.''
   Some institutions have begun to cut back on the number of
journal articles they will look at when hiring and promoting
faculty members. New guidelines at Harvard Medical School suggest
specific limits, such as five papers for an assistant professor,
seven for an associate professor and 10 for a full professor.
   David Pendlebury, an editor at The Scientist, a newspaper for
the profession, agrees that the system has its weaknesses. But he
believes the volume of published studies simply reflects the huge
success of science.
   ``While there might be an increase in the number of papers, it's
hard to believe that a cartel of scientists hungry for references
in their bibliographies get together and create a journal,'' he
says. ``A journal has to exist in response to an invisible college
of researchers. It's got to make some sort of intellectual or
economic sense to survive.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 17</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
