<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1349EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv17   07-05 0837</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 17,0854</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Wopat says after seven years on ``The
Dukes of Hazzard,'' with its good ol' boy stereotypes, working on
his newest series seems like ``the Promised Land.''
   Wopat stars in the CBS summer series ``Blue Skies,'' in which he
plays an advertising executive who gives up his career in San
Franciso and returns with his new family to his hometown in Oregon.
   ``I look at the `Dukes' as something that will fade in time,''
says Wopat. ``I don't mind the notoriety. I don't disclaim it. If I
keep plugging away at what I do, people will see a well-rounded
entertainer and see that I'm not a one-trick pony.''
   ``Blue Skies,'' half-way through an eight-week run, also stars
Season Hubley as his wife, Pat Hingle as his father and Kim Hauser,
Alyson Croft and Danny Gerard as their chidren.
   ```Dukes' was a great education for me,'' says Wopat, ``but when
I started working with Carol and Nigel McKeand it was like the
Promised Land. The writing quality is so good. And after a few
weeks they began writing to my personality, which they should. The
attention to detail is so good.''
   The McKeands, who are the executive producers, also created
``Family,'' a successful ABC series in the 1970s.
   ``I had no desire to get right back into another series,'' Wopat
says. ``But this show seemed like a wonderful opportunity to get
back to the TV audience. The comment I'm getting from most people
is, `I didn't know you could act.'''
   In ``The Dukes of Hazzard,'' he and John Schneider played
cousins Luke and Bo, who never seemed to have anything better to do
than to tear around Hazzard County in the General Lee _ a souped-up
Dodge Charger _ and foil the latest scheme of the corrupt county
politician Boss Jefferson Davis Hogg and the dimwitted Sheriff
Roscoe P. Coltrane.
   After he and Schneider finished work on ``Dukes'' in 1985, Wopat
resumed his musical career that had languished during his TV days.
   ``I focused all of my energy on musical pursuits, both in
Nashville and in New York,'' says Wopat. ``I'm pretty firmly
established in Nashville now. My second album, `Don't Look Back'
from Capital Records, is coming out in July.
   ``When we finished the series I did a revival of `Carousel' in
Washington. Then I did an off-Broadway show called `Olympus on My
Mind,' which is based on a Greek legend. I played the god Jupiter.
While I was doing `Olympus' I got a call to do the `CBS Morning
News.'''
   Wopat says McKeand, who was looking for a lead for ``Blue
Skies,'' happened to see the interview while he was shaving. ``It
was pure dumb luck,'' he says. The two-hour pilot was filmed on
location in Ferndale, a picturesque little town known for its
Victorian architecture near Eureka in Northern California. After he
finished the pilot he went to Nashville to work on his new album.
Then he came back to do seven episodes.
   ``I feel the relationships in the series develop very well,'' he
says. ``That and the strength of the cast give it an awful lot of
potential. Plus, of course, the writing by the McKeands. I play
Frank Cobb, who was a widower with two children who marries a woman
with one child. There are some interesting conflicts with the
children, hers and mine.
   ``I also have some conflict with my father, Henry, played by Pat
Hingle. He's angry that I came back because he wanted me to rise
above his humble beginnings. It's a matter of communication. The
generation gap still exists. There's conflict, but also a lot of
affection.''
   In the final episode of the summer run, his wife, Annie,
discloses that she's pregnant. If the show does well enough in the
ratings (the early ones were so-so) to get a pickup for next
midseason, the arrival _ or imminent arrival _ of a baby will give
them plenty of story material.
   ``We've all extended our contracts to see how it does,'' says
Wopat. ``We're up against `ALF' on NBC and `MacGyver' on ABC. I
think at this time of year there's a good potential for growth. I
think the show gets better as it goes along and the later episodes
will reward people who stick with the show.''
   Last year Wopat was reunited with Schneider for a TV movie,
``Christmas Comes to Willow Creek.'' It was an opportunity for them
to work together again _this time outside their ``Dukes'' roles.
   ``I enjoy working with John,'' says Wopat. ``We feed well off
each other. But we're two completely different actors. I don't mind
doing more work with him. But I think both of us want to show that
we can do more than that.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
