<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Red Heat''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Odd-couple crime fighters are much in vogue this summer: the
generation-gap pairs of Sean Penn and Robert Duvall in ``Colors'';
Mark Harmon and Sean Connery in ``The Presidio.''
   Now comes the cultural-gap variety: Arnold Schwarzenegger and
James Belushi in ``Red Heat.''
   It was a nifty notion on the part of Walter Hill (``Southern
Comfort,'' ``48 HRS'') to transport the Dirty Harry of Moscow to
the mean streets of Chicago, and for most of the way, the movie
works on a purely action level. Only in the latter portions does
Hill succumb to the customary overkill of piling one violent action
on another until the viewer is numbed by crashes and shootouts.
   Hill wrote the original story and collaborated on the screenplay
with Harry Kleiner and Troy Kennedy Martin. The impact begins
immediately as Schwarzenegger strides menacingly through a steam
bath filled with hard-muscled men and women. He confronts the
leader of a drug ring, and the battle begins, with head blows that
would kill a full-grown ox.
   The Soviet scenes display a rare verisimilitude since Hill was
allowed to film establishing shots in Red Square and other Moscow
landmarks. Interiors and street scenes were done in Budapest, where
the Eastern European locales and faces also contribute to a sense
of reality. Hill wisely has the actors speak Russian, and English
subtitles explain the dialogue.
   When a vicious drug dealer (Ed O'Ross) escapes to Chicago,
Schwarzenegger insists on permission to track him down. The Soviet
cop is combined with Chicago's most undisciplined detective,
Belushi, and between arguments they pursue the dealer and his
equally brutal confederates.
   Hill is expert at staging gun battles and chases, and he
maintains the excitement most of the way. But excess does not
always succeed, as when Schwarzenegger and his quarry fight a
street duel with Greyhound buses. Such destruction of Chicago real
estate hasn't been seen since John Landis filmed ``The Blues
Brothers.''
   Schwarzenegger is perfectly cast as the stoic, single-minded
Russian, whose brutal enforcement is leavened with wry one-liners.
Since he says little, his reluctant sidekick Belushi is required to
maintain both sides of their conversations, and he is able and
amusing. Peter Boyle has some good scenes as Belushi's superior. Ed
O'Ross is a real find as the steel-eyed villain.
   ``Red Heat'' is a Tri-Star Picture produced by Hill and Gordon
Carroll. The rating is rightfully R because of language, nudity and
violence. Running time: 103 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
