<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If your child accidentally swallows a pesticide,
will you know what to do? What if a bee stings you, or while
camping with friends you stomp through a patch of poison ivy.
   Not every one knows instant first aid, but it's one of the most
important things for us to know. A new cassette from MCA Home
Video, ``Dr. Heimlich's Home First Aid,'' gives simple, useful
instructions for everything from poison to burns to bleeding,
choking, bee stings and animal bites.
   Henry Heimlich, the doctor who is credited with the procedure
used for choking victims called the Heimlich Maneuver, developed
the video with home emergencies in mind. He cautions that one
should remain calm in any life-threatening situation.
   ``There's no place for panic in an emergency,'' he says.
   The 36-minute home video will be in stores in September in VHS
and Beta with a suggested retail price of $19.95.
   Also for September from MCA is ``Swing _ The Best of the Big
Bands,'' a wonderful collection of vintage 1940s and 50s film
footage of such artists as Duke Ellington, Nat ``King'' Cole, Tommy
Dorsey, Charlie Barnet, Gene Krupa and Billie Holiday.
   The two-volume package will be available on laser videodisc with
a suggested retail price of $34.98 each.
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Moving'' and ``Stranded.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Moving'' (Warner Home Video; VHS-@Beta, $89.95; Rated R)
   
   Richard Pryor courts Murphy's Law in this crazy glimpse of
middle-class moving woes. Not only does everything go wrong, but
things you'd never dream of also get bent out of shape.
   It all begins when Arlo Pear (Pryor), a milquetoast transit
engineer, must uproot his family from Summit, N.J., and move to
Boise, Idaho, because of a job change.
   He and his wife go out to Boise and house hunt. It's a tedious
task but they finally locate the perfect home. As they admire
various appointments in the house, such as carpeting, art work,
doors, cabinets, sinks, etc., the existing owners jokingly tell
them, ``Yes, but we're taking it with us.''
   It's an ominous joke because when they arrive in Boise, they
find everything including the kitchen sink ripped from the house:
There are no doors, windows, stairs, cabinets, toilets.
   Meanwhile, the movers Pear has hired are right out of
Marat@Sade. These are guys you wouldn't entrust a bag of garbage
let alone your valuables. And the guy he hires to drive his car
West is a looney who changes costumes in every state. The car is
delivered totally stripped with four bald tires.
   But Pear gets pushed too far, and leaves wimpville for
Ramboland. With greasepaint, headband, camouflage fatigues and a
few guns, he takes on the movers, his crooked employer and an
unsavory next-door neighbor played with oozing callousness by Randy
Quaid.
   ``Moving'' reflects the episodic TV writing of Andy Breckman
(``Saturday Night Live,'' ``Late Night With David Letterman''), who
strains credibility with situations that ultimately are absurd and
not very funny.
   Directed by Alan Metter (``Back to School''), ``Moving'' is
rated R.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Stranded'' (RCA-Columbia Pictures Home Video; VHS-Beta,
$79.95; Rated PG-13)
   
   There are lots of good guys and bad guys in ``Stranded'' but
it's not too hard to tell them apart. No, they don't wear black
hats and white hats _ they just speak differently. The good guys
talk nice; the bad guys talk mean.
   Caught in the middle is a band of aliens who have fled
persecution on their home planet and seek another and better world.
They're good guys.
   So is the local sheriff, played with intense sensitivity by Joe
Morton (``Brother From Another Planet''). But not many of his
deputies are good. Nor is a government agent.
   The aliens land in the living room of an elderly woman (Maureen
O'Sullivan) and her granddaughter (Ione Skye). After initial
nonsensical mutterings about how this simply can't be happening,
they manage to communicate; a young alien lad even falls in love
with the granddaughter.
   They can't stay on Earth and are being pursued by one of their
world's tormentors. But there's a stand-off at the farmhouse.
   The end is fairly predictable but that doesn't diminish the
effectiveness of ``Stranded.'' It's light entertainment for the
entire family and is rated PG-13 for a few violent and tense
moments.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
