<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--LumpectomyGroup Adv07   07-05 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Lumpectomy Group, Adv 07,0529</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, July 7, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Women Meet for Support After Breast-Sparing Cancer Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For decades, breast cancer meant mastectomy, but
Rosanne Forziano had her cancer removed in December while keeping
her breast.
   It's easy to assume that with her tumor gone without
disfigurement, her problems were over _ but that's not the story
that emerges from Forziano and other members of an unusual support
group for ``lumpectomy'' patients.
   ``What is devastating to you is that you had cancer,'' says
Forziano, 34. ``It's gone now but will it come back, and where will
it come back?''
   Lumpectomy patients are not alone among cancer patients in
worrying about recurrance. But Forziano and other group members say
the shared surgical experience helps in discussing that issue and
others.
   Having chosen lumpectomy, ``I want to be with women who made
that kind of choice,'' says ``Sarah,'' a woman in her mid-50s who
asked that her real name not be used. ``These are the people who
know what this is about.''
   Nancy Denton, a social worker who works with lumpectomy groups
at Long Island Jewish Hospital, says many people fail to realize
that patients whose breasts have been spared still need emotional
support.
   ``They are looked at by society, by their family members, by a
lot of the medical profession as `Here they are, they have their
whole breast intact so they don't need anything.'
   ``In fact, the bottom line is that they have breast cancer. That
in itself warrants some attention.''
   Support groups specifically for lumpectomy patients are unusual.
Most are for breast cancer patients in general or even cancer
patients in general.
   The Long Island hospital plans four lumpectomy groups a year,
each running six weeks. The one that included Forziano had a dozen
members.
   Lumpectomies account for maybe 20 to 25 percent of breast cancer
surgeries and ``it's definitely on the increase,'' says Dr. David
Winchester, medical director of the cancer department of the
American College of Surgeons.
   The surgery is used on small tumors. Then the breast is
irradiated five times a week for about six weeks. Chemotherapy also
may be required.
   The radiation treatments involve the strain not only of daily
trips to the hospital, but also of seeing radiation patients who
are doing poorly, says Forziano. ``You say to yourself, `Is that
going to be me next year?'''
   The support group lets members discuss such feelings, as well as
anger at what cancer has done to their lives and the pressure to be
stoic around their families, says Denton. Meetings also include
lessons in stress management, exercise and breast self-examination.
   One payoff, says ``Sarah,'' is ``being able to encourage each
other to allow family and friends to really be there in an
emotional, supportive way.
   ``I still come out feeling most of the time that I'm lucky ...
to have had it found early, have been able to keep my breast, and
be with other women who know what that's about.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880705-0256 </DOCNO>
