<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Japan-US-Security Adv07   07-05 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Japan-US-Security, Adv 07,0502</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, July 7, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Techno-Friction Gives Rise To Security Conflict</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-EXP--Japan-US-Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takehiko Furusawa, an engineer specializing in a
technological field with potential military application, says there
is a definite change under way in Japan regarding freedom of
information.
   ``Research results here used to be completely open, but since
Eastern bloc countries have used our technology for military
purposes we've had to close off conferences and the flow of
information in a number of fields,'' said the University of Tokyo
professor.
   In the wake of last year's scandal involving exports of
sensitive technology to the Soviet Union, Japan has moved with
uncharacteristic speed to clamp down on strategic exports and cut
off access to information on sensitive technology, like the carbon
composite materials Furusawa specializes in.
   But Washington, which regards Tokyo as lax, has called on Japan
to make a bigger commitment in a strategic new agreement on
scientific and technological cooperation, concluded in June after
10 months of negotiations.
   Japan bowed to U.S. pressure and agreed to limit the publication
of U.S.-Japan technology with possible military application.
Japanese officials also agreed that they would control the flow of
informarchers spotted
the Spadefoot, or Scaphiopus bombifrons, which is common in lower
areas east of the Laramie Mountains.
   The Spadefoot is difficult to study because it can burrow as
much as 15 feet into moist soil and stay there up to six years,
said William Gern, head of the university's zoology-physiology
department. Why they re-emerge is unknown.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>First Stage of Futuristic Experiment Gets Under Way</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORACLE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company that wants to develop closed
environments that will be needed for life in space has begun
raising the insects it plans to include in a 2{-acre ``biosphere''
where eight people will live for two years.
   Space Biosphere Ventures held opening ceremonies June 27 for its
``insectary'' at Sunspace Ranch. The building will be used to raise
insects for Biosphere II, a $30 million effort scheduled to begin
in January 1990.
   The company will choose 250 species to include with eight
``biospherians,'' various animals and plants in an effort to create
a self-sustaining environment that will remain sealed until January
1992.
   Biosphere II will have 2\ acres of savannah, tropical rain
forest, desert, a 35-foot-deep ocean, marshes and thorn scrub, the
experiment presents problems in species selection, Ms. Leigh said.
The largest closed system so far is smaller than a basketball, the
company said.
   While the Biosphere is being designed to house experiments for
100 years, the first experiment will have some backup food sources
to help out if things don't go as planned, Ms. Leigh said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
