<DOCNO> AP880705-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary Adv07   07-05 1154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary, Adv 07,1187</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, July 7, and thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: This is the Explorations package for July 7 in summary form.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japan Agrees It's Time To Repay A Science Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks between Japan and the United States have
focused on balancing trade between the countries, but haven't
ignored the fact that Japan has built its technological edge on the
foundations of Western science.
   Under a pact signed last month by President Reagan and Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita, Japan will spend $4 million to invite
U.S. scientists and engineers to the country, open research
laboratories to Americans and boost the number of foreigners
invited on scholarships from 28 to 200.
   Washington has demanded more research funding and a commitment
to balance the flow of researchers and information, getting tough
as critics, particularly U.S. industry, call for an end to what
they say has been Japan's free ride.
   The Japan Center at the University of North Carolina estimates
that 15,000 Japanese students and researchers enter U.S.
institutions a year, five times the number of Americans who come to
Japan.
   Leading Japanese scientists, many of whom have studied or worked
in America, agree that the time has arrived for Japan to repay its
debt.
   ``My generation has all gone to the United States to study.
Japan just preaches about international cooperation, but it really
has to start putting out more funds ... like the U.S. government
which has spent so much over the years,'' Tokyo University
Professor Shoji Tanaka, one of the world's leading
superconductivity researchers, said in an interview.
   Hiroshi Inose, head of the National Center for Science
Information System and inventor of the digital telephone switch
when he was a researcher at the University of Pennsylvania and Bell
Telephone in the late 1950s, agrees.
   ``I have repeatedly told the government that the United States
has spent a great deal to invite Japanese scientists and engineers
on Fulbright scholarships... I don't think we ever reciprocated for
that.''
   The U.S.-Japan Agreement on Cooperation in Science and
Technology was first signed in 1980 to promote basic research in
non-energy areas. It was renewed five times since 1985 and, after
10 months of negotiations ending in June, officials agreed to a new
pact effective until 1993.
   In Tokyo, however, the feeling pervades that Japan is being
forced to comply with a pact of benefit only to Washington. ``To us
in Japan it appears we are under the pressure of the U.S.
government,'' Inose said.
   And American researchers are ``afraid of being left behind by
their colleagues back home,'' said Nagahide Onozawa, who will
oversee 100 foreign researchers under the governmental Japan
Society for the Promotion of Science.
   Tokyo University's Tanaka, head of the new International
Superconductivity Technology Center, questions U.S. intentions.
Tanaka found no takers when he tried recently to interest American
companies in the project. In addition, the U.S. government has
closed off symposiums on superconductivity to foreigners while
citing the field as one for joint research in the bilateral pact.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Experts Disagree Whether Safe or Dangerous</HEAD>
