<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against all major currencies in
light European trading early today as the market awaited the return
of New York dealers after the Fourth of July holiday weekend.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Dealers in Rome said the dollar slipped in mainly technical
dealings in Asia but that the European market was trying to bid it
higher. However, the dollar was being pressed by light but repeated
dollar sales by the West German central bank, the Bundesbank.
   Dealers said they expected the dollar to remain relatively
stable before U.S. merchandise trade figures for May are announced
in mid-July.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.55 Japanese yen to a closing 134.30
yen. Later, in London, it was unchanged at 134.30 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8217 West German marks, down from 1.8295; 1.5155
Swiss francs, down from 1.5233; 6.1355 French francs, down from
6.1593; 2.0531 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0575; 1,352.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,353.25; and 1.2160 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2215.
   In London, the British pound jumped to $1.7020 from $1.6825 late
Monday. British commercial banks on Monday announced another
half-percentage point increase in their base lending rate to 10
percent in an effort to stem sterling's five-week slide.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $437.50 a troy ounce, up
from $437.25 bid late Monday. At mid-morning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $437.40.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $437.40, down from $437.50 bid
late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose to a closing bid of $440.41
from $439.64 bid at Monday's close.
   Silver bullion edged higher in London to a bid price of $6.74 a
troy ounce from $6.73 bid late Monday.
</TEXT>
