<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0456</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines and its parent, Texas Air Corp.,
canceled a contract calling for Eastern to sell its popular
Northeast shuttle service to another Texas Air subsidiary.
   Eastern gave no explanation Friday for the cancellation. The
sale of the profitable Washington-New York-Boston shuttle routes
would have brought the financially ailing Eastern $225 million,
company officials have said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s Chevrolet, Buick and
Oldsmobile divisions extended through Sept. 28 buyer incentive
campaigns that were to expire today.
   Many of the Chevrolet rebates, announced Friday, will be leaner,
but Buick rebates will continue unchanged except for the LeSabre,
which was dropped from the program, a spokeswoman said. Chevrolet
also dropped its double rebate on the Nova and Spectrum subcompacts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polluters should be punished for allowing rampant
industrial waste to push the Soviet Union to the brink of an
ecological disaster, the head of the country's new environmental
protection committee said.
   Fyodor Morgun, chief of the committee, on Friday told a
Communist Party conference that the natural fertility of soils is
declining, forests are ``in an unsatisfactory condition,'' and the
air in all industrial centers is polluted ``above the hygienic
standards.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline stations across Poland struggled
to cope with demand when gasoline without ration coupons went on
sale legally for the first time since 1981.
   Customers at gasoline station No. 560 on Silver Street in Warsaw
waited an average of four hours Friday to pay $2.69 a gallon,
compared with the ration price of $1.58 a gallon.
   Some people feared the new regulations are a government ruse to
raise prices even further.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A severe drought in Mexico's
northwestern grainbelt is rapidly depleting wells and irrigation
dams, leaving farmers with little more to do than ``stare at the
sky.''
   Vital cropland sits idle, cattle are dying and the government is
wondering how it will pay for all the food it will have to import.
   Recent rains in other important agricultural areas prevented a
national catastrophe, although wheat yields are down about 15
percent and other crops are expected to be off due to late planting
and low soil moisture.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated Friday in a flurry of pre-holiday
selling. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 10.13 to
2,131.58, finishing the week with a net loss of 11.38 points.
   Bond prices rose on a stronger dollar. Gold rose slightly and
oil prices tumbled to the lowest level since December 1986. Corn
prices soared because of the drought.
</TEXT>
