<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     07-05 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today
as markets expanded and the yen strengthened against the dollar,
traders said.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at 27,577.17 yen, up
216.78 yen, or 0.79 percent. It opened trading at 27,360.39, and
within an hour rose to 27,427.95.
   The dollar closed the day's session at 134.30 yen, down 0.55 yen
from Monday's close.
   The U.S. currency opened at 135.24 yen, the dollar's highest
opening rate since last Nov. 10, when the dollar rose briefly to
135.75 yen.
   King Ogino, a foreign exchange trader for Goldman Sachs in
Tokyo, attributed the rise in the stock market to the yen's rise.
   ``The mood seems to be lightening, based on the yen's
strength,'' he said.
   Nick Gunner, a trader for Vickers da Costa, said the yen rose
because of comments from Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa that the
yen will not get much weaker, implying that there was a lid on how
low Japan would let the yen go.
   ``Traders see the dollar possibly getting weaker, which means
the downside for the dollar is greater,'' he said.
   He said stock prices rose because of expansion by buyers into
new sectors such as heavy electricals.
</TEXT>
