<HEAD>London Shares Slightly Higher at Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were slightly higher Tuesday amid
concern about how Wall Street would hold up after the July 4
holiday and a lack of news.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was up 4.3
points, or 0.2 percent, to 1,852.3, at midday. Volume was a light
221.8 million shares.
   ``There are bits and pieces of stories in the market, but
nothing you could hang your hat on,'' said one London trader, who
described the session as lackluster.
   Monday's concerns about the British commercial banks' half-point
increase in their base lending rate to 10 percent and the shooting
down of an Iranian passenger plane by the U.S. Navy largely have
faded, a trader said.
   But some traders said they remained worried about how the U.S.
markets would respond to Sunday's plane disaster.
   ``There will be a bit of uncertainty'' until New York returns
after the long holiday weekend, one trader said.
   However, London traders were encouraged by a strong gain in
Tokyo earlier Tuesday, he added.
   ``They (Japanese traders) seem to be shrugging off any worries
about the Middle East,'' he said.
