<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Switzerland-Fraud     07-05 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Switzerland-Fraud,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Massive Fraud Against Swiss Bank Thwarted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attempt to defraud the London branch of the
Union Bank of Switzerland of $53 million has been thwarted, police
reported.
   The City of London Police said in a brief statement Monday night
the attempted fraud involved the transfer of money from London to
the Swiss town of Nyon through a computer-based switching system.
   The police statement gave few other details but the British
domestic news agency Press Association said it understood police
were alerted after the transfer of the money triggered a
computerized alarm at the bank in Switzerland.
   However, the London newspaper the Daily Telegraph said it was
believed a failure in the computer system in Zurich stopped the
transfer being completed before it was discovered.
   The Daily Telegraph said the company fraud department of the
City of London Police was called in by the bank last Wednesday.
   Police said persons in London and Switzerland were being
questioned.
   The City of London Police is a small force which polices the
City, London's financial district. It operates separately from the
larger Metropolitan Police force, which polices the rest of London.
</TEXT>
