<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Daihatsu     07-05 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Daihatsu,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Daihatsu Considering Sale of Minicar in U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daihatsu Motor Co., which began selling a
subcompact car in the United States late last year, is considering
sales of minicars in the U.S. market, officials said Tuesday.
   Minicars, defined by the industry as cars with an engine
capacity smaller than 550 cubic centimeters, are largely aimed at
Japan's domestic market and have not been aggressively marketed
outside the country.
   Daihatsu officials said the company is considering marketing the
Leeza, a 550-cubic centimeter car, in the United States.
   However, it would be several years before the Leeza would be
available to American car buyers because the cars would require
technical modifications to handle U.S. driving conditions,
officials said.
   If successful, however, Daihatsu would become the first Japanese
carmaker in about 20 years to sell minicars in the U.S.
   Fuji Heavy Industries Ltd., the maker of Subaru cars, tried in
the late 1960s but sold only a small number of minicars.
</TEXT>
