<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Taiwan-Trade     07-05 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Taiwan-Trade,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan's Trade Surplus Grows In June From May, But Down From Year
Earlier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan's surplus with the United States increased
29 percent to $839 million in June from $652 million in May,
although it was still 48 percent below the surplus of $1.61 billion
in June 1987, the government said Tuesday.
   It was the third month in a row Taiwan has posted an increased
trade surplus with the United States after eight months of decline.
   Overall, Taiwan posted a $1.38 billion trade surplus in June,
the highest level of the year but still less than a year earlier,
the government said.
   The overall June surplus was 23.7 percent higher than the May
surplus of $1.12 billion, but 23.6 percent below the surplus of
$1.81 billion in June 1987, according to the Directorate General of
Budget, Accounting and Statistics.
   Taiwan's trade surplus for the year's first six months came to
$4.54 billion, down 50.1 percent from the same period last year.
   Exports in June totaled $5.29 billion, up 6.7 percent from a
year ago, and imports reached $3.91 billion, up 22.1 percent.
   Trade officials associated the larger overall monthly surplus
mainly with stable New Taiwan dollar that drew many orders back to
local manufacturers.
   The Taiwan dollar, after two years of appreciation in value
against the U.S. currency, has remained stable since the start of
the year.
   Another factor in the larger monthly surplus was a reduction in
Taiwan's imports of gold bullion from the United States, the
island's largest trading partner, although precise June figures
were not immediately available, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
