<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Trade     07-05 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Trade,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cabinet Approves Agricultural Import Pacts With U.S., Australia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese Cabinet gave its formal approval
Tuesday to agreements with the United States and Australia aimed at
easing curbs on imports of beef and citrus fruits from those
nations, a Foreign Ministry official said.
   The approval was given during a regular Cabinet meeting,
clearing the way for a gradual loosening of Japan's import curbs on
the agricultural items, according to the official, who demanded
anonymity.
   Japan's restrictions on beef and citrus fruits was a hotly
contested issue among the three nations, with both the United
States and Australia threatening to take their case to the General
Agreement on Trade and Tariffs, an international body based in
Geneva that sets trade rules and offers a forum for resolving
disputes.
   Japan escaped a GATT battle in mid-June by reaching separate
bilateral agreements with the two countries.
   On June 20, the Japanese government acceded to U.S. demands to
phase out quotas blocking beef imports over a three-year period
beginning 1991. Farm Minister Takashi Sato signed a similar
agreement with Australian officials in Canberra on June 24.
   Also beginning in 1991, Japan will permit unlimited imports of
U.S. oranges, but subject to the current tariff rates of 40 percent
in season and 20 percent off season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
