<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-05 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Higher, Quickly Turn Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices turned sharply
lower today after opening higher on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Traders and analysts attributed the decline to profit-taking in
the wake of the National Weather Service's latest 6-to-10-day
outlook, which predicted above-normal rainfall in key growing areas
late this week and early next week.
   Substantial weekend rains in the Southeast and extreme Northern
Plains also pressured the markets, analysts said.
   But prices appeared to be rebounding at midmorning after the
early gyrations.
   Jerry Gidel, an analyst with the G.H. Miller Division of
British-owned trading company LIT America Inc., said some private
meteorologists disagreed with the National Weather Service
prediction, and expect continued hot and dry conditions for the
drought-stricken Farm Belt.
   ``People are feeling the weather scenario hasn't changed that
drastically yet,'' Gidel said.
   In early trading, wheat was 13 cents to 18 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.84 a bushel; corn was unchanged
to 5{ cents higher with July at $3.42 a bushel; oats were 3 cents
to 15 cents lower with July at $3.20 a bushel; soybeans were 11
cents to 25 cents lower with July at $9.64 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while most pork futures were
sharply lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .50 cent higher with August at
64.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent to .80 cent higher
with August at 73.97 cents a pound; hogs were .72 cent lower to
1.18 cents higher with July at 44.55 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .72 cent to 2 cents lower with July at 33.75 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Friday while pork futures were
sharply lower.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
