<DOCNO> AP880705-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Airliner-OilPrices     07-05 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Oil Prices,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Airliner Crisis Has Only Mild Impact on Oil Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices rose only slightly today in reaction
to the U.S. destruction of an Iranian jetliner over the Persian
Gulf, and traders said they did not think the crisis marked a big
threat to supplies from that region.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, a key barometer of prices,
the August-delivery price for West Texas Intermediate crude was up
only 13 cents per 42-gallon barrel to $15.07 by late this morning.
   ``The expectations are that the Iranians aren't going to take
any action that threaten oil supplies,'' said Jayne Ball, an
energy-futures trader at the investment firm of Dean Witter
Reynolds in New York. ``If they were, the market would have been up
a dollar here. The market already has figured out that's not going
to happen.''
   Some said that because the incident happened Sunday and the
Iranians had not retaliated, U.S. oil-market strategists had more
than a day to consider the risks before domestic trading resumed,
which lessened the chances of any drastic reaction. The market was
closed Monday for the Fourth of July holiday.
   Others said the market did not react strongly to the crisis
because excessive supplies have been overwhelming demand recently,
pushing prices down to the lowest level of the year.
   A key reason is that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, which once controlled prices, has failed to enforce
production discipline among its members, which are increasingly
violating output restraints.
   ``I think the reaction here is muted because of overwhelming
concern about the fundamentals,'' said Stephen Smith, an oil
analyst at Bear Stearns Cos. in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
