<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0396</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was narrowly mixed today in
light trading amid investor apathy following the long holiday
weekend.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 1.78 at 2,133.36
by midday.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 10 to 9 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 572 up, 638 down and
516 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 73.78 million shares as of noon
on Wall Street.
   There was some initial profit-taking in the wake of higher
interest rates in the credit markets and Friday's lackluster
equities trading session. But one trader characterized activity as
``more apathetic than anything else _ the market is trying to shrug
off holiday cobwebs.''
   Traders anticipated light volume as some key decision makers
have extended their holiday weekend and since portfolio managers
have yet to pick their investments for the new quarter. ``Those
decisions aren't made in a day,'' a trader noted.
   Because the stock market was closed Monday for the Independence
Day holiday, this is the first opportunity traders had to react to
the weekend downing of an Iranian passenger plane by the U.S. Navy.
But analysts said the incident was not a key focus.
   ``The market will take it as an international incident,'' said
Larry Wachtel, first vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc.
   He noted that the oil and precious metals markets, which are
most sensitive to such global news, had no response, and therefore
``to attribute any weakness in the Dow to that (incident) would be
missing the point.''
   Traders speculated that there would have been more of a reaction
if the jetliner attack had occurred during the week.
   Mirroring activity in the previous session, utility stocks
dominated the most active issues on the Big Board, with Delmar
Power and Light up [ at 18|; Boston Edison down [ at 15[; Pacific
Telesis up \ at 29|, and Southwestern Bell down { at 38].
   Many of the utility issues were involved in short-term trading
strategies to capture their quarterly dividend payments.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.21 to 153.89. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 0.50 at 308.50.
</TEXT>
