<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-RewritableDisk     07-05 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rewritable Disk,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little-Known Company Assembles Laser Disk System For Data Storage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Getting a jump on bigger rivals, a 4-year-old
company has put together a system that allows personal computers to
use rewritable laser disks for storing huge quantities of
information.
   Rewritable laser disks are considered part of the future of the
computer business. They are close cousins of the compact disks used
for music, except they are set up for computer information and can
be erased and written on repeatedly.
   The system assembled by New York-based Advanced Graphic
Applications Inc. is the first of its kind on the U.S. market, said
Ed Rothchild, chairman of Rothchild Associates, a San
Francisco-based consulting firm.
   Advanced Graphic Applications, which buys the components from
other companies, wrote software that allows the data-storage
devices to be connected easily to personal computers using the
popular MS-DOS operating system.
   ``It's significant that they're offering a plug-and-play
solution,'' Rothchild said. But, he added, ``They will have lots of
competitors.''
   For now, the 40-employee company has a jump on companies such as
Sony Corp., Maxtor Corp. and Eastman Kodak Co.'s Verbatim unit,
which have not put together complete systems that are ready for
sale.
   Sharp Corp. announced a complete system in December, but only
for the Japanese market, Rothchild said. He said some companies may
be hanging back, waiting to see what industry standards develop.
   Rewritable laser disks are capable of storing 650 megabytes of
data, or nearly 300,000 typewritten pages of information, which is
many times more than can be held on fixed hard disks. Moreover,
unlike hard disks they can be taken out and used in other computers.
   The laser disk drives already on the market, led by
International Business Machines Corp.'s top-selling model, can
write information once but cannot erase and rewrite. IBM's model is
made for it by Matsushita Electric Industrial Co.
   The disk drive in the new Discus Rewritable system is made by
Olympus Corp. of Japan and the disks themselves are made by
Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing Co.
   Advanced Graphic Applications said it was taking orders on the
$4,995 system for November delivery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880705-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1407EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Guyana-Glance Adv10   07-05 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Guyana-Glance, Adv 10,0464</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday July 10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Guyana-at-a-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Guyana-Socialism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some facts and figures on Guyana.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ The Guianas, a region that today includes Suriname,
French Guiana, Guyana and parts of Brazil and Venezuela, was
sighted by Columbus in 1498, but Guyana was not settled until late
in the next century by the Dutch. The British became the rulers in
1796 and established British Guiana in 1831. Independence was
granted in 1966. Guyana, which means ``Land of Many Waters,''
became a Republic in 1970 and was declared a cooperative republic
``in transition from capitalism to socialism'' by the 1980
constitution.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE LAND _ Guyana is a tropical country on the northeast coast
of South America. Its 83,000-square-miles area is about the same as
Idaho. Guyana is inhabited mostly along the coast. The rest of the
country is tropical savanna and dense rain forest, rich in rivers,
ricelands, wildlife, gold, diamonds, silica sand and semi-precious
stones.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE _ The majority of Guyana's population of 780,000 is
made up of English and Creolese-speaking people. They are highly
literate _ about 94 percent. Most of the people are descendants of
African slaves or indentured servants, mostly from India and a few
from Portugal, after slavery was abolished in 1833.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE GOVERNMENT _ Guyana has a modified parliamentary system,
with legislative power in a unicameral National Assembly. The
president, who is the leader of the majority party, is the chief
executive and appoints a prime minister, who is first vice
president, and a cabinet.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   POLITICS _ Politics are based more on ethnics than ideology,
with the ruling People's National Congress supported by urban
blacks and the People's Progressive Party of Cheddi Jagan backed by
Indo-Guyanese, most of them farmers. The National Congress, first
under the late President Forbes Burnham, and for the last two years
under President Desmond Hoyte, has governed Guyana since 1964.
Opposition parties, Western governments and human rights
organizations have accused the National Congress of maintaining
power by election manipulation. National elections were held in
1985. The next elections must be held no later than December 1990,
although President Hoyte could call them earlier.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ECONOMY _ The government has launched a major drive for foreign
investment to spur the economy, which is nearly at a standstill and
dominated by a black market created by the country's nearly
depleted foreign exchange account. Economists estimate black market
transactions account for 80 percent of the country's economic life.
The country has a foreign debt exceeding $1.3 billion, 37 to 50
percent inflation, and 25 to 35 percent unemployment or
underemployment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday July 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
