<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   07-05 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Finish Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates thruout with closing prices.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices finished higher Tuesday as traders in
London were heartened by a relatively strong opening on Wall Street.
   The closely-watched Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share
index rose 6.8 points, or 0.4 percent, to 1,854.8.
   Trading volume was 383.2 million shares, compared with Monday's
370.0 million shares.
   Market watchers had predicted earlier in the day that stock
prices in New York would fall in the wake of the U.S. Navy's
shooting down of an Iranian commercial jet on Sunday over the
Persian Gulf.
   But as U.S. stock trading resumed following the three-day
Independence Day weekend, prices opened only marginally lower and
strengthened as the session wore on.
   ``As soon as the market got wind that Wall Street wouldn't open
too far down, our market actually perked up,'' said one British
stock salesman.
   Analysts said the London market was also heartened by gains
sterling made after Monday's half-point rise to 10 percent in the
British commercial banks' base lending rate.
   ``Sterling's making a triumphant comeback,'' one trader said.
``This is the start of the rebound.''
   Another analyst said equities were freed to move higher since
the market has got the base rate increase ``out of its system.''
   However, stocks of companies with dollar earnings presented a
mixed picture at the end of the trading session, dealers said.
</TEXT>
