<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Atlantic-Sun     07-05 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Atlantic-Sun,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sun Agrees to Buy Atlantic Petroleum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sun Co. Inc., a leading producer and
distributor of gasoline and petroleum products, said Tuesday it has
agreed to buy the smaller Atlantic Petroleum Corp. for $513 million.
   The acquisition is to be made, said Sun chairman Robert
McClements Jr., by purchasing all shares of Atlantic Petroleum
Maatschappij BV, a Netherlands holding company.
   The holding company is owned by John Duess, who bought the
Atlantic properties from Atlantic Richfield Co. in 1985 for $420
million.
   As part of the deal, Sun said it will pay for whatever
inventory, including crude oil and finished products, and working
capital is on hand at time of consummation.
   ``This acquisition is consistent with our objective of
strengthening the company's position in refining and marketing,''
said McClements.
   He said Sun currently owns four refineries with a processing
capacity of 460,000 barrels of crude oil daily and 6,000 Sunoco
stations in 27 states in the eastern half of the U.S.
   Atlantic has one refinery with 440 employees, in Philadelphia,
which handles 130,000 barrels of crude daily plus 571 company-owned
stations. Atlantic supplies another 400 independent stations, all
primarily in Pennsylvania, New York and New Jersey.
   Also part of the purchase are 30 oil terminals owned by Atlantic
plus its 986-mile products pipeline system from its refinery to
Pittsburgh, Pa., and Rochester and Tonawanda, N.Y.
   All will continue to be operated under the Atlantic logo, said
Robert Campbell, president of Sun Refining and Marketing Co.
   ``The acquisition fits extremely well into Sun's existing
configuration and lends additional strength to our overall refining
and marketing efforts,'' Campbell said.
   Campbell said the Atlantic name will be retained because
Atlantic is ``well-managed and efficient'' and ``the combined Sun
and Atlantic operations will allow each organization to take
advantage of the other's strengths.''
   The acquisition is subject to antitrust review by the Federal
Trade Commission and the U.S. Department of Justice.
   Sun's refineries are located in Marcus Hook, Pa., a Philadelphia
suburb; Toleo, Ohio; Tulsa, Okla., and Yabucoa, Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
