<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-05 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rainy Forecast Pressures Soybean Futures; Corn Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures closed sharply lower Tuesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade as a rainy forecast diluted drought
fears, but corn prices advanced on speculation that the moisture
would come too late to prevent significant damage to that crop.
   Wheat and oats followed the soybean market, which saw some
contracts plummet the 30-cents-a-bushel limit for daily trading.
   After a brief opening rally across the board, soybean futures
plunged as the market digested Monday's 6-to-10 day National
Weather Service forecast predicting above-normal rainfall in key
growing areas for the five-day period beginning Sunday.
   The large speculative trading firms Refco Inc. and C&D
Commodities were big sellers of both soybeans and wheat, despite
disagreement among private and government forecasters about the
6-to-10 day outlook.
   But virtually all forecasters concurred on a hot, dry scenario
in the drought-stricken Farm Belt for the rest of this week and
that was enough to support corn prices.
   The corn crop is entering its critical pollination stage in the
eastern Corn Belt and ``if these private forecasters are right, its
going to be real, real bad for corn,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was 8{ cents to 11{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.89 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
to 4 cents higher with July at $3.46 a bushel; oats were unchanged
to 15 cents lower with July at $3.22 a bushel; soybeans were 12
cents to 30 cents lower with July at $9.61 a bushel.
