<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0237</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose today in moderate,
post-holiday trading despite declines in the dollar and the credit
markets.
   The U.S. currency's fall, higher bond prices and weekend tragedy
in the Persian Gulf had convinced many traders that the stage had
been set for a selloff in the stock market.
   But while the market did open lower on some initial
profit-taking, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials moved into
plus territory around midday and continued a steady climb higher
throughout the session.
   ``Bargain hunters came in, and we saw some buy programs that
bought the market up,'' said Peter Vandenberg, a trader at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. He noted that a lack of institutional selling
helped the market rebound.
   Charles Jensen, chief technical analyst at MKI Securities Corp.,
said that stocks are ``continuing to gather a following because
people are realizing they're not going down when bonds are off.''
   With the stock market closed Monday for the Independence Day
holiday, this was the first opportunity traders had to react to the
weekend downing of an Iranian passenger plane by the U.S. Navy. But
analysts said the incident was largely overlooked.
   ``It appears that the market is suggesting that this event, as
tragic as it is, will pass,'' said Hugh Johnson, senior vice
president at First Albany Corp.
</TEXT>
