<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-05 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls; Pound Spurts; Gold Prices Steady</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower in light trading
Tuesday as the British pound jumped in response to Monday's
increase in British interest rates.
   Gold prices were little changed. Republic National Bank of New
York said gold was bid at $438 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up
from $437.25 an ounce late Friday.
   In the absence of notable economic news, currency traders were
reluctant to try pushing the dollar either sharply higher or
sharply lower.
   ``There was not a lot of conviction,'' said Phil Therkelsen, a
vice president and corporate trader at Bear, Stearns & Co.
   ``The market still likes the look of the dollar but are a little
afraid of the central banks,'' said John Lorry, a corporate trader
at Chase Manhattan Bank in London.
   The main beneficiary of the dollar's tight range was the pound,
as Britain's relatively high interest rates pulled in money,
dealers said.
   The Bank of England signaled a half-point increase in the
British commercial banks' base lending rate to 10 percent Monday,
but it took more than half a day for the rate hike to have any
impact on the currency, dealers said.
   In London, the pound rose to $1.7075 from $1.6825 late Monday.
Later in New York, the pound rose to $1.7076 from $1.6825 late
Friday.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar fell 0.55 Japanese yen to a closing 134.30 yen. Later, in
London, it was 134.20 yen. At the end of the trading day in New
York, the dollar fell to 134.33 yen from 135.40 yen late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8204 West German marks, down from 1.8295; 1.5148
Swiss francs, down from 1.5233; 1.2129 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2215; 6.1415 French francs, down from 6.1595; and 1,351.50
Italian lire, down from 1,352.50.
   There was no U.S. trading in currencies or precious metals
Monday because of the Independence Day holiday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8235 West German marks, down from 1.8295; 1.5165
Swiss francs, down from 1.5233; 6.1430 French francs, down from
6.1595; 2.0600 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0575; 1,355.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,353.25; and 1.2134 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2215.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose to a closing bid of $440.41 a troy ounce
from $439.64 bid at Monday's close.
   Gold finished in London at a late bid price of $437.25 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Monday. In Zurich, gold was also unchanged at
a bid $437.50 an ounce.
   Later, on the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for
current delivery rose to $438.10 a troy ounce from $437.20 an ounce
late Friday.
   Silver prices rose on the London market, where the metal was
trading at a late bid price of $6.74 a troy ounce, compared with
$6.73 an ounce late Monday. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery rose to $6.766 a troy ounce from $6.703 an ounce
late Friday.
</TEXT>
