<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Singer-Ryobi     07-05 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singer-Ryobi,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer To Sell Motor Products Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Co. said Tuesday it has agreed to
sell its motor products division to Ryobi Limited of Japan for
about $325 million.
   The division, located in Pickens and Anderson, S.C., is a major
source of power tools for Sears, Roebuck & Co. It also produces
floor-care equipment.
   Ryobi is a diversified manufacturer based in Tokyo with
consolidated annual sales of $1 billion.
   Ryobi and Singer said in a joint announcement of their
definitive agreement that they expect to complete the transaction
by mid-August.
   Hiroshi Urakami, president of Ryobi and Paul Bilzerian, chairman
and chief executive of Singer, said the agreement ``represents a
positive development for both parties.
   ``The motor products division's position as a leader in the U.S.
power tool industry adds a significant new business strength to
Ryobi. At the same time, Ryobi understands the industry and is
deeply committed to further enhancing the motor products division's
reputation for product quality and innovation.''
   Singer's motor products division employs about 2,600 people in
South Carolina. Their employment was not expected to be affected by
the agreement, said Tom Elliott, a Singer spokesman in Stamford.
   Singer, a Stamford-based aerospace and consumer manufacturing
company, has annual sales of $1.9 billion.
</TEXT>
