<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1737EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp Bjt   07-05 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, Bjt,0821</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Prices Plummet On Rainy Forecast; Corn Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices plunged Tuesday on the Chicago Board of
Trade as a rainy forecast diluted drought fears, but corn prices
advanced on speculation that the moisture would come too late to
prevent heavy damage to the corn crop.
   Wheat and oats futures prices followed the soybean market, which
saw some contracts plummet the 30-cents-a-bushel limit for daily
trading.
   On other markets, cattle futures were mostly higher while pork
futures were mostly lower; energy and precious-metals futures
gained; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Trading was heavy and ``extraordinarily volatile'' in the grain
and soybean markets as players digested Monday's 6-to-10 day
National Weather Service forecast predicting above-normal rainfall
in key growing areas next week, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   After a brief opening rally across the board, soybean futures
plunged and the grains generally followed.
   Analysts said a return to normal precipitation patterns even
this late in the growing season would save most of the soybean
crop. Indications that a growing number of farmers in the Southeast
and southern Great Plains plan to plant soybeans on land cleared by
the winter wheat harvest also weighed on soybean prices, said Jerry
Gidel, an analyst for G.H. Miller & Co. in Chicago.
   The large speculative trading firms Refco Inc. and C&D
Commodities were massive sellers of both soybeans and wheat,
despite disagreement among private and government forecasters about
the 6-to-10 day outlook, analysts said.
   But virtually all forecasters concurred on a hot, dry scenario
in the drought-stricken Farm Belt for the rest of this week and
that was enough to support corn futures prices as the crop entered
its critical pollination phase.
   ``This week we're staring down the barrel of pollination in the
eastern Corn Belt areas,'' Gidel said. ``The corn crop could
sustain significant damage this week if the current weather
patterns persist. And even if the rain comes next week it's not
going to help the cause very much.''
   Added Lespinasse: ``If these private forecasters are right, its
going to be real, real bad for corn.''
   Wheat settled 8{ cents to 11{ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.89 a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 4\ cents
higher with July at $3.44 a bushel; oats were unchanged to the
limit 15 cents lower with July at $3.22 a bushel; and soybeans were
12 cents to 30 cents lower with July at $9.59 a bushel.
   The drop in grain prices, combined with a demand-driven rise in
cash cattle prices, gave most cattle futures a healthy boost on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   But hog futures finished mixed and frozen pork bellies plummeted
their 2-cents-a-pound limit for the second consecutive session in a
continued bearish reaction to Thursday's monthly hogs-and-pigs
report from the Agriculture Deparment, analysts said.
   ``The report showed a lot more hogs than expected and there were
ideas we'll have to liquidate those hogs now because of the high
corn prices,'' said Thomas Morgan, president of Sterling Research
Inc. of Arlington Heights, Ill.
   Live cattle settled .53 cent lower to 1.10 cents higher with
August at 65.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .78 cent to 1.45
cents higher with August at 75.12 cents a pound; hogs were .97 cent
lower to .58 cent higher with July at 44.07 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.90 cents to 2 cents lower with July at 33.25
cents a pound.
   Oil futures rallied on the New York Mercantile Exchange but the
market registered little reaction to the downing of an Iranian
passenger jetliner by a U.S. Navy ship in the Persian Gulf,
analysts said.
   Instead, the rise in prices was primarily a technical correction
after last week's sharp declines, said Peter Cardillo, commodities
trading adviser for Josephthal & Co. in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 12 cents to 16 cents
higher with August at $15.09 a barrel; heating oil was .54 cent to
.60 cent higher with August at 41.59 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .85 cent to 1.37 cents higher with August at 49.72
cents a gallon.
   Precious metals basically followed the oil markets higher in
rather dull trading, said Richard Levine, vice president of the
precious metals and foreign exchange group for Elders Futures Inc.
in New York.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled 70 cents to $1.20
higher with August at $440.30 a troy ounce; silver was 6 cents to
6.6 cents higher with July at $6.766 a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures posted strong gains on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for September delivery of
the Standard & Poor's 500 index settled 5.75 points higher at
278.65.
</TEXT>
