<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SantaFeGold     07-05 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Santa Fe Gold,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Santa Fe Plans To Begin Mining Gold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A subsidiary of Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp.
said Tuesday it would spend about $75 million to start a gold mine
near Winnemucca, Nev., and hopes to recover an estimated 800,000
ounces of the precious metal.
   Santa Fe Pacific Mining Inc. plans to begin mining its Rabbit
Creek deposit, covering 56 square miles, in the second half of
1990. When the mine reaches full production in 1991, Santa Fe said
it is expected to mine about 100,000 ounces of gold each year.
   Robert D. Krebs, Santa Fe's chairman, president and chief
executive officer, said that even though the company has drilled
270 test holes on only a small part of the property, it believes
the mine could contain approximately 3.6 million ounces of gold.
   The first phase of the project involves further drilling,
metallurgical testing and engineering to prepare for the mine and
mill construction, the company said. That work should be done by
the end of the year, it said.
   Santa Fe said it would cost an estimated $75 million to fully
develop the open pit mine, the carbon-in-leach mill and other
facilities needed to process the oxide reserves.
   The company said in a statement that it would take ``substantial
additional investment'' to build the facilities needed to process
the sulfide reserves also at the site.
</TEXT>
