<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Iowa's governor says he might declare a statewide drought
emergency, and an Indiana official is warning of possible power
shortages as generating plants ran low on cooling water.
   Farmers in the Southeast celebrated rain and high prices Tuesday
because of the Midwest's problems, and a new heat wave spread water
restrictions and brushfires into the Northeast.
   A dispute over diversion of Lake Michigan water continued to
cause friction between Great Lakes and Mississippi Valley states as
one of the Mississippi River's shipping channels shrank to a depth
of only 7 feet.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   After a brief rally across the board, soybean futures prices
plunged on the Chicago Board of Trade as a rainy forecast diluted
drought fears.
   Meanwhile, corn prices advanced Tuesday on speculation that the
moisture would come too late to prevent heavy damage to the corn
crop.
   Wheat and oats futures prices also fell along with pork prices,
while cattle futures were mostly higher; energy and precious-metals
futures gained; and stock-index futures advanced.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropicana Products Inc. has sued
Coca-Cola Co. over labeling and advertising claims for its
``premium choice'' pasteurized Minute Maid orange juice.
   Tropicana contends the description on the side panel of the
Minute Maid container and ads depicting the juice as ``100 percent
pure Florida orange juice straight from the orange'' are false and
deceptive under an appellate ruling in a 6-year-old case.
   In the 1982 case against Tropicana, Coca Cola established that
no processor could claim pasteurized orange juice was juice ``as it
comes from the orange,'' according to Martin Gutfreund, a Tropicana
vice president.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional study has concluded the Reagan
administration should abandon its controversial proposal to trade
away potentially valuable oil rights in the Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge.
   The Interior Department wants to trade the mineral rights to
166,000 acres in the refuge for surface rights to 896,000 acres
owned by six Alaska native corporations.
   The GAO said Tuesday that Interior has valued the acreage at six
times its appraised market value, while Interior is rating the deal
as an even-up trade worth $539 million to both sides and one that
offers the nation its best hope of lessening increasing dependence
on imported oil.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration is cautioning
consumers against indiscriminate use of the prescription acne drug
Retin-A to reduce wrinkles.
   The agency also announced a crackdown Tuesday on unlicensed
manufacturers it said have started to advertise and distribute
bogus drugs identified as Retin-A.
   Retin-A, manufactured by Ortho Pharmaceutical Corp. of Raritan,
N.J., has long been approved to treat acne and normally is applied
to small areas of the skin for limited periods of time.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower in light trading. Gold prices were
little changed.
   Bond prices declined. The Treasury's closely watched 30-year
bond lost about { point, or $5 for every $1,000 in face value.
   The stock market climbed to its highest levels since the October
crash in moderate trading. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
gained 27.03 points to finish at 2,158.61.
   Soybean futures prices fell along with wheat and oat prices,
while cattle, energy and precious metals futures advanced.
</TEXT>
