<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 2025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CNWStrike     07-05 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CNW Strike,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CNW Threatens To Cut 1,200 Brakeman Jobs If No Concessions Made</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CNW Corp. threatened Tuesday to eliminate 1,200
railroad jobs and risk a strike affecting 40,000 Chicago-area
commuters unless it gets substantial union contract concessions
beyond those proposed by a presidential board aiming to avert a
strike.
   But the leader of the United Transportation Union called the
announcement a ploy and said the union had no plans to meet with
the company to discuss the job cuts, which would take effect Aug. 4.
   A three-member emergency board, appointed by order of President
Reagan under the Railway Labor Act to head off a threatened strike,
has recommended a non-binding compromise that would allow CNW's
railroad subsidiary, the Chicago & North Western Transportation
Co., to eliminate nearly 700 jobs.
   Further job reductions would be decided on a case-by-case basis,
under the recommendation made Friday.
   But Chicago-based CNW expressed disappointment Tuesday in the
panel's suggestion, saying it ``does not go far enough toward
solving the problem of archaic work rules that require the North
Western to retain obselete, unproductive brakeman jobs.
   ``If the recommendation were accepted, the North Western would
still be required to retain approximately 500 brakeman jobs which
no longer have any function and would spend approximately $25
million each year for unproductive labor costs,'' the company said
in a statement.
   CNW's plan to eliminate virtually all the brakeman jobs on its
freight trains _ cutting the crew size from four to two workers in
most cases _ would save the company $53 million a year, said
spokesman Fred Bloedorn.
   Bloedorn said technological advances of the past 100 years have
eliminated many of the brakeman's traditional duties.
   But the union contends elimination of the jobs would violate its
contract and insists that no cuts be made.
   Although the proposed job reductions apply only to CNW's freight
lines, both the union and railroad said a strike would halt
commuter service.
   CNW said it expected to meet with the union within the next few
days under the auspices of the National Mediation Board. But unless
the UTU offers concessions ``substantially beyond the emergency
board's recommendation,'' the company said it would implement its
job-reduction plan on Aug. 4, immediately after the end of a 30-day
cooling-off period.
   ``As far as I'm concerned, that's just a ploy by the carrier,''
UTU General Chairman Don Markgraf said in a telephone interview
from his office in Wauwatosa, Wis.
   He called the presidential panel's recommendation ``a
disgrace,'' and said CNW ``got everything imaginable from the
emergency board.''
   When asked whether the union planned to meet with the company,
Markgraf replied: ``Nobody's contacted me.''
   President Reagan appointed the emergency panel on April 20,
after the National Mediation Board said a union walkout could
deprive several Midwestern states of essential transportation
service.
   CNW is the eighth-largest U.S. railroad, based on revenue, and
handled nearly 1.5 million carloads of traffic in 1986. It also
provides the primary daily rail service for about 40,000
Chicago-area commuters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
