<DOCNO> AP880705-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 2320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SKorea-OverseasInvestment     07-05 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SKorea-Overseas Investment,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Individuals To Be Allowed To Buy Real Estate Overseas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea would allow individuals to
buy up to $1 million worth of overseas real estate under a
government draft plan that drastically would ease current
restrictions on such purchases, officials said Wednesday.
   Officials at the Finance Ministry said that under the draft
measures, the purchases would be subject to the Bank of Korea's
approval and would apply to houses, land and other real estate.
   The ministry officials said the measures were expected to go
into effect later this month following revisions to foreign
exchange control regulations.
   They said the new measures were intended to spur investment
abroad and trim the country's sizable current account surplus in a
bid to avoid friction with the United States and other countries
which run trade deficits with South Korea.
   South Korea's current account surplus reached $9.8 billion last
year and is projected to hit the $10 billion mark this year unless
steps are taken to hold it down.
   They said business corporations would be exempt from any
government control in purchasing up to $1 million in real estate
overseas but would need the central bank's approval for purchase of
more than $1 million.
   However, both individual and corporate investors would be banned
from buying luxurious villas in famous world resort areas, the
ministry officials said.
   Under the new measures, the scope of corporate purchase, now
limited to business-related property such as offices, warehouses,
parking lots and exhibit halls, would be expanded to include
houses, welfare facilities, forest land and other real estate, the
officials said.
   South Korea's overall direct investment overseas aggregated to
$1.03 billion at the end of 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
